{"title_page": "Passion Play of Iztapalapa", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n<!--{{coord|19|20|39.37|N|99|5|30.43|W|region:MX|display=inline,titletype:event}} -->\n[[File:La Cuevita de Iztapalapa en Semana Santa.jpg|thumb|A Good Friday Procession to the \"Cuevita\" during Holy Week in Iztapalapa]]\nThe '''''Passion Play of Iztapalapa''''' is an annual event during [[Holy Week in Mexico|Holy Week]] in the [[Iztapalapa]] borough of [[Mexico City]]. It one of the oldest and most elaborate [[passion play]]s in [[Mexico]] as well as the best known, covered by media both in Mexico and abroad. Unlike others in [[Latin America]], its origins are not in the colonial period but rather in a [[cholera]] epidemic in the 19th century, which gave rise to a procession to petition relief. Over time, the procession included a passion play which grew to include various scenes related to Holy Week. Today, the play includes not only hundreds of actors but also thousands of men called \u201cNazarenes\u201d who carry their own crosses to follow the actor chosen to play Jesus to the site where the crucifixion is reenacted. While the event is still primarily religious, it has also become a rite of identity for Iztapalapa (only residents of certain communities may participate) as well as a major tourism attraction for both the borough and the city.\n\n==Description of event==\n[[File:Nazareno_en_La_Cuevita.jpg|thumb|A \"Nazarne\" carrying cross during Holy Week in Iztapalapa]]\nIn Mexico, many communities stage processions and passion plays for [[Good Friday]], which in some places extends into other days of Holy Week.<ref name=wbooth>{{cite news |title= Passion Comes Amid Suffering |author= William Booth |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/11/AR2009041102380.html |newspaper= Washington Post Foreign Service |location=Washington DC |date=April 12, 2009  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> The Mexico City borough of Iztapalapa holds the largest and most elaborate of these, with up to 5,000 people participating and 150 of these with speaking roles.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=trexler>{{cite journal |author=Robert H. Lavenda |date=December 2004 |title= Reliving Golgotha: The Passion Play of Iztapalapa |journal=American Anthropologist |volume=106 |issue=4 |page=782 |doi=10.1525/aa.2004.106.4.782.1}}</ref> While a religious event principally, it is also a community event, as only residents of the eight original communities of the borough (San Lucas, Santa B\u00e1rbara, San Ignacio, San Pablo, San Jos\u00e9, San Pedro, La Asunci\u00f3n and San Miguel) can participate.<ref name=alista>{{cite news |title= Iztapalapa se alista para Semana Santa |author= Mar\u00eda Eugenia Mart\u00ednez |url= http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/ciudad/105677.html |newspaper=El Universal|location=Mexico City |date=April 2, 2011  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Iztapalapa enlists for Holy Week }}</ref><ref name=once>{{cite news |title=Viacrucis en Iztapalapa |author=Norma Vargas |url=http://oncetv-ipn.net/noticias/blog/ciudad/?p=273 |newspaper=Once TV |location=Mexico City |date=April 3, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Stations of the Cross in Iztapalapa |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415012253/http://oncetv-ipn.net/noticias/blog/ciudad/?p=273 |archivedate=April 15, 2012 }}</ref> The event is popular, drawing crowds of anywhere from 2.5 million to four million from Mexico and abroad during the week that scenes are performed.<ref name=alista/><ref name=once/><ref name=zedillo>{{cite web |url=http://zedillo.presidencia.gob.mx/welcome/PAGES/culture/note_semanasanta.html |title= Semana Santa   (Holy Week) |publisher=Government of Mexico |location=Mexico |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> The play is also accompanied by news media helicopters and rows of police to keep control of the crowds.<ref name=wbooth/>\n\nThe performances do not adhere strictly to the [[Bible]] as there are influences from other religious writings and even secular stories. While it is claimed that the original script for the play still exists, its performance has evolved over the years. Unique features to the Iztapalapa event include a character called the \u201cWandering Jew\u201d, a harem belonging to [[Herod Antipas|King Herod]], and a spy and dog that accompany [[Judas Iscariot]] who personally brings Jesus to [[Pontius Pilate]].<ref name=zedillo/> Costumes are elaborate. The Roman soldiers wear leather sandals, bright tunics, plumed helmets, and carry javelins and swords.<ref name=wbooth/> A number of these ride horses lent by the Mexico City police who train them to ride.<ref name=draw100s>{{cite news |title= Mexican Passion play draws hundreds of thousands: MEXICO HOLY |newspaper=EFE News Service |location=Madrid |date=April 7, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe performances begin on [[Palm Sunday]] with a procession along Calle Aztecas to the local parish church, where Mass is held. Then the recreation of Jesus\u2019s entry into Jerusalem is held.<ref name=terra>{{cite web |url= http://www.terra.com.mx/articulo.aspx?articuloid=131367 |title= Semana Santa en Iztapalapa   |publisher=Terra |location=Mexico City |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Holy Week in Iztapalapa }}</ref> On [[Holy Tuesday]], a scene depicting the miracle of the loaves and fishes is held.<ref name=once/> Crowds grow for [[Maundy Thursday]] at the Cuitlahuac Plaza, which begins with a procession that finishes with the reenactment of the [[Last Supper]], the washing of Jesus\u2019 feet, and Judas\u2019 betrayal. When Jesus is arrested, [[Huehuetl|Aztec drums]] and flutes announce the event.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=terra/> There is also a Procession of Silence which winds its way through the eight communities.<ref name=llegahoy>{{cite news |title= Llega hoy el cl\u00edmax de la Semana Santa |author=Ilich Valdez |newspaper=Reforma |location=Mexico City |page=2 |date=April 2, 2010 |language=Spanish |trans-title=The climax of Holy Week arrives today}}</ref>\n\nThe play is intense and emotional, especially on [[Good Friday]].<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=lablog>{{cite news |title= 'Jesus Christ Superstar' in Iztapalapa, Mexico |url= http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/laplaza/2009/04/its-not-hard-to-imagine-what-the-real-crucifixion-of-christ-might-have-been-like-if-you-were-anywhere-near-the-populous-w.html |newspaper= Los Angeles Times |location=Los Angeles |date=April 13, 2009  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> The scene of Jesus being tried by Pontius Pilate occurs at midday at the Cuitlahuac Plaza. He is then turned over to the [[Pharisee]]s. After this, about 10,000 take part in the procession to [[Calvary]], carrying crosses of different sizes.<ref name=draw100s/><ref name=terra/> This procession is an enactment of the [[Stations of the Cross]]. Jesus is kicked, beaten, and whipped, and cinematic blood used. When he stumbles and falls, the crowds react. Judas walks through the streets and the crowd calls out \u201ctraitor\u201d, as the actor throws fake coins from a bag.<ref name=wbooth/> At the top of the [[Cerro de la Estrella National Park|Cerro de la Estrella]], which doubles as Mount Calvary, the sound of nails being hammered comes across the loudspeakers, and the crowd becomes very quiet. The actor is really bound to the cross and remains there for about twenty minutes. As the cross with Jesus is lifted it is not unusual to see people crying.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=lrohter>{{cite news |title= A Mexican Tradition Runs on Pageantry and Faith |author= Larry Rohter |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/12/world/americas/12mexico.html?_r=0 |newspaper= New York Times |location=New York |date=April 11, 2009  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> After the crucifixion, the representation ends with Judas hanging himself alongside Jesus.<ref name=zedillo/>\n\nIn addition to the man and women chosen to play Jesus and Mary, hundreds of young men called Nazarenes follow in the procession to the Cerro de la Estrella, barefoot, with crosses of varying sizes and often with crowns of thorns. They are accompanied by \u201c''V\u00edrgenes de Pueblo''\u201d (Town Virgins) .<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=zedillo/>\n\nThe annual passion play has become an important tourist attraction for Mexico City, especially for the borough of Iztapalapa, which promotes tourism to the area during this time, offering guided tours of local museums, landmarks and green spaces. There are also specials in local hotels and restaurants.<ref name=buenrostro>{{cite news |title= Fomentan actividades turisticas y religiosas en Iztapalapa durante Semana Santa; |author=Irma Buenrostro |newspaper=Noticias Financieras |location=Miami |page=1 |date=March 26, 2004 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Tourism and religious activities are encouraged in Iztapalapa during Holy Week}}</ref> Around the staging areas, there is a carnival atmosphere with street vendors, amusement rides, and those selling religious items.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=zedillo/> Many of the scenes take place on the esplanade in front of borough hall. In 1992 the city published a book about it called ''Semana Santa en Iztapalapa'' (Holy Week in Iztapalapa).<ref name=zedillo/> In 2009 a cultural festival called the Festival Cultural Pasi\u00f3n por Iztapalapa was created to run alongside the religious event.<ref name=alista/> In the same year, two monumental [[sawdust carpet]]s were created related to the event for a photographic exhibition on the plaza in front of borough hall.<ref name=lucen>{{cite news |title= Lucen tapetes de aserr\u00edn con im\u00e1genes de Semana Santa en Iztapalapa. |author= |newspaper=NOTIMEX |location=Mexico City |page= |date=April 9, 2009 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Sawdust carpets shine with images of Holy Week in Iztapalapa}}</ref> However, in remembrance of the solemnity of the occasion, the sale of alcohol in all venues, including bars, restaurants, and nightclubs is banned for the entire week.<ref name=prohiben>{{cite news |title= Por Semana Santa, en Iztapalapa Proh\u00edben Venta del Alcohol |author= |newspaper=La Voz Hispanic|location=Pasco, Washington |page= |date=April 9, 2009 |language=Spanish |trans-title=For Holy Week, Iztapalapa prohibits Sale of Alcohol}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\n\nThe production of the event is a massive undertaking. It requires the coordination of people from the eight original communities (barrios) of the borough, which amount to thousands of people who devote months rehearsing, creating costumes and sets, decoration of churches and streets and more.<ref name=zedillo/> A number of the tasks as well as certain roles have been passed down for generations, such as providing first aid, creating the cloth Veronica uses to wipe Jesus\u2019 face and certain acting roles although this has been challenged as more people want to participate.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=lrohter/> There are 136 principal actors that rehearse for 37 days, along with another 275 actors, 500 extras and about 2,000 Nazarenes that follow the actor playing Jesus when he carried the cross to his crucifixion.<ref name=once/> In addition, there is coordination with borough and city authorities who provide logistics in terms of thousands of police for crowd control, as well as ambulances, doctors, helicopters and water stations.<ref name=llegahoy/><ref name=hcorzo>{{cite news |title= Mantiene Iztapalapa atraccion continental |author=Hugo Corzo |newspaper=Reforma |location=Mexico City |page=2 |date=April 8, 2004 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Iztapalpa maintains its attraction for Europe}}</ref> Direct costs run in the hundreds of thousands of [[Mexican peso|pesos]], with millions more in city services.<ref name=alista/><ref name=mendieta>{{cite news |title= Eligen a pr\u00f3ximo Jes\u00fas de Iztapalapa |url= http://df.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7df07da1c27c195b1924d562962108b6 |newspaper=Milenio |location=Mexico City |date=January 13, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=They chose the next Jesus of Iztapalapa }}</ref> All of this is coordinated by a committee of Iztapalapa residents, called the Comit\u00e9 Organizador de la Semana Santa en Iztapalapa. It has over fifty members and its organization is partially based on indigenous traditions.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=mendieta/>\n[[File:Operativo de Semana Santa.jpg|thumb|Police line streets for the Good Friday procession to Cerro de la Estrella]]\nAnother important role for the committee is to select the people to play the most important roles, especially the man and woman to play Jesus and Mary respectively.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=zedillo/> Tradition demands that those chosen to play these two roles may not date, drink, smoke or go to parties until they have finished their commitments, along with two newer ones, no tattoos or piercings. The candidates must also show that they have the economic means to buy the costumes.<ref name=lrohter/> The candidates are investigated to ensure the meet these requirements.<ref name=mendieta/> In addition, candidates to play Jesus, must also show that they have the physical endurance for the beatings, the carrying of a 100 kilo cross for four kilometers.<ref name=zedillo/> Once the chosen candidate passes the two rounds of the selection process, he is then required to remain celibate for the intervening year before the performance, and begin physical training six months in advance.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=draw100s/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Nazareno descansa en Iztapalapa.jpg|thumb|A \"Nazarene\" resting during the procession]]\nThe event is one of the most elaborate and oldest of its kind in Mexico.<ref name=patrimonio>{{cite news |title= Semana Santa de Iztapalapa, Patrimonio Cultural Intangible del DF |url= http://noticias.univision.com/mexico/actualidad/article/2012-04-03/semana-santa-iztapalapa-patrimonio-intangible#axzz2LMFgCBhD |newspaper=Univision |location=Miami |date=April 3, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Holy Week in Iztapalapa, Intangible Heritage of Mexico City }}</ref> However, unlike most passion plays in Latin America, this does not date from the colonial period.<ref name=lrohter/> Its origins are in a [[cholera]] epidemic in 1843, when the Iztapalapa area, outside of Mexico City proper, had a population of about 20,000, mostly indigenous. As a petition to ease the pestilence, the area began a procession to the \u201cSe\u00f1or de la Cuevita\u201d( Lord of the Small Cave), an image of Christ entering [[Jerusalem]] on a donkey which is found in a small natural cave in the community of [[Pueblo Culhuac\u00e1n]] .<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=cnnmex>{{cite news |title= Semana Santa en Iztapalapa, patrimonio intangible de la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico   |url= http://mexico.cnn.com/entretenimiento/2012/04/03/semana-santa-en-iztapalapa-patrimonio-intangible-de-la-ciudad-de-mexico |newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico |location=Mexico City |date=April 3, 2012  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Holy Week in Iztapalapa, intangible heritage of Mexico City }}</ref> When the epidemic ended it was seen as a miracle and it became a permanent annual event. Soon after, the procession included a reenactment of the crucifixion on Good Friday and over time, the passion play grew to cover almost all of the events associated with Holy Week.<ref name=once/> Although its origins are in the 19th century, there is evidence of syncretism with indigenous traditions. The procession changed from the image in the cave to Cerro de la Estrella in 1920, after a heavy rain inundated the original site. This site was that of the Pyramid of Mixcoatl, associated with the [[New Fire ceremony]]. Aztec drums and flutes appear in the event as well.<ref name=zedillo/>\n\nCatholic authorities have alternatively banned and approved the event since its inception. There is a letter dated 1867 asking [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]] for help in its preservation against hostile church authorities. During the [[Mexican Revolution]], the event was suspended due to clashes between governmental and church authorities. However a legend states that [[Emiliano Zapata]] lent his horses and ordered the renewal of the event in 1914.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=zedillo/><ref name=draw100s/> Church criticisms of the play have included that it deviates too much from the Biblical account, and it does have elements of other stories such as Dante\u2019s [[Divine Comedy]]. Examples of deviation include King Herod\u2019s [[harem]] which performs a sensual [[belly dance]]. However, the play has survived not only church prosecution but also governmental opposition to public displays of religion and Iztapalapa\u2019s demographic change from indigenous to mestizo.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=lrohter/>\n\nThe popularity of the performance began to significant increase after [[World War II]], attracting tourists first from within Mexico then from abroad. This popularity increased in the 1960s, when [[Vatican II]] legitimated passion reenactments.<ref name=trexler/> It has become the most famous passion play in Mexico.<ref name=cnnmex/> Television coverage of the event began in the 1980s, and since is regularly broadcast to the Spanish speaking world, as well as covered by media in the United States and Europe.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=hcorzo/> While it remains first and foremost a religious event, it has also become a rite of local identity and has brought attention to the poverty of the borough.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=lrohter/> A documentary about the event called Iztapalapa, memoria y tradici\u00f3n was directed by Francisco Alatriste Torres of the Escuela Nacional de Antropolog\u00eda e Historia.<ref name=msuarez>{{cite news |title= Proyectar\u00e1n documental sobre la Semana Santa en Iztapalapa |author= Mariana Su\u00e1rez |url= http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2012/05/29/capital/037n3cap |newspaper=La Jornada |location=Mexico City |date=May 29, 2012 |page=37 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Documentary Project about Holy Week in Iztapalapa }}</ref> The city government has declared the event to be an intangible cultural heritage of Mexico City, as part of an effort to gaining similar recognition from [[UNESCO]] .<ref name=patrimonio/> The increased tourism, as well as \u201ccompetition\u201d and influence from other passion plays have had an effect. The urban space where the play takes place has changed to accommodate its growth. Passion plays in the [[Philippines]] have had an influence leading to more realism in the violence, both in the flogging and the crucifixion. The actors have become younger as well as the Nazarenes, which now include some children.<ref name=trexler/>\n\nDue to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mexico]], the play was moved indoors for the first time in its 177-year history and it was broadcast on television. Fairs, commercial events, pilgrimages, and shows associated with [[Holy Week in Mexico]] were also suspended.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[La Jornada]]|title=Suspenden Viacrucis de Iztapalapa; actos a puerta cerrada y v\u00eda tv |language=es|trans-title=Way of the Cross of Iztapalapa suspended; acts behind closed doors and via tv|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/capital/2020/03/17/cancelan-viacrucis-de-iztapalapa-5742.html}}</ref> Schools were closed and vacationers were advised to stay away from beaches and other tourist attractions. The broadcasts, the first to be aired nationwide on television, were co-produced by the borough government and public stations [[Canal Catorce|Channel 14]] and [[Canal Once (Mexico)|Channel 11]], as well as the city owned [[XHCDM-TDT|Capital 21]] (with broadcasts online to viewers abroad just as it had been the case, with the added first ever international broadcasts via satellite).\n\n==References==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{div col end|2}}\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n{{Portal|Mesoamerica}}\n\n[[Category:Iztapalapa]]\n[[Category:Holy Week processions]]\n[[Category:Passion plays]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n<!--{{coord|19|20|39.37|N|99|5|30.43|W|region:MX|display=inline,titletype:event}} -->\n[[File:La Cuevita de Iztapalapa en Semana Santa.jpg|thumb|A Good Friday Procession to the \"Cuevita\" during Holy Week in Iztapalapa]]\nThe '''''Passion Play of Iztapalapa''''' is an annual event during [[Holy Week in Mexico|Holy Week]] in the [[Iztapalapa]] borough of [[Mexico City]]. It one of the oldest and most elaborate [[passion play]]s in [[Mexico]] as well as the best known, covered by media both in Mexico and abroad. Unlike others in [[Latin America]], its origins are not in the colonial period but rather in a [[cholera]] epidemic in the 19th century, which gave rise to a procession to petition relief. Over time, the procession included a passion play which grew to include various scenes related to Holy Week. Today, the play includes not only hundreds of actors but also thousands of men called \u201cNazarenes\u201d who carry their own crosses to follow the actor chosen to play Jesus to the site where the crucifixion is reenacted. While the event is still primarily religious, it has also become a rite of identity for Iztapalapa (only residents of certain communities may participate) as well as a major tourism attraction for both the borough and the city.\n\n==Description of event==\n[[File:Nazareno_en_La_Cuevita.jpg|thumb|A \"Nazarne\" carrying cross during Holy Week in Iztapalapa]]\nIn Mexico, many communities stage processions and passion plays for [[Good Friday]], which in some places extends into other days of Holy Week.<ref name=wbooth>{{cite news |title= Passion Comes Amid Suffering |author= William Booth |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/11/AR2009041102380.html |newspaper= Washington Post Foreign Service |location=Washington DC |date=April 12, 2009  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> The Mexico City borough of Iztapalapa holds the largest and most elaborate of these, with up to 5,000 people participating and 150 of these with speaking roles.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=trexler>{{cite journal |author=Robert H. Lavenda |date=December 2004 |title= Reliving Golgotha: The Passion Play of Iztapalapa |journal=American Anthropologist |volume=106 |issue=4 |page=782 |doi=10.1525/aa.2004.106.4.782.1}}</ref> While a religious event principally, it is also a community event as only residents of the eight original communities of the borough (San Lucas, Santa B\u00e1rbara, San Ignacio, San Pablo, San Jos\u00e9, San Pedro, La Asunci\u00f3n and San Miguel) can participate.<ref name=alista>{{cite news |title= Iztapalapa se alista para Semana Santa |author= Mar\u00eda Eugenia Mart\u00ednez |url= http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/ciudad/105677.html |newspaper=El Universal|location=Mexico City |date=April 2, 2011  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Iztapalapa enlists for Holy Week }}</ref><ref name=once>{{cite news |title=Viacrucis en Iztapalapa |author=Norma Vargas |url=http://oncetv-ipn.net/noticias/blog/ciudad/?p=273 |newspaper=Once TV |location=Mexico City |date=April 3, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Stations of the Cross in Iztapalapa |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415012253/http://oncetv-ipn.net/noticias/blog/ciudad/?p=273 |archivedate=April 15, 2012 }}</ref> The event is popular, drawing crowds of anywhere from 2.5 million to four million from Mexico and abroad during the week that scenes are performed.<ref name=alista/><ref name=once/><ref name=zedillo>{{cite web |url=http://zedillo.presidencia.gob.mx/welcome/PAGES/culture/note_semanasanta.html |title= Semana Santa   (Holy Week) |publisher=Government of Mexico |location=Mexico |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> The play is also accompanied by news media helicopters and rows of police to keep control of the crowds.<ref name=wbooth/>\n\nThe performances do not adhere strictly to the [[Bible]] as there are influences from other religious writings and even secular stories. While it is claimed that the original script for the play still exists, its performance has evolved over the years. Unique features to the Iztapalapa event include a character called the \u201cWandering Jew,\u201d a harem belonging to [[Herod Antipas|King Herod]] and a spy and dog that accompany [[Judas Iscariot]] who personally brings Jesus to [[Pontius Pilate]] .<ref name=zedillo/> Costumes are elaborate. The Roman soldiers wear leather sandals, bright tunics, plumed helmets and carry javelins and swords.<ref name=wbooth/> A number of these ride horses lent by the Mexico City police, who train the actors.<ref name=draw100s>{{cite news |title= Mexican Passion play draws hundreds of thousands: MEXICO HOLY |newspaper=EFE News Service |location=Madrid |date=April 7, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe performances begin on [[Palm Sunday]], with a procession along Calle Aztecas to the local parish church, where mass is held. Then the recreation of Jesus\u2019s entry into Jerusalem is held.<ref name=terra>{{cite web |url= http://www.terra.com.mx/articulo.aspx?articuloid=131367 |title= Semana Santa en Iztapalapa   |publisher=Terra |location=Mexico City |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Holy Week in Iztapalapa }}</ref> On [[Holy Tuesday]], a scene depicting the miracle of the loaves and fishes is held.<ref name=once/> Crowds grow for [[Maundy Thursday]] at the Cuitlahuac Plaza, which begins with a procession, that finishes with the reenactment of the [[Last Supper]], the washing of Jesus\u2019 feet and Judas\u2019 betrayal. When Jesus is arrested, [[Huehuetl|Aztec drums]] and flutes announce the event.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=terra/> There is also a Procession of Silence which winds its way through the eight communities.<ref name=llegahoy>{{cite news |title= Llega hoy el cl\u00edmax de la Semana Santa |author=Ilich Valdez |newspaper=Reforma |location=Mexico City |page=2 |date=April 2, 2010 |language=Spanish |trans-title=The climax of Holy Week arrives today}}</ref>\n\nThe play is intense and emotional, especially on [[Good Friday]].<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=lablog>{{cite news |title= 'Jesus Christ Superstar' in Iztapalapa, Mexico |url= http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/laplaza/2009/04/its-not-hard-to-imagine-what-the-real-crucifixion-of-christ-might-have-been-like-if-you-were-anywhere-near-the-populous-w.html |newspaper= Los Angeles Times |location=Los Angeles |date=April 13, 2009  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> The scene of Jesus being tried by Pontius Pilate occurs at midday at the Cuitlahuac Plaza. He is then turned over to the [[Pharisee]]s. After this, about 10,000 take part in the procession to [[Calvary]], carrying crosses of different sizes.<ref name=draw100s/><ref name=terra/> This procession is an enactment of the [[Stations of the Cross]]. Jesus is kicked, beaten, whipped, and with cinematic blood. When he stumbles and falls, the crowds react. In the processional, Judas walks through the streets and the crowd call out \u201ctraitor\u201d as the actor throws fake coins from a bag.<ref name=wbooth/> At the top of the [[Cerro de la Estrella National Park|Cerro de la Estrella]], which doubles as Mount Calvary, the sounds of nails being hammers come across the loudspeakers, and the crowd becomes very quiet. The actor is really bound to the cross and remains there for about twenty minutes. As the cross with Jesus is lifted it is not unusual to see people crying.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=lrohter>{{cite news |title= A Mexican Tradition Runs on Pageantry and Faith |author= Larry Rohter |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/12/world/americas/12mexico.html?_r=0 |newspaper= New York Times |location=New York |date=April 11, 2009  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 }}</ref> After the crucifixion, the representation ends with Judas hanging himself alongside Jesus.<ref name=zedillo/>\n\nIn addition to the man and women chosen to play Jesus and Mary, hundreds of young men called Nazarenes follow in the procession to the Cerro de la Estrella, barefoot, with crosses of varying sizes and often with crowns of thorns. They are accompanied by \u201cV\u00edrgenes de Pueblo\u201d (Town Virgins) .<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=zedillo/>\n\nThe annual passion play has become an important tourist attraction for Mexico City, especially the borough of Iztapalapa. The borough promotes tourism to the area during this time, offering guided tours of local museums, landmarks and green spaces. There are also specials in local hotels and restaurants.<ref name=buenrostro>{{cite news |title= Fomentan actividades turisticas y religiosas en Iztapalapa durante Semana Santa; |author=Irma Buenrostro |newspaper=Noticias Financieras |location=Miami |page=1 |date=March 26, 2004 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Tourism and religious activities are encouraged in Iztapalapa during Holy Week}}</ref> Around the staging areas, there is a carnival atmosphere with street vendors, amusement rides and vendors selling religious items.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=zedillo/> Many of the scenes take place on the esplanade in front of borough hall. In 1992, the city published a book about it called Semana Santa en Iztapalapa (Holy Week in Iztapalapa) .<ref name=zedillo/> In 2009, a cultural festival called the Festival Cultural Pasi\u00f3n por Iztapalapa was created to run alongside the religious event.<ref name=alista/> In the same year, two monumental [[sawdust carpet]]s were created related to the event for a photographic exhibition on the plaza in front of borough hall.<ref name=lucen>{{cite news |title= Lucen tapetes de aserr\u00edn con im\u00e1genes de Semana Santa en Iztapalapa. |author= |newspaper=NOTIMEX |location=Mexico City |page= |date=April 9, 2009 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Sawdust carpets shine with images of Holy Week in Iztapalapa}}</ref> However, in remembrance of the solemnity of the occasion, the sale of alcohol in all venues, including bars, restaurants and nightclubs is banned for the entire week.<ref name=prohiben>{{cite news |title= Por Semana Santa, en Iztapalapa Proh\u00edben Venta del Alcohol |author= |newspaper=La Voz Hispanic|location=Pasco, Washington |page= |date=April 9, 2009 |language=Spanish |trans-title=For Holy Week, Iztapalapa prohibits Sale of Alcohol}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\n\nThe production of the event is a massive undertaking. It requires the coordination of people from the eight original communities (barrios) of the borough, which amount to thousands of people who devote months rehearsing, creating costumes and sets, decoration of churches and streets and more.<ref name=zedillo/> A number of the tasks as well as certain roles have been passed down for generations, such as providing first aid, creating the cloth Veronica uses to wipe Jesus\u2019 face and certain acting roles although this has been challenged as more people want to participate.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=lrohter/> There are 136 principal actors that rehearse for 37 days, along with another 275 actors, 500 extras and about 2,000 Nazarenes that follow the actor playing Jesus when he carried the cross to his crucifixion.<ref name=once/> In addition, there is coordination with borough and city authorities who provide logistics in terms of thousands of police for crowd control, as well as ambulances, doctors, helicopters and water stations.<ref name=llegahoy/><ref name=hcorzo>{{cite news |title= Mantiene Iztapalapa atraccion continental |author=Hugo Corzo |newspaper=Reforma |location=Mexico City |page=2 |date=April 8, 2004 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Iztapalpa maintains its attraction for Europe}}</ref> Direct costs run in the hundreds of thousands of [[Mexican peso|pesos]], with millions more in city services.<ref name=alista/><ref name=mendieta>{{cite news |title= Eligen a pr\u00f3ximo Jes\u00fas de Iztapalapa |url= http://df.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7df07da1c27c195b1924d562962108b6 |newspaper=Milenio |location=Mexico City |date=January 13, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=They chose the next Jesus of Iztapalapa }}</ref> All of this is coordinated by a committee of Iztapalapa residents, called the Comit\u00e9 Organizador de la Semana Santa en Iztapalapa. It has over fifty members and its organization is partially based on indigenous traditions.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=mendieta/>\n[[File:Operativo de Semana Santa.jpg|thumb|Police line streets for the Good Friday procession to Cerro de la Estrella]]\nAnother important role for the committee is to select the people to play the most important roles, especially the man and woman to play Jesus and Mary respectively.<ref name=wbooth/><ref name=zedillo/> Tradition demands that those chosen to play these two roles may not date, drink, smoke or go to parties until they have finished their commitments, along with two newer ones, no tattoos or piercings. The candidates must also show that they have the economic means to buy the costumes.<ref name=lrohter/> The candidates are investigated to ensure the meet these requirements.<ref name=mendieta/> In addition, candidates to play Jesus, must also show that they have the physical endurance for the beatings, the carrying of a 100 kilo cross for four kilometers.<ref name=zedillo/> Once the chosen candidate passes the two rounds of the selection process, he is then required to remain celibate for the intervening year before the performance, and begin physical training six months in advance.<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=draw100s/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Nazareno descansa en Iztapalapa.jpg|thumb|A \"Nazarene\" resting during the procession]]\nThe event is one of the most elaborate and oldest of its kind in Mexico.<ref name=patrimonio>{{cite news |title= Semana Santa de Iztapalapa, Patrimonio Cultural Intangible del DF |url= http://noticias.univision.com/mexico/actualidad/article/2012-04-03/semana-santa-iztapalapa-patrimonio-intangible#axzz2LMFgCBhD |newspaper=Univision |location=Miami |date=April 3, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Holy Week in Iztapalapa, Intangible Heritage of Mexico City }}</ref> However, unlike most passion plays in Latin America, this does not date from the colonial period.<ref name=lrohter/> Its origins are in a [[cholera]] epidemic in 1843, when the Iztapalapa area, outside of Mexico City proper, had a population of about 20,000, mostly indigenous. As a petition to ease the pestilence, the area began a procession to the \u201cSe\u00f1or de la Cuevita\u201d( Lord of the Small Cave), an image of Christ entering [[Jerusalem]] on a donkey which is found in a small natural cave in the community of [[Pueblo Culhuac\u00e1n]] .<ref name=zedillo/><ref name=cnnmex>{{cite news |title= Semana Santa en Iztapalapa, patrimonio intangible de la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico   |url= http://mexico.cnn.com/entretenimiento/2012/04/03/semana-santa-en-iztapalapa-patrimonio-intangible-de-la-ciudad-de-mexico |newspaper=CNN M\u00e9xico |location=Mexico City |date=April 3, 2012  |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Holy Week in Iztapalapa, intangible heritage of Mexico City }}</ref> When the epidemic ended it was seen as a miracle and it became a permanent annual event. Soon after, the procession included a reenactment of the crucifixion on Good Friday and over time, the passion play grew to cover almost all of the events associated with Holy Week.<ref name=once/> Although its origins are in the 19th century, there is evidence of syncretism with indigenous traditions. The procession changed from the image in the cave to Cerro de la Estrella in 1920, after a heavy rain inundated the original site. This site was that of the Pyramid of Mixcoatl, associated with the [[New Fire ceremony]]. Aztec drums and flutes appear in the event as well.<ref name=zedillo/>\n\nCatholic authorities have alternatively banned and approved the event since its inception. There is a letter dated 1867 asking [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]] for help in its preservation against hostile church authorities. During the [[Mexican Revolution]], the event was suspended due to clashes between governmental and church authorities. However a legend states that [[Emiliano Zapata]] lent his horses and ordered the renewal of the event in 1914.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=zedillo/><ref name=draw100s/> Church criticisms of the play have included that it deviates too much from the Biblical account, and it does have elements of other stories such as Dante\u2019s [[Divine Comedy]]. Examples of deviation include King Herod\u2019s [[harem]] which performs a sensual [[belly dance]]. However, the play has survived not only church prosecution but also governmental opposition to public displays of religion and Iztapalapa\u2019s demographic change from indigenous to mestizo.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=lrohter/>\n\nThe popularity of the performance began to significant increase after [[World War II]], attracting tourists first from within Mexico then from abroad. This popularity increased in the 1960s, when [[Vatican II]] legitimated passion reenactments.<ref name=trexler/> It has become the most famous passion play in Mexico.<ref name=cnnmex/> Television coverage of the event began in the 1980s, and since is regularly broadcast to the Spanish speaking world, as well as covered by media in the United States and Europe.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=hcorzo/> While it remains first and foremost a religious event, it has also become a rite of local identity and has brought attention to the poverty of the borough.<ref name=trexler/><ref name=lrohter/> A documentary about the event called Iztapalapa, memoria y tradici\u00f3n was directed by Francisco Alatriste Torres of the Escuela Nacional de Antropolog\u00eda e Historia.<ref name=msuarez>{{cite news |title= Proyectar\u00e1n documental sobre la Semana Santa en Iztapalapa |author= Mariana Su\u00e1rez |url= http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2012/05/29/capital/037n3cap |newspaper=La Jornada |location=Mexico City |date=May 29, 2012 |page=37 |accessdate=February 21, 2013 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Documentary Project about Holy Week in Iztapalapa }}</ref> The city government has declared the event to be an intangible cultural heritage of Mexico City, as part of an effort to gaining similar recognition from [[UNESCO]] .<ref name=patrimonio/> The increased tourism, as well as \u201ccompetition\u201d and influence from other passion plays have had an effect. The urban space where the play takes place has changed to accommodate its growth. Passion plays in the [[Philippines]] have had an influence leading to more realism in the violence, both in the flogging and the crucifixion. The actors have become younger as well as the Nazarenes, which now include some children.<ref name=trexler/>\n\nDue to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mexico]], the play was moved indoors for the first time in its 177-year history and it was broadcast on television. Fairs, commercial events, pilgrimages, and shows associated with [[Holy Week in Mexico]] were also suspended.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[La Jornada]]|title=Suspenden Viacrucis de Iztapalapa; actos a puerta cerrada y v\u00eda tv |language=es|trans-title=Way of the Cross of Iztapalapa suspended; acts behind closed doors and via tv|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/capital/2020/03/17/cancelan-viacrucis-de-iztapalapa-5742.html}}</ref> Schools were closed and vacationers were advised to stay away from beaches and other tourist attractions. The broadcasts, the first to be aired nationwide on television, were co-produced by the borough government and public stations [[Canal Catorce|Channel 14]] and [[Canal Once (Mexico)|Channel 11]], as well as the city owned [[XHCDM-TDT|Capital 21]] (with broadcasts online to viewers abroad just as it had been the case, with the added first ever international broadcasts via satellite).\n\n==References==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{div col end|2}}\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n{{Portal|Mesoamerica}}\n\n[[Category:Iztapalapa]]\n[[Category:Holy Week processions]]\n[[Category:Passion plays]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription of event:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passion_Play_of_Iztapalapa"}
{"title_page": "Youth Resistance", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Youth Resistance\n| native_name = Jugendwiderstand\n| logo = \n| colorcode = {{Socialist Party (Netherlands)/meta/color}}\n| abbreviation = JW\n| leader1_title = \n| leader1_name = \n| leader2_title = \n| leader2_name = \n| leader3_title = \n| leader3_name = \n| leader4_title = \n| leader4_name = \n| leader5_title = \n| leader5_name = \n| founder = \n| founded = 1 May 2015\n| dissolved = 9 June 2019\n| split = \n| headquarters = Berlin\n| newspaper = \n| student_wing = \n| youth_wing = \n| ideology = [[Communism]] <br> [[Marxism-Leninism-Maoism]]\n| position = [[Far-left politics|Far-left]]\n| colours = [[Red]]\n<br> [[Yellow]]\n| website = [http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com// Youth Resistance]\n| country = Germany\n}}\n\n'''Youth Resistance''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Jugendwiderstand,'' abbreviated '''JW''') was a [[Maoism|Maoist]] youth group in [[Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/p/kurzbeschreibung.html|title=Kurzvorstellung & Kontakt|last=|first=|date=|website=Jugendwiderstand - Rebellion ist gerechtfertigt!|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== History & overview ==\nThe JW was founded from a split in the [[Berlin]] branch of the [[Magdeburg]]-based group [[Fighting Together]] (''Zusammen K\u00e4mpfen).'' The split was caused by an ideological conflict between more [[Libertarian Marxism|libertarian Marxist]]-oriented members and the more orthodox [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jungewelt.de/artikel/351691.berlins-jugendwiderstand-rappende-revolution\u00e4re.html|title=Rappende Revolution\u00e4re|date=2019-03-27|website=junge Welt|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>  Currently JW is primarily based in [[Berlin]], but also lists branches in [[B\u00fcckeburg]], [[Dresden]], [[Flensburg]], [[Hamburg]], [[Magdeburg]] and [[M\u00fcnster]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/|title=Jugendwiderstand - Rebellion ist gerechtfertigt!|website=jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe ideology of JW is based upon the theory of [[Marxism-Leninism-Maoism]] (MLM). MLM is the universal application of the [[Mao-Zedong-Thought]], with the principal theorist being the [[Peru]]vian [[Abimael Guzm\u00e1n]], chairman of the [[Communist Party of Peru (Shining Path)]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/958459002|title=Continuity and rupture : philosophy in the Maoist terrain|last=Moufawad-Paul, J. (Joshua), 1978-|isbn=9781785354762|location=Winchester, UK|oclc=958459002}}</ref>\n\nThey were noted for their repeated usage of [[Nationalism|nationalist]] and [[v\u00f6lkisch]] themes. Some members of the group are former [[National Democratic Party of Germany|NPD]] members.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/gewalttaetige-politsekte-jugendwiderstand-maos-schlaeger-aus-berlin-neukoelln/23729980.html|title=Maos Schl\u00e4ger aus Berlin-Neuk\u00f6lln|website=www.tagesspiegel.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\nJW is henceforth fiercely supportive of the revolutionary struggles of the [[Communist Party of the Philippines]] and the [[Naxalite\u2013Maoist insurgency|Naxalites]] in [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2016/10/berlin-lal-salaam-den-martyrern-von.html|title=Berlin: Lal Salaam den M\u00e4rtyrern von Malkangiri|last=|first=|date=2016-10-30|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=UNTERST\u00dcTZ DIE REVOLUTION AUF DEN PHILIPPINEN. SIEG DEM VOLKSKRIEG!|url=https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-bESPWVWWIhg/WpcKxgUJsII/AAAAAAAACJ0/94tvzERtpYMCqJLWHoPuxi-FsUJiSqLZACLcBGAs/s1600/plakat.jpg|journal=Plakat der Jugendwiderstand|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Other activities of JW are among others participation in the yearly [[International Workers' Day|May Day]] and [[Rosa Luxemburg|Luxemburg]]-[[Karl Liebknecht|Liebknecht]] (LL) demonstrations,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2019/01/bericht-das-lenin-liebknecht-luxemburg.html|title=Bericht & Fotos: Das Lenin-Liebknecht-Luxemburg-Wochenende 2019 in Berlin|last=|first=|date=2019-01-24|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> campaigning for [[election boycott]]s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2016/08/berlin-geht-nicht-wahlen-keine-stimme.html|title=Berlin: Geht nicht w\u00e4hlen - Keine Stimme dem Ausbeutersystem!|last=|first=|date=2016-08-25|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> and [[Anti-fascism|anti-fascist]] organizing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redspark.nu/en/imperialist-states/a-red-block-against-the-fascists-of-die-rechte-party-in-hamm/|title=A Red Block against the fascists of Die Rechte Party in Hamm !|last=Kistler|first=C.|date=4 October 2016|website=Redspark|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2019 JW announced on social media that it had dissolved. The main reason given by the organisation was that it could not make the transition between being a [[avant-garde]] youth organisation and an actual [[Mass line|mass]] [[Cadre (politics)|cadre]] [[communist party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2019/06/das-ende-des-jugendwiderstand.html|title=Das Ende des Jugendwiderstand|last=|first=|date=2019-06-09|website=Jugendwiderstand - Rebellion ist gerechtfertigt!|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of the 26 June 2019 the police raided seven houses of nine JW members in [[Berlin]] and [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]. The police confiscated weapons, hard drives, mobile phones and disguises. The announced dissolution of JW is suspected of being a deception to complicate the investigations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/maos-schlaeger-aus-neukoelln-razzia-bei-sieben-jugendwiderstand-mitgliedern/24495352.html|title=Razzia bei sieben \u201eJugendwiderstand\u201c-Mitgliedern|website=www.tagesspiegel.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. \n\n== Criticisms ==\nJW has been criticised of being [[Homophobia|homophobic]], [[Nationalism|nationalistic]], [[Antisemitism|anti-semitic]], [[Sectarianism|sectarian]], and violent towards other leftwing groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/gewalttaetige-politsekte-jugendwiderstand-maos-schlaeger-aus-berlin-neukoelln/23729980.html|title=Maos Schl\u00e4ger aus Berlin-Neuk\u00f6lln|website=www.tagesspiegel.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morgenpost.de/1-mai-berlin/article214141183/Linksextreme-Antisemiten-ziehen-am-1-Mai-durch-Neukoelln.html|title=Israel-Hasser demonstrieren am 1. Mai in Neuk\u00f6lln|last=Betschka|first=Julius|date=2018-04-27|website=www.morgenpost.de|language=de-DE|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> The group is under surveillance of the ''Verfassungsschutz Berlin'' for being a radical left-wing anti-semitic organization.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.berlin.de/sen/inneres/verfassungsschutz/publikationen/verfassungsschutzberichte/jahresbericht-2017-webfassung.pdf|title=Verfassungsschutz Berlin 2017|last=|first=|publisher=Berliner Verfassungsschutz|year=2018|isbn=|location=Berlin|pages=191\u2013195}}</ref> JW refutes these criticisms as being either untrue, or as being part of their political [[Praxis (process)|praxis]] (in the case of their violent disposition towards other leftwing groups).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2018/03/zu-der-hetze-gegen-unsere-genossen-in.html|title=Zu der Hetze gegen unsere Genossen in Flensburg|last=|first=|date=2018-03-20|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>. JW was noted for their repeated usage of [[Nationalism|nationalist]] and [[v\u00f6lkisch]] themes.  Also some members of the group were former [[National Democratic Party of Germany|NPD]] members.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Communist Party of Germany/Marxists\u2013Leninists]]\n* [[Marxist\u2013Leninist Party of Germany]]\n* [[Marxism\u2013Leninism\u2013Maoism]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-revisionist organizations]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in Germany]]\n[[Category:Maoist organizations in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Youth Resistance\n| native_name = Jugendwiderstand\n| logo = \n| colorcode = {{Socialist Party (Netherlands)/meta/color}}\n| abbreviation = JW\n| leader1_title = \n| leader1_name = \n| leader2_title = \n| leader2_name = \n| leader3_title = \n| leader3_name = \n| leader4_title = \n| leader4_name = \n| leader5_title = \n| leader5_name = \n| founder = \n| founded = 1 May 2015\n| dissolved = 9 June 2019\n| split = \n| headquarters = Berlin\n| newspaper = \n| student_wing = \n| youth_wing = \n| ideology = [[Communism]] <br> [[Marxism-Leninism-Maoism]]\n| position = [[Far-left politics|Far-left]]\n| colours = [[Red]]\n<br> [[Yellow]]\n| website = [http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com// Youth Resistance]\n| country = Germany\n}}\n\n'''Youth Resistance''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Jugendwiderstand,'' abbreviated '''JW''') was a [[Maoism|Maoist]] youth group in [[Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/p/kurzbeschreibung.html|title=Kurzvorstellung & Kontakt|last=|first=|date=|website=Jugendwiderstand - Rebellion ist gerechtfertigt!|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== History & overview ==\nThe JW was founded from a split in the [[Berlin]] branch of the [[Magdeburg]]-based group [[Fighting Together]] (''Zusammen K\u00e4mpfen).'' The split was caused by an ideological conflict between more [[Libertarian Marxism|libertarian Marxist]]-oriented members and the more orthodox [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jungewelt.de/artikel/351691.berlins-jugendwiderstand-rappende-revolution\u00e4re.html|title=Rappende Revolution\u00e4re|date=2019-03-27|website=junge Welt|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>  Currently JW is primarily based in [[Berlin]], but also lists branches in [[B\u00fcckeburg]], [[Dresden]], [[Flensburg]], [[Hamburg]], [[Magdeburg]] and [[M\u00fcnster]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/|title=Jugendwiderstand - Rebellion ist gerechtfertigt!|website=jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe ideology of JW is based upon the theory of [[Marxism-Leninism-Maoism]] (MLM). MLM is the universal application of the [[Mao-Zedong-Thought]], with the principal theorist being the [[Peru]]vian [[Abimael Guzm\u00e1n]], chairman of the [[Communist Party of Peru (Shining Path)]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/958459002|title=Continuity and rupture : philosophy in the Maoist terrain|last=Moufawad-Paul, J. (Joshua), 1978-|isbn=9781785354762|location=Winchester, UK|oclc=958459002}}</ref>\n\nJW is henceforth fiercely supportive of the revolutionary struggles of the [[Communist Party of the Philippines]] and the [[Naxalite\u2013Maoist insurgency|Naxalites]] in [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2016/10/berlin-lal-salaam-den-martyrern-von.html|title=Berlin: Lal Salaam den M\u00e4rtyrern von Malkangiri|last=|first=|date=2016-10-30|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=UNTERST\u00dcTZ DIE REVOLUTION AUF DEN PHILIPPINEN. SIEG DEM VOLKSKRIEG!|url=https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-bESPWVWWIhg/WpcKxgUJsII/AAAAAAAACJ0/94tvzERtpYMCqJLWHoPuxi-FsUJiSqLZACLcBGAs/s1600/plakat.jpg|journal=Plakat der Jugendwiderstand|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Other activities of JW are among others participation in the yearly [[International Workers' Day|May Day]] and [[Rosa Luxemburg|Luxemburg]]-[[Karl Liebknecht|Liebknecht]] (LL) demonstrations,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2019/01/bericht-das-lenin-liebknecht-luxemburg.html|title=Bericht & Fotos: Das Lenin-Liebknecht-Luxemburg-Wochenende 2019 in Berlin|last=|first=|date=2019-01-24|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> campaigning for [[election boycott]]s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2016/08/berlin-geht-nicht-wahlen-keine-stimme.html|title=Berlin: Geht nicht w\u00e4hlen - Keine Stimme dem Ausbeutersystem!|last=|first=|date=2016-08-25|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> and [[Anti-fascism|anti-fascist]] organizing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redspark.nu/en/imperialist-states/a-red-block-against-the-fascists-of-die-rechte-party-in-hamm/|title=A Red Block against the fascists of Die Rechte Party in Hamm !|last=Kistler|first=C.|date=4 October 2016|website=Redspark|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2019 JW announced on social media that it had dissolved. The main reason given by the organisation was that it could not make the transition between being a [[avant-garde]] youth organisation and an actual [[Mass line|mass]] [[Cadre (politics)|cadre]] [[communist party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2019/06/das-ende-des-jugendwiderstand.html|title=Das Ende des Jugendwiderstand|last=|first=|date=2019-06-09|website=Jugendwiderstand - Rebellion ist gerechtfertigt!|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\nThe group strived for a [[civil war]] in Germany to overthrow the system. They were noted for their repeated usage of nationalist and [[v\u00f6lkisch]] themes. Some members of the group are former [[National Democratic Party of Germany|NPD]] members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/gewalttaetige-politsekte-jugendwiderstand-maos-schlaeger-aus-berlin-neukoelln/23729980.html|title=Maos Schl\u00e4ger aus Berlin-Neuk\u00f6lln|website=www.tagesspiegel.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\nJW has been criticised of being [[Homophobia|homophobic]], [[Nationalism|nationalistic]], [[Antisemitism|anti-semitic]], [[Sectarianism|sectarian]], and violent towards other leftwing groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/gewalttaetige-politsekte-jugendwiderstand-maos-schlaeger-aus-berlin-neukoelln/23729980.html|title=Maos Schl\u00e4ger aus Berlin-Neuk\u00f6lln|website=www.tagesspiegel.de|language=de|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morgenpost.de/1-mai-berlin/article214141183/Linksextreme-Antisemiten-ziehen-am-1-Mai-durch-Neukoelln.html|title=Israel-Hasser demonstrieren am 1. Mai in Neuk\u00f6lln|last=Betschka|first=Julius|date=2018-04-27|website=www.morgenpost.de|language=de-DE|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> The group is under surveillance of the ''Verfassungsschutz Berlin'' for being a radical left-wing anti-semitic organization.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.berlin.de/sen/inneres/verfassungsschutz/publikationen/verfassungsschutzberichte/jahresbericht-2017-webfassung.pdf|title=Verfassungsschutz Berlin 2017|last=|first=|publisher=Berliner Verfassungsschutz|year=2018|isbn=|location=Berlin|pages=191\u2013195}}</ref> JW refutes these criticisms as being either untrue, or as being part of their political [[Praxis (process)|praxis]] (in the case of their violent disposition towards other leftwing groups).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/2018/03/zu-der-hetze-gegen-unsere-genossen-in.html|title=Zu der Hetze gegen unsere Genossen in Flensburg|last=|first=|date=2018-03-20|website=Jugendwiderstand|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Communist Party of Germany/Marxists\u2013Leninists]]\n* [[Marxist\u2013Leninist Party of Germany]]\n* [[Marxism\u2013Leninism\u2013Maoism]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|url=http://jugendwiderstand.blogspot.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-revisionist organizations]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in Germany]]\n[[Category:Maoist organizations in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Vjr300", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Youth_Resistance"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Europe}}\n{{About|the pandemic in the continent|the pandemic in the political and economic union|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the European Union}}\n{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]] amending from PC1 due to activity level |small=yes}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 COVID-19 pandemic in Europe\n| image           = Persons died due to coronavirus COVID-19 per capita in Europe.svg\n| caption         = Cumulative number of deaths per million inhabitants from COVID-19 in Europe.<ref name=\"coronacount\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus update (live) |date=20 March 2020 |website=www.worldometers.info |url-status=live |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322140128/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |archive-date=22 March 2020 }}</ref><!-- Date and legend inside image -->\n| map2            = Red COVID-19 Outbreak Cases per capita in Europe.svg\n| legend2         = Confirmed cases of SARS-CoV-2 infected people in relation to the population of the country (cases per million inhabitants).<ref name=\"coronacount\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus update (live) |date=20 March 2020 |website=www.worldometers.info |url-status=live |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322140128/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |archive-date=22 March 2020 }}</ref> The numbers are not comparable, as the testing strategy differs between countries and time periods. |link=Special:FilePath/Coronavirus_infected_persons_per_capita_in_Europe.svg \n| map3            = COVID-19 death per infected in Europe.svg\n| legend3         = Number of deaths per 100 confirmed COVID-19 infected inhabitants in Europe.<ref name=\"coronacount\" /><!-- Date and legend inside image -->\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Europe\n| first_case      = [[Bordeaux]], France\n| arrival_date    = 21 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=21|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China<ref name=\"20200130cdc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/summary.html |title=2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) Situation Summary |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126210549/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-nCoV/summary.html |archive-date=26 January 2020 |access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases  =   210,127<ref name=\"coronacount\" />\n| deaths          =   73,625<ref name=\"coronacount\" />\n| confirmed_cases =   852,899<ref name=\"coronacount\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories     = 57<ref name=\"coronacount\" />\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=locations}}\n\n{{As of|2020|03|13|post=,}} the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) considered Europe the active centre of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|<noinclude>2019\u201320 coronavirus </noinclude>pandemic]]. Cases by country across Europe had doubled over periods of typically 3 to 4 days, with some countries (mostly those at earlier stages of detection) showing doubling every 2 days.<ref>[https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus Max Roser, Hannah Ritchie and Esteban Ortiz-Ospina (2020) \u2013 \"Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) \u2013 Research and Statistics\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319171947/https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus |date=19 March 2020}} 13 March 2020, ''ourworldindata.org/coronavirus'', accessed 14 March 2020</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|03|17|alt=As of 17 March|post=,}} all countries within Europe had a confirmed case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], with [[Montenegro]] being the last European country to report at least one case.<ref>[https://twitter.com/MeGovernment/status/1239992049350447104 Two COVID-19 cases confirmed in Montenegro] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317191704/https://twitter.com/MeGovernment/status/1239992049350447104 |date=17 March 2020}} ''twitter.com/MeGovernment'' accessed 17 March 2020</ref> In 18 countries, at least one death has been reported.\n\n{{As of|2020|03|18|alt=As of 18 March|post=,}} more than 250&nbsp;million people are in lockdown in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |last=Henley |first=Jon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-lockdown-eu-belgium-germany-adopt-measures |title=More than 250m in lockdown in EU as Belgium and Germany adopt measures |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |issn=0261-3077 |access-date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401085742/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-lockdown-eu-belgium-germany-adopt-measures |archive-date=1 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Risk assessment for the pandemic in the EU/EEA and UK ==\nAs of 17 March 2020, there had been 2,740 reported deaths in the EU/EEA and UK from COVID-19<ref name=ECDC>{{cite web |url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/cases-2019-ncov-eueea |title=Situation update for the EU/EEA and the UK |date=13 March 2020 |website=www.ecdc.europa.eu |access-date=15 March 2020 <!--08:00--> |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304105320/https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/cases-2019-ncov-eueea |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> (25 March number: 10,049).\n\nOn 13 March 2020, the following COVID-19 related risks were assessed by the ECDC:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/current-risk-assessment-novel-coronavirus-situation |title=Daily risk assessment on COVID-19, 13 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020 |website=www.ecdc.europa.eu |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305021409/https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/current-risk-assessment-novel-coronavirus-situation |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Risk\n! Level\n|-\n| risk of severe disease associated with COVID-19 infection for people in the EU/EEA and UK: general population\n| moderate  \n|-\n| risk of severe disease associated with COVID-19 infection for people in the EU/EEA and UK: older adults and individuals with chronic underlying conditions\n| high\n|-\n| risk of milder disease, and the consequent impact on social and work-related activity,\n| high\n|-\n| risk of the occurrence of sub-national community transmission of COVID-19 in the EU/EEA and the UK\n| very high\n|-\n| risk of occurrence of widespread national community transmission of COVID-19 in the EU/EEA and the UK in the coming weeks \n| high\n|-\n| risk of healthcare system capacity being exceeded in the EU/EEA and the UK in the coming weeks\n| high\n|-\n|risk associated with transmission of COVID-19 in health and social institutions with large vulnerable populations \n| high\n|}\n\n== Statistics by country and territory ==\n{{Main|Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data}} \n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Europe medical cases chart}}\n\n[[File:COVID-19-Europe-selection-relative-deaths-log.svg|thumb|600px|Cumulative number of deaths per million inhabitants for a selection of European countries, over time. The legend is sorted in descending order of these values. Logarithmic vertical axis. Data source: [[ECDC]].<ref name=ECDC/>]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+Summary table of confirmed cases in Europe (as of 13 April 2020)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bnonews.com/index.php/