q/retroactive|title=Retroactive|last=Bailey|first=Keith|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=2015-11-23}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Road (2011 film)|The Road]]'' || 2011 || A group of teens finally work up the fortitude to explore a rural road, that has all the warning signs of being a bad idea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/11/movies/the-road-by-the-philippine-director-yam-laranas|title=Crawling Backwards In Time Into Haunted Real Estate|last=Catsoulis|first=Jeannette|work=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=2015-11-23}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Run Lola Run]]'' || 1998 || A woman needs to obtain 100,000 Deutsche Mark in twenty minutes to save her boyfriend's life\u2014and gets three tries to do so.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Buckland|first1=Warren|title=Puzzle Films: Complex Storytelling in contemporary cinema|date=2009|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|location=Chichester, West Sussex, U.K.|isbn=9781444305715|pages=129\u2013150|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uV_uY-iliwgC&pg=PA131&lpg=PA131&dq=%22Run%2BLola%2BRun%22%2B%22time%2Bloop%22&source=bl|accessdate=4 September 2016|language=en}}</ref> Not featuring time loops in the strict sense the German action film illustrates the [[butterfly effect]] / [[chaos theory]].\n|-\n| ''[[Salvage (2006 film)|Salvage]]'' || 2006 || Claire encounters horror and murder after finishing a day working at a convenience store, not once but many times. An official selection of the 2006 [[Sundance Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chang|first1=Justin|title=Review: \u2018Salvage\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/reviews/salvage-2-1200518868/|website=Variety|accessdate=6 May 2014|date=31 January 2006}}</ref>  \n|-\n| ''[[Source Code]]'' || 2011 || U.S. Army Aviation pilot Captain Colter Stevens repeatedly experiences the last eight minutes of another person's life to identify the bomber in a terrorist attack in order to prevent a second, nuclear attack on Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lawler|first1=Kelley|title=It's still 'Groundhog Day': The 4 best time-loop movies|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2014/06/06/edge-of-tomorrow-groundhog-day-best-time-loop-movies/77279562/|website=USA Today|accessdate=26 September 2017|date=6 June 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Timecrimes]]'' || 2007 || Hector, a middle-aged man, is chased by an unidentified bandaged man. He meets a scientist with a time machine, and travels a short period back in time to briefly escape the unknown assailant.<ref>{{cite web|last1=King|first1=Kris|title=Best of: Time Loops (Time Loops [Time Loops])|url=https://nitehawkcinema.com/williamsburg/2014/01/30/best-of-time-loops-time-loops-time-loops/|website=[[Nitehawk Cinema]]|accessdate=26 September 2017|date=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Triangle (2009 British film)|Triangle]]'' || 2009 || A group of friends go on boat trip and become stranded due to a storm. They discover a cruise ship which causes them to experience a series of repeating events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/triangle-2/review/|title=Triangle Review|last=Li|first=Shirley|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=2009-10-01|accessdate=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Urusei Yatsura 2: Beautiful Dreamer]]'' || 1984 || The students of Tomobiki high school relive the day before the school festival over and over again.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hartl|first1=John|title=Disney Will Distribute Animated Japanese Movie|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980903&slug=2769906|accessdate=May 15, 2017|work=The Seattle Times|date=September 3, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=French|first1=Todd|title=Reviews|journal=Cinefantastique|date=July 1996|volume=27|issue=11/12|page=123|accessdate=April 28, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?lr=&id=6vQHAQAAMAAJ|quote=The student body of Tomobiki High experiences a major cause of deja vu when they find themselves endlessly repeating \"the day before the School Festival.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Oshii says dissatisfaction behind 'eternal youth'|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|date=August 1, 2008|page=18|quote=The sequel, 1984's Urusei Yatsura 2: Beautiful Dreamer, meanwhile, included a gut-wrenching philosophical aspect into the storyline. In the movie, the characters relive the night before a school festival over and over, eventually blurring the line between reality and fantasy. The concept and execution took that film beyond mere anime geared toward kids.}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[When We First Met]]'' || 2018 || Noah Ashby find out that a local Photo Booth can transport him back in time 3 years and tries to make the love of his life fall in love with him.<ref>{{cite web|title=When We First Met (2018)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5783956/|website=IMDB|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n* [[List of time travel works of fiction]]\n* [[Time travel]]\n* [[Time travel in fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Alternate timeline films]]\n[[Category:Lists of films by common content]]\n[[Category:Time loop films| ]]\n[[Category:Films about time travel]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis '''list of films featuring [[time loop]]s''' where characters experience the same period of time which is repeatedly resetting: when a certain condition is met, such as a death of a character or a clock reaches a certain time, the loop starts again, with one or more characters retaining the memories from the previous loop.<ref name=\"TTIPM\">{{cite|title=Time Travel in Popular Media|author1=Matthew Jones|author2=Joan Ormrod|year=2015|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=9780786478071}}</ref>{{rp|207}} The list provides the names and brief synopses of films in which time loops are a prominent plot device.\n\n==List==\n<!-- PLEASE ADD A FILM AND ITS CITATION IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Film \n! scope=\"col\" | Year \n! scope=\"col\" class=\"sortable\" style=white-space:nowrap | Description\n|-\n| ''[[12 Dates of Christmas]]'' || 2011 || Kate finds herself reliving [[Christmas Eve]] (including a blind date with a man named Miles) over and over again. She must discover how to break the cycle \u2013 should she attempt to win back her ex-boyfriend Jack, should she pursue Miles, or something else?<ref>{{cite web|last1=Griffiths|first1=John|title=12 Dates of Christmas|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/review--12-dates-of-christmas-2011612|website=[[US Weekly]]|accessdate=7 May 2014|date=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''12 Days of Christmas Eve'' || 2004 || Calvin is an executive and as Christmas nears he becomes so preoccupied in clinching a deal that he fails to notice the preparations being made for the holidays by his girlfriend and son. On Christmas Eve itself Calvin is hurt in an accident and it takes nurse Angie to make him realize how he can make up for lost time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Geno|title=The Twelve Days of Christmas Eve|url=https://www.scaredstiffreviews.com/the-twelve-days-of-christmas-eve-2004-%E2%80%93-xmas-movie-review|website=[[Scared Stiff Reviews]]|accessdate=21 Jan 2019|date=2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[12:01 (1993 film)|12:01]]'' || 1993 || Office worker Barry Thomas is forced to relive the worst day of his life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.tvguide.com/movie-news/Ask-FlickChick-Its-7932.aspx|title=It's like Groundhog Day, but different. What is it?|work=TV Guide|accessdate=2014-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328023603/http://movies.tvguide.com/movie-news/ask-flickchick-its-7932.aspx|archive-date=2014-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[12:01 PM (1990 film)|12:01 PM]]''  || 1990 || This is the first film adaptation of the short story \"[[12:01 PM]]\" by [[Richard A. Lupoff]], which was published in 1973 in ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy and Science Fiction]]''. It originally aired on [[cable television]] as part of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] ''30-Minute Movie'' anthology series. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1229994805425 |title=1990 (63rd): Short Film (Live Action) |work=Academy Awards Database |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402164428/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1229994805425 |archivedate=2015-04-02 }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[About Time (2013 film)|About Time]]'' || 2013 || A 21-year-old man is given his family secret, the ability to travel back in time. His first goal is to find a girlfriend, and subsequent trials and errors lead him to appreciate ordinary happiness in life. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2194499/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[ARQ (film)|ARQ]]'' || 2016 || An engineer, whose invention causes time to loop during a home invasion, attempts to save his former lover, while learning who has targeted him and why.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tsoumbakos|first1=Rachel|title=The Latest Netflix Original Movie \u2018ARQ\u2019 Is A Dystopian Time Loop Adventure|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/3474705/the-latest-netflix-original-movie-arq-is-a-dystopian-time-loop-adventure/|website=The Inquisitr|accessdate=2016-10-26|date=2016-09-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Before I Fall (film)|Before I Fall]]'' || 2017 || A popular high school senior finds herself reliving the same day over and over.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Felperin|first1=Leslie|title=\u2018Before I Fall\u2019: Film Review|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/review/before-i-fall-review-967494|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=15 February 2017|date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Blood Punch]]'' || 2013 || A trio visits a remote cabin for a one-time criminal endeavor and finds each member independently reliving the same day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blood Punch - Fruity Looper |url=https://www.filmtrap.com/blood-punch-fruity-looper/ |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Camp Slaughter]]'' (also known as ''Camp Daze'') || 2005 || A group of present-day teenagers are sent back to 1981, and discover a summer camp which is stuck reliving the day a demented killer went on a rampage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/333638/Camp-Slaughter/overview|title=''Camp Slaughter'' (2005)|last=Wheeler|first=Jeremy|website=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[All Media Network|AllRovi]]|accessdate=12 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512221623/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/333638/Camp-Slaughter/overview|archivedate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Christmas Every Day]]'' || 1996 || An [[Cinema of the United States|American]] [[television movie]] based on [[William Dean Howells]]' 1892 short story \"Christmas Every Day\". A selfish teenager is forced to relive the same Christmas every day.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caro|first1=Jason|title=Christmas Every Day|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/film/mddm7/christmas-every-day|website=Radio Times|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[A Day (film)|A Day]]'' || 2017 || A father attempts to save his daughter whilst stuck in an endless time loop.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Hyo-won|title=Cannes: South Korean Time Travel Film 'A Day' Sells to Multiple Territories|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-south-korean-film-a-day-sells-multiple-territories-1011010|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=25 September 2017|date=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Doctor Strange (2016 film)|Doctor Strange]]'' || 2016 || Stephen Strange traps himself and Dormmamu in a time loop in order to stop him from consuming the Earth.<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Couch |title='Doctor Strange' Writer on Time-Bending Twist and What It Means for Marvel's Future |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/doctor-strange-end-screenwriter-explains-twist-944334 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=26 November 2016 |accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Edge of Tomorrow (film)|Edge of Tomorrow]]'' (also known as ''Live. Die. Repeat: Edge of Tomorrow) || 2014 || Maj. William \"Bill\" Cage ([[Tom Cruise]]) and Special Forces soldier Rita Vrataski ([[Emily Blunt]]) team up to fight a hostile alien race known as Mimics, with Cage continually returning to a repeating battle through a time loop.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-edge-of-tomorrow-trailer-tom-cruise-fights-an-eternal-battle-20140325,0,2975972.story|title='Edge of Tomorrow' trailer: Tom Cruise fights an eternal battle|author=Gettell, Oliver |date=2014-03-25|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Endless (film)|The Endless]]'' || 2017 || Two brothers return to a cult that is stuck in a time loop.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/04/lets-unpack-that-big-twist-in-the-endless.html|title=Unpacking That Big Twist in The Endless|last=Crucchiola|first=Jordan|work=[[Vulture.com]]|date=April 6, 2018|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Toki o Kakeru Sh\u014djo (1983 film)|The Girl Who Leapt Through Time]]'' (live-action) || 1983\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Based on [[Yasutaka Tsutsui]]'s 1965 [[The Girl Who Leapt Through Time|novel of the same name]]. The story is about a Japanese school girl who accidentally gains the ability to time travel, which she experiments with and attempts to alter past events, leading her on a journey through multiple time loops.<ref>{{cite web |title=THE GIRL WHO LEAPT THROUGH TIME (2006) |url=http://deptfordcinema.org/new-events/2017/8/9/the-girl-who-leapt-through-time-2006 |website=[[Deptford Cinema]] |date=August 9, 2017 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=THE GIRL WHO LEAPT THROUGH TIME (2006) at Deptford Cinema |url=https://www.ticketsource.co.uk/whats-on/london/deptford-cinema/the-girl-who-leapt-through-time-2006/e-opyqmx |website=[[TicketSource]] |accessdate=2