{"title_page": "Banaras Hindu University", "text_new": "{{short description|University in Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh, India}} \n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name            = Banaras Hindu University\n| nickname        = \n| former_name     = Central Hindu College\n| image_name      = Banaras Hindu University seal.svg\n| image_size      = 150\n| caption         = The seal of Banaras Hindu University, depicting Goddess [[Saraswati]]\n| motto           = ''Vidyay\u0101'mritama\u0219nute''\n| mottoeng        = \"Knowledge imparts immortality\"\n| established     = {{start date and age|1916}}\n| type            = [[Public university|Public]]\n| chancellor      = Giridhar Malaviya<ref>{{cite web |title=Banaras Hindu University, Varanasi |url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/admin/chancellor.php |website=www.bhu.ac.in |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n| vice_chancellor = [[Rakesh Bhatnagar]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Vice-Chancellor|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/admin/vc.php|website=www.bhu.ac.in|accessdate=29 March 2018}}</ref>\n| students        = 30,698<ref name=\"BHU\">{{cite web |title=University |url=https://www.ugc.ac.in/centralniversitylist.aspx?id=33&Unitype=1 |website=www.ugc.ac.in |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n| undergrad       = 15,746<ref name=\"BHU\"/>\n| postgrad        = 7,557<ref name=\"BHU\"/>\n| doctoral        = 4,555<ref name=\"BHU\"/>\n| city            = [[Varanasi]]\n| state           = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| country         = [[India]]\n| campus          = Multiple sites\n| mascot          = [[Goddess Saraswati]]\n| affiliations    = {{hlist|[[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]]|[[Association of Indian Universities|AIU]]|[[National Assessment and Accreditation Council|NAAC]]|[[University Grants Commission (India)|UGC]]}}\n| website         = {{URL|bhu.ac.in}}\n| founder         = [[Madan Mohan Malaviya]]<br /> [[Annie Besant]]\n| logo            = \n}}\n{{coords|25.2677203|82.9890695|display=title}}\n\n'''Banaras Hindu University''' ([[Hindi]]: [ka\u0283i hind\u032au vi\u0283v\u0259vid\u032ayal\u0259y], '''BHU'''), formerly '''Central Hindu College''', is a [[Public university|public]] [[Central University (India)|central university]] located in [[Varanasi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. It was established in 1916 by [[Madan Mohan Malaviya]], with co-operation from [[Annie Besant]].<ref name=bhu-history>{{cite web |title=History of BHU |url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/history1.htm |publisher=Banaras Hindu University website |access-date=8 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184751/http://www.bhu.ac.in/history1.htm |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> With over 30,000 students residing in campus, it is the largest [[residential college|residential university]] in Asia.<ref name=red>{{cite web |title=University at Buffalo, BHU sign exchange programme |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/oct/04univ.htm|publisher=[[Rediff]] News |date=4 October 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe university's main campus spread over {{convert|1300|acre|km2}} was built on land donated by the [[Kashi Naresh]] [[Prabhu Narayan Singh]], the hereditary ruler of Banaras (\"Kashi\" being an alternative name for Banaras or Varanasi). The south campus, spread over {{convert|2700|acre|km2}},<ref name=bhu-rgsc-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/aboutrgsc.html|title=About the Campus|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618042838/http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/aboutrgsc.html|archivedate=18 June 2012}}</ref> hosts the Krishi Vigyan Kendra (Agriculture Science Centre)<ref name=bhu-rgsc>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/index.html|title=Rajiv Gandhi South Campus|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> and is located in Barkachha in [[Mirzapur district]], about {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} from Banaras.  .<ref>{{cite web|title=Banaras Hindu University keen to {{sic|hide=y|set|up}} its Center in Bihar|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/banaras-hindu-university-keen-to-setup-its-center-in-bihar/|work=IANS|publisher=Biharprabha News|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nBHU is organised into 6 institutes and 14 faculties (streams) and about 140 departments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/Annexure-I%20(A%20brief%20note%20about%20the%20University).doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211052710/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/Annexure-I%20(A%20brief%20note%20about%20the%20University).doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 December 2018|title=UGC BHU Fact Sheet}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723094026/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2018|title=UGC Fact Sheet}}</ref><!-- Due to non-updation at official website of university, it shows there 3 institutes and/or 16 faculties etc. \nHowever calculating these numbers on the basis of printed brochures being circulated in university, on the basis of the speech-mentions of the Vice-Chancellor himself and other official printed (but non- electronic) sources, the data mentioned here is correct. --> {{as of|2017}}, the total student enrolment at the university is 27,359<ref>{{cite web|title=Submitted Institute Data for National Institute Ranking Framework - Banaras Hindu University, Varanasi|url=https://nirfcdn.azureedge.net/2018/pdf/UNIVERSITY/IR-3-O-OMD-U-0500.pdf|publisher=NIRF|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> coming from 48 countries.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Banaras Hindu University: All rounder : 2011 - India Today|url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/indias-best-universities-banaras-hindu-university/1/147177.html|website = indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate = 10 November 2015}}</ref> It has over 75 [[hostel]]s for resident students. Several of its faculties and institutes include arts ([[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University|FA - BHU]]), commerce ([[Faculty of Commerce, Banaras Hindu University]]), management studies (Institute of Management Studies Banaras Hindu University|I.M.St. - BHU), science ([[Institute of Science, Banaras Hindu University|I.Sc. - BHU]]), performing arts (FPA-BHU), law ([[Faculty of Law, Banaras Hindu University|FL-BHU]]), agricultural science (Institute of Agricultural Science, Banaras Hindu University|I.A.S. - BHU), medical science (Institute of Medical Science, Banaras Hindu University|I.M.S. - BHU) and environment and sustainable development (Institute of Environment And Sustainable Development, Banaras Hindu University|I.E.S.D. - BHU) along with departments of linguistics, journalism & mass communication, among others. The university's engineering institute was designated as an [[Indian Institute of Technology]] ([[IIT BHU]]) in June 2012.\n\nBHU celebrated its centenary year in 2015-2016. The Centenary Year Celebration Cell organised various programs including cultural programs, feasts, competitions and Mahamana Madan Mohan Malviya Birth Anniversary on 25 December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 things to know about Madan Mohan Malviya|url = http://www.abplive.in/india-news/10-things-to-know-about-madan-mohan-malviya-23228|website = ABP Live|accessdate = 10 November 2015|date = 24 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n[[File: Madan Mohan Malaviya 01.JPG|right|upright|thumb|Statue of [[Madan Mohan Malviya]] at the entrance of Shri Vishwanath Mandir]]\n\nThe Banaras Hindu University was established by [[Madan Mohan Malviya]]. A prominent lawyer and an [[Indian independence activist]], Malviya considered education as the primary means for achieving a national awakening.<ref name=bhu-founder-18>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=18|year=2006|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the 21st Conference of the [[Indian National Congress]] in [[Benares]] in December 1905, Malviya publicly announced his intent to establish a university in Varanasi. On the request of Malviya, Sant baba Attar Singh ji Mastuana sahib, Sangrur Punjab laid the foundation stone of Banaras Hindu University at Varanasi in 1914. Malviya continued to develop his vision for the university with inputs from other Indian nationalists and educationists. He published his plan in 1911. The focus of his arguments was the prevailing poverty in India and the decline in income of Indians compared to Europeans. The plan called for the focus on technology and science, besides the study of India's religion and culture:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The millions mired in poverty here can only get rid (of it) when science is used in their interest. Such maximum application of science is only possible when scientific knowledge is available to Indians in their own country.\"<ref name=bhu-founder-19>{{cite web |url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=19|year=2006|accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nMalviya's plan evaluated whether to seek government recognition for the university or operate without its control. He decided in favour of the former for various reasons. Malviya also considered the question of medium of instruction and decided to start with English given the prevalent environment, and gradually add [[Hindi language|Hindi]] and other [[Languages of India|Indian languages]]. A distinguishing characteristic of Malviya's vision was the preference for a [[residential college|residential university]]. All other Indian universities of the period, such as the universities in [[University of Mumbai|Bombay]], [[University of Calcutta|Calcutta]], [[University of Madras|Madras]], etc., were affiliating universities which only conducted examinations and awarded degrees to students of their affiliated colleges.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite book |title=Banaras Region: A Spiritual and Cultural Guide |last=Singh |first=Rana P.B. |authorlink= |author2=Pravin S. Rana |year=2002 |publisher=Indica Books |location=Varanasi |isbn=81-86569-24-3 |page=141 |url= }}<!--|accessdate=1 April 2011--></ref> Malviya had supported [[Annie Besant]]'s cause and in 1903, he had raised 250,000 Rupees in donations to finance the construction of the school's [[dormitory|hostel]].<ref name=bhu-founder-12>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM1.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=12|year=2006|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> In 1907 Besant had applied for a [[Royal charter#United Kingdom|royal charter]] to establish a university. However, there was no response from the British government.\n\nFollowing the publication of Malviya's plan, Besant met Malviya and in April 1911 they agreed to unite their forces to build the university in Varanasi.<ref name=bhu-mahamana>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/mahamana.htm|title= Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya: The Man, The Spirit, The Vision|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nMalviya soon left his legal practice to focus exclusively on developing the university and his independence activities.<ref name=bhu-founder-11>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=11|year=2006|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> On 22 November 1911, he registered the Hindu University Society to gather support and raise funds for building the university.<ref name=bhu-founder-30>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM1.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=30|year=2006|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> He spent the next 4 years gathering support and raising funds for the university. Malviya sought and received early support from the [[Kashi Naresh]] [[Prabhu Narayan Singh]] and Maharaja Sir [[Rameshwar Singh Bahadur]] of [[Raj Darbhanga]].<ref name=\"Singh\"/> Thakur Jadunath Singh of [[Arkha]] along with other noble houses of United Provinces contributed for the development of the university.\n\nIn October 1915, with support from Malviya's allies in the Indian National Congress, the ''Banaras Hindu University Bill'' was passed by the [[Imperial Legislative Council]].<ref name=ik-bhu-act>{{cite web|url=http://indiankanoon.org/doc/1421454/|title=The Banaras Hindu University Act, 1915|publisher=Indian Kanoon|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBHU was finally established in 1916, the first university in India that was the result of a private individual's efforts. The foundation for the main campus of the university was laid by [[Charles Hardinge, 1st Baron Hardinge of Penshurst|Lord Hardinge]], the then [[Viceroy of India]], on [[Vasant Panchami]] 4 February 1916.<ref name=bhu-mahamana/><ref name=cs-bhu>{{cite journal|url=http://cs-test.ias.ac.in/cs/Volumes/101/08/1091.pdf|title=Madan Mohan Malaviya and Banaras Hindu University|journal=Current Science|publisher=Indian Academy of Sciences|volume=101|issue=8|date=25 October 2011|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> To promote the university's expansion, Malviya invited eminent guest speakers such as [[Mahatma Gandhi]], Sir [[Jagadish Chandra Bose]], Prof [[C. V. Raman]], [[Prafulla Chandra Roy]], Prof [[Sam Higginbottom]], Sir [[Patrick Geddes]], and Besant to deliver a series of what are now called ''The University Extension Lectures'' between 5\u20138 February 1916. Gandhi's lecture on the occasion was his first public address in India.<ref name=cs-bhu/>\n\n[[Sir Sunder Lal]] was appointed the first Vice-Chancellor, and the university began its academic session<ref name=bhu-history/> the same month with classes initially held at the Central Hindu School in the Kamachha area, while the campus was being built on over {{convert|1300|acres|km2}} of land donated by the Kashi Naresh on the outskirts of the city. The [[Nizam]] of [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] and [[Central Provinces and Berar|Berar]], [[Mir Osman Ali Khan]], also made a donation of {{INR|1}} lakh for the university.<ref>{{cite news|url =https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/A-lsquomiser-who-donated-generously/article15988076.ece |title = A 'miser' who donated generously|newspaper=thehindu|date= 24 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telanganatoday.com/reminiscing-seventh-nizam-enormous-contribution-education|title=Reminiscing the seventh Nizam's enormous contribution to education|first=AuthorJS|last=Ifthekhar|website=Telangana Today}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://missiontelangana.com/nizam-gave-funding-for-temples-and-hindu-educational-institutions|title=Nizam gave funding for temples, and Hindu educational institutions|date=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe university's anthem, known as the ''Kulgeet'', was composed by Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar.<ref name=bhu-heritage>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/malviyaheritage/heritage.html|title=Heritage Complex|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Main campus===\n[[File:Dept of Electrical Engineering IIT-BHU.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|Dept of Electrical Engineering IIT-BHU]]\n[[File:Sir sundar lal hospital.jpg|thumb|Sir Sundarlal Hospital]]\n[[File:Birla Hostel, BHU.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|Birla Hostel, BHU]]\n\nBHU is located on the southern edge of Varanasi, near the banks of the river [[Ganges]]. Development of the main campus, spread over {{convert|1300|acre|km2}}, started in 1916 on land donated by the then Kashi Naresh [[Prabhu Narayan Singh]]. The campus layout approximates a [[semicircle]], with intersecting roads laid out along the radii or in arcs. Buildings built in the first half of the 20th century are fine examples of [[Indo-Gothic]] architecture.\n\nThe campus has over 60 hostels offering residential accommodation for over 12,000 students.<ref name=bhu-amenities>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/student/index.html|title=Student Amenities|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> On-campus housing is also available to a majority of the full-time faculty.\n \nThe main entrance gate and boundary wall was built on the donation made by Maharaja of [[Balrampur]], Maharaja Pateshvari Prashad Singh.\n\nThe [[Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library, BHU|Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library]] is the main library on campus and houses over 1.3&nbsp;million volumes as of 2011. Completed in 1941, its construction was financed by Maharaja [[Sayajirao Gaekwad III]] of [[Baroda]]. In addition to the main library, there are three institute libraries, eight faculty libraries and over 25 departmental libraries available to students and staff.\n\n[[Sir Sunderlal Hospital]] on the campus is a [[teaching hospital]] for the Institute of Medical Sciences. Established in 1926 with 96 beds, it has since been expanded to over 900 beds and is the largest [[tertiary referral hospital]] in the region.\n\n[[File:New Vishwanath Temple at BHU.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|left|[[Shri Vishwanath Mandir]] has the tallest temple tower in the world.<ref name=\"Brief description\">{{cite news|title=Brief description|publisher=[[Benaras Hindu University]] website|accessdate=7 March 2015|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/VT/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425201106/http://www.bhu.ac.in/VT/|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 April 2018}}</ref>]]\nThe most prominent landmark is the [[Shri Vishwanath Mandir]], located in the centre of the campus. The foundation for this {{convert|252|ft|m}} high complex of seven temples was laid in March 1931, and took almost three decades to complete.<ref name=bhu-landmarks>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/aboutbhu/landmarks.html|title=Landmarks and Heritage of BHU|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614160823/http://www.bhu.ac.in/aboutbhu/landmarks.html|archivedate=14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Bharat Kala Bhavan]] is an art and archaeological museum on the campus. Established in January 1920, its first chairman was [[Nobel laureate]] [[Rabindranath Tagore]], with his nephew [[Abanindranath Tagore]] as the vice-chairman. The museum was expanded and gained prominence with the efforts of [[Rai Krishnadasa]].<ref name=kala-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/kala/history.htm|title=History|publisher=Bharat Kala Bhavan|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The museum is best known for its collection of Indian paintings, but also includes archaeological artefacts, textiles and costumes, Indian philately as well as literary and archival materials.<ref name=kala-collection>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/kala/history.htm|title=Collection|publisher=Bharat Kala Bhavan|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The Alice Boner Gallery was also set up at Bharat Kala Bhavan with the assistance of the Alice Boner Foundation in 1989 to mark the birth centenary of [[Alice Boner]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/kala/gallery_aliceboner.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817193547/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/kala/gallery_aliceboner.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 August 2018|title=Alice Boner Gallery}}</ref>\n\n=== Rajiv Gandhi South Campus ===\nThe south campus is located in Barkachha in [[Mirzapur district]],<ref name=\"bhu-rgsc-history\" /> about {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwest of the main campus. Spread over an area of over {{convert|2700|acre|km2}}, it was transferred as a lease in perpetuity to BHU by the Bharat Mandal Trust in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/barkachha/index.html|title=History|publisher=RGSC, Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt hosts the Krishi Vigyan Kendra (Agricultural Science Centre), with focus on research in agricultural techniques, agro-forestry and bio-diversity appropriate to the [[Vindhya Range]] region.<ref name=\"bhu-rgsc-projects\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/projects.html|title=Research Projects|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The South Campus features a lecture complex, library, student hostels and faculty housing, besides administrative offices.<ref name=\"bhu-rgsc-infra\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/infrastructure.html|title=Infrastructure|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nBHU is organised into 6 institutes and 14 faculties (streams). The institutes are administratively autonomous, with their own budget, management and academic bodies.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090417011232/http://education.nic.in/cd50years/x/7H/8I/7H8I0201.htm]\n</ref>\n\n==Institutes==\n\n===Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi===\n\n{{main|Indian Institute of Technology, BHU}}\nThe [[Indian Institute of Technology, BHU|Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi]] (IIT-BHU) is an engineering institute under the aegis of BHU. IIT-BHU has 14 departments and 3 inter-disciplinary schools,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iitbhu.ac.in/dept|title=Departments|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> providing technology education with an emphasis on its industrial applications. Established in 1919, it is one of the oldest engineering institutes in India.<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction|url=http://www.jee.iitk.ac.in/|publisher=IIT Kanpur|accessdate=6 October 2011}}</ref> The institute in its present form was created by the merger of three BHU colleges \u2013 the Banaras Engineering College, the College of Mining and Metallurgy, and the College of Technology.\n\nIt was designated as [[Indian Institutes of Technology|Indian Institute of Technology]] (IIT) by The Institutes of Technology (Amendment) Act, 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iitbhu.ac.in/institute/IT_Act_Amended.pdf|title=IIT-BHU Act|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> of [[Parliament of India|Parliament]] in 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iitmandi.ac.in/news/articles/files/IT-Amendment-Act-2012.pdf |title=IT-Amendment-Act-2012|author= Ministry of Law and Justice (Legislative Department)|date=21 June 2012|publisher=[[The Gazette of India]] |accessdate=21 September 2012}}</ref> and is declared as [[List of Institutes of National Importance|Institute of National Importance]] by [[Government of India]] under IIT Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Institutions of National Importance|url=http://mhrd.gov.in/institutions-national-importance|publisher=Ministry of Human Resource Development, Government of India|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Institute of Science ===\n{{main|Institute of Science, Banaras Hindu University}}\nThe Institute of Science (ISc) comprises 13 departments covering various branches of modern science, and several inter-disciplinary schools and research centres. It offers undergraduate, postgraduate and PhD in most disciplines, MSc (Tech.) in Geophysics, MCA, and conducts research programmes in all areas.Two vocational courses, Industrial Microbiology and Electronics Instrumentation and Maintenance have been introduced in recent years at U.G. level. Aakanksha is its annual cultural fest organised every year in the month of February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amarujala.com/photo-gallery/uttar-pradesh/varanasi/bhu-youth-festival-akansha-start-from-today|title=Amar Ujala|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Institute of Agricultural Sciences===\n\n{{main|Institute of Agricultural Sciences, Banaras Hindu University}}\nThe Institute of Agricultural Sciences (IAS) was founded as Institute of Agricultural Research in 1931 and was the first institute in India to provide postgraduate programs (MSc and PhD) in [[agricultural science]]. In 1945, undergraduate degrees were introduced and it was renamed as the College of Agriculture. It was renamed as the Faculty of Agriculture in 1968 and was raised to the status of the Institute of Agricultural Sciences in August 1980. It is involved in both education and research in agricultural science.<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/ias/|publisher=Institute of Agricultural Sciences, BHU|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Institute of Medical Sciences===\n\n[[File:Institute Of Medical Sciences BHU.jpg|thumb|right|Institute of Medical Sciences, BHU]]\n{{Main|Institute of Medical Sciences, Banaras Hindu University}}\nThe Institute of Medical Sciences (IMS) is a residential, co-educational medical institute. It admits students for its programs in medicine through the NEET entrance examination held across India. In addition to the [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MBBS]] programs, it offers specialisations and PhD programs for physicians in medicine and surgery. It also offers graduate and post-graduate programs in [[Nursing]], [[Ayurvedic medicine]], [[Dentistry]] and [[Medical statistics|Health Statistics]]. It is one of the finest institutes in the country. It produces some of the best physicians and results across the country. There are three faculties viz. Medicine, Ayurveda and Dental Sciences.\n\n===Institute of Environment and Sustainable Development===\n\nThe Institute of Environment & Sustainable Development (IESD) aiming to develop and advance the knowledge of technology and processes for sustainable development was started in 2010 in the tenure of the then Vice-Chancellor of BHU, D.P. Singh.<ref name=iesd-welcome>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/institute_enviroment_sustanable/|title=Welcome|publisher=Institute of Environment & Sustainable Development, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518100351/http://www.bhu.ac.in/institute_enviroment_sustanable/|archivedate=18 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn accordance with the UN visualisation that higher education should contribute significantly to the development of appropriate knowledge and competencies in the area of sustainable development, a nation-level Institute of Environment & Sustainable Development has been established in the Banaras Hindu University. The institute will cover education about sustainable development (developing an awareness of what is involved) and education for sustainable development (using education as a tool to achieve sustainability). The institute will be dedicated to a better understanding of critical scientific and social issues related to sustainable development goals through guided research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/iesd/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723093238/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/iesd/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2018|title=IESD}}</ref>\n\n===Institute of Management Studies===\nThe Institute of Management Studies is the [[business school]] of Banaras Hindu University. Established in 1968 as the Faculty of Management Studies (FMS, BHU), it is among the earliest management schools in [[India]]. It was renamed to its current name on 16 December 2015.<ref>http://www.bhu.ac.in/fms/NofIoMS-BHU16Dec2015.pdf</ref>\n\nThe institute offers several two-year [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA) programmes. Admission is based on the combined merit acquired by a candidate in [[Common Admission Test|CAT]], group discussion and interview. Eligibility requirements are a graduate degree under 10+2+3 Pattern / degree in Agriculture, Technology, Medicine, Education or Law / Post-graduate degree in any discipline under 10+2+3+2 pattern from any Indian University/Institution recognised by AIU/AICTE with at least 50% marks in aggregate (at least 45% for SC/ST candidates).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/fms/admissions.php|title=Welcome to Institute of Management Studies, BHU.|website=www.bhu.ac.in|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Faculties==\n[[File:Faculty of Arts, BHU.JPG|thumb|Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University]]\n\nAcademic faculties of the university include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/education/faculty.html |title=Faculty & Institute, BHU |publisher=Bhu.ac.in |date=19 August 2006 |accessdate=19 August 2011}}</ref>\n*[[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Arts]]\n*Faculty of Ayurveda\n*[[Faculty of Commerce, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Commerce]]\n*Faculty of Education\n*[[Faculty of Law, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Law]]\n*Faculty of Performing Arts\n*[[Faculty of Sanskrit Vidya Dharma Vijnan, Banaras Hindu University|Sanskrit Vidya Dharma Vijnan Sankaya]]\n*Faculty of Social Sciences\n*Faculty of Visual Arts\n\n=== Faculty of Performing Arts ===\nThe Faculty of Performing Arts offers [[Undergraduate education#Indian system|undergraduate]], [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] and [[doctorate]] courses in [[performing arts]]. It was founded in 1950 and had several renowned and award-winning artists and musicians as faculty members.<ref name=\"Faculty of Performing Arts\">{{cite news|title=Faculty of Performing Arts|publisher=BHU website|accessdate=25 June 2015|url=http://bhu.ac.in/performing_arts/}}</ref><ref name=\"Location\">{{cite news|title=Location|publisher=Latlong.net|accessdate=25 June 2015|url=http://www.latlong.net/}}</ref> Faculty of Performing Arts was started by [[Omkarnath Thakur]] in 1950. It was initially instituted as a college called \"Music and Fine Arts\". In 1966, under Govind Malviya and founding principal Omkarnath Thakur, the college was restructured to a faculty, with three departments ([[Vocal music]], [[Instrumental music]] and [[Musicology]]). Faculty of Performing Arts claims to start the first department of Musicology in India headed by musicologists [[Prem Lata Sharma]].<ref name=\"Faculty of Performing Arts\"/>\n\n=== Faculty of Social Sciences ===\n[[File:Fss vasu.jpg|thumb|upright|Samanvaya Bhawan, Faculty of Social Sciences (Old PG Building) as seen from Faculty of Arts building]]\nThe Faculty of Social Sciences offers [[Undergraduate education#Indian system|undergraduate]] and [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] courses in [[Social science]]. It was bifurcated from the [[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Arts]] in 1971. It includes the departments of Economics, History, Political Science, Psychology and Sociology.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to \"Faculty of Social Sciences\"|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther than the departments, there are five centres which carry on the studies in various fields, namely the Centre for the Study of Nepal, Centre for Women's Study and Development, Centre for Integrated Rural Development, Centre for the Study of Social Exclusion and Inclusion Policy and the Malviya Centre for Peace Research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to \"Faculty of Social Sciences\"|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}} Click \"Centers\".</ref>\n\nThe faculty holds three chairs, the currently ({{as of|2018|lc=y}}) vacant Babu Jagjivan Ram Chair for Social Research, commemorating [[Jagjivan Ram]] and his contributions,<ref>{{cite web|title=Babu Jagjivan Ram Chair for Social Research (BJRC)|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/chair.php|website=bhu.ac.in|publisher=Banaras Hindu University, Faculty of Social Sciences Varanasi|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> the Dr. Ambedkar Chair for Nationalism & National Integration established in 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dr. B.R. Ambedkar Chair|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/ambedkar/|website=bhu.ac.in|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> and the Pt. Deendayal Upadhyay Chair, established in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pt. Deendayal Upadhyay Chair|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/deendayal/|website=bhu.ac.in|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nFSS Connect, a project website for students was launched in 2018. Abhikalpan is the annual Youth Fest of Faculty of Social Sciences, BHU. In 2018, Innovation Unit for students, that is Innovision is under DIC, MIC-IIC BHU, Atal Incubation Centre and Media and Publishing Council of Students keep indulging students in a creative way. And every year FSS-BHU can see changes in inter-disciplinary and co-curricular activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=FSS Connect - Faculty of Social Sciences, BHU |url=https://www.fssconnect.org/home |website=fssconnect.org/ |publisher=Faculty of Social Sciences, BHU |accessdate= 31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty of Visual Arts ===\nThe Faculty of Visual Arts offers undergraduate and postgraduate courses in [[Applied arts|applied]] and [[visual arts]]. It was founded in 1916.<ref name=\"About Faculty\">{{cite news|title=About Faculty of Visual Arts|publisher=BHU website|accessdate=1 October 2015|url=http://bhu.ac.in/visualarts/}}</ref> It includes five departments:\n\n:*[[Painting]]\n:*[[Applied arts]]\n:*[[Plastic arts]]\n:*[[Pottery]] and [[Ceramics]]\n:*Textile designing\n\n==Inter-disciplinary schools==\n\n===School of Biotechnology===\n\n[[File:School of Biotechnology, Banaras Hindu University (BHU).jpg|thumb|School of Biotechnology, Faculty of Science, Banaras Hindu University]]\nThe School of Biotechnology (SBT) is a center for postgraduate teaching and research under the aegis of Institute of Science of the BHU.<ref>{{cite web|title=Home Page of Faculty of Science, BHU|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/science/index.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402213023/http://www.bhu.ac.in/science/index.html|archivedate=2 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=bhu-biotech>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/biotechnology/|title=About the department - School of Biotechnology, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609022459/http://www.bhu.ac.in/biotechnology/|archivedate=9 June 2012}}</ref> It was established in 1986 with funding from the [[Department of Biotechnology]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Human Resource Development, Department of Biotechnology, Government of India|url=http://dbtindia.nic.in/uniquepage.asp?id_pk=16#1|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124075204/http://dbtindia.nic.in/uniquepage.asp?id_pk=16#1|archivedate=24 November 2011}}</ref> of the Ministry of Science and Technology, [[Government of India]]. It offers MSc and PhD programmes in [[Biotechnology]].\n\nThe interdisciplinary program involves the partnership between the Institute of Science, the Institute of Medical Sciences and the Indian Institute of Technology at BHU. Notable faculty include [[Arvind Mohan Kayastha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/biotechnology/amkayastha.neraj|title=Lab web page of Prof. A. M. Kayastha, School of Biotechnology|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===DBT-BHU Interdisciplinary School of Life Sciences===\n\nThe Interdisciplinary School of Life Sciences (ISLS) is a joint initiative of the Department of Biotechnology (DBT), Government of India and the BHU. It was established with a grant of INR 238.9&nbsp;million from the DBT.<ref name=toi-lifesci>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-10-07/varanasi/28089134_1_life-sciences-bd-singh-dp-singh|title=Central grant to BHU for school of life sciences|publisher=The Times of India|date=7 October 2009|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===DST Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences===\n\nThe Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences (CIMS) focuses on research and education in mathematics, modelling and statistics. It was established under the management of the Faculty of Science, with support from the [[Department of Science and Technology (India)|Department of Science and Technology]] (DST).<ref name=bhu-cims>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/CIMS/|title=About us|publisher=DST Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619075814/http://www.bhu.ac.in/CIMS/|archivedate=19 June 2012}}</ref> The centre imparts post-graduate education and research with participation from the Department of Mathematics, Department of Statistics and Department of Computer Science of the Institute of Science and the Department of Applied Mathematics of the IIT-BHU. It regularly organises training programmes, workshops, Seminars and conferences.\n\n===Centre of Food Science and Technology===\n\nThe Centre of Food Science & Technology (CFST) is an inter-disciplinary research centre with collaboration between the Institute of Agricultural Sciences and the Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) focusing on food processing technology.<ref name=bhu-cfst>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/CFST/|title=Overview|publisher=Centre of Food Science & Technology, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Research centres==\nApart from specialised centres directly funded by DBT, DST, ICAR and ISRO, a large number of departments under the Institutes of Sciences, Engineering & Technology and Faculty of Social Sciences receive funding from the DST Fund for Improvement of Science & Technology Infrastructure (FIST) and the University Grants Commission (UGC) Special Assistance Programme (SAP). UGC SAP provides funds under its Centre of Advanced Study (CAS), Department of Special Assistance (DSA) and Departmental Research Support (DRS) programmes.<ref name=ugc-financial>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugc.ac.in/financialsupport/guideline_24.html|title=Financial Support: Special Assistance Programme (SAP)|publisher=University Grants Commission|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBHU research centres include:\n* DBT Centre of Genetic Disorders<ref name=\"bhu-cgd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/CGD/CGD%20website.htm|title=About CGD|publisher=Centre for Genetic Disorders, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511063704/http://www.bhu.ac.in/CGD/CGD%20website.htm|archivedate=11 May 2012}}</ref>\n* Center for Environmental Science and Technology<ref name=\"bhu-cest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/cest|title=Welcome|publisher=Centre for Environmental Science & Technology, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n* Nano science and Technology Center\n* Hydrogen Energy Center\n* UGC Advanced Immunodiagnostic Training and Research Center\n* Centre for Experimental Medicine and Surgery\n* Center for Women's Studies and Development (CWSD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cwsd/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215122712/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cwsd/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=CWSD}}</ref>\n* Center for the Study of Nepal (CNS)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/csn/|title=CSN|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* Malviya Center for Peace Research (MCPR)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/mcpr/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215123122/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/mcpr/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=MCPR}}</ref>\n* Center for Rural Integrated Development (CIRD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cird/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215171356/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cird/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=CIRD}}</ref>\n* Centre for Study of Social Exclusion and Inclusive Policy (CSSEIP)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/csseip/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215122901/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/csseip/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=CSSEIP}}</ref>\n* DST Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences\n\n== Affiliated colleges and schools ==\n\n===Colleges===\n\n[[File:Women's College, Banaras Hindu University, Varanasi.jpg|thumb|160px|[[Mahila Maha Vidyalaya]], Banaras Hindu University]]\n\n* [[Mahila Maha Vidyalaya]] (within main campus)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/mmv/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721172857/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/mmv/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2018|title=MMV}}</ref>\n* [[Arya Mahila Mahavidyalaya]]\n* [[DAV Post Graduate College]]\n* [[Vasanta College for Women]]\n* [[Vasant Kanya Mahavidyalaya]]\n\n===Schools===\n\n* Ranvir Sanskrit Vidyalaya,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ranvir/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723093419/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ranvir/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2018|title=RSV}}</ref>\n* [[Central Hindu Boys School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/chs/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721172601/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/chs/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2018|title=CHS}}</ref> \n* [[Central Hindu Girls School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/CHGS/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721173326/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/CHGS/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2018|title=CHGS}}</ref>\n\n==Library system==\n{{main|Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library, BHU}}\n[[File:Central Library BHU.jpg|thumb|200px|Central Library, BHU]]\nThe Banaras Hindu University Library system was established from a collection donated by P.K. Telang in the memory of his father Justice [[Kashinath Trimbak Telang]] in 1917. The collection was housed in the Telang Hall of the Central Hindu College, Kamachha. In 1921, the library was moved to the Central Hall of the Arts College (now the Faculty of Arts).\n\nThe present Central Library of BHU was established with a donation from Maharaja [[Sayajirao Gaekwad III]] of [[Baroda]]. Upon his return from the [[Round Table Conferences (India)|First round Table Conference]], Gaekwad wanted a library built on the pattern of the [[British Library]] and [[British Museum Reading Room|its reading room]], which was then located in the [[British Museum]]. On Malviya's suggestion, he made the donation to build the library on the BHU campus.<ref name=bhu-centrallibrary>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/bhulibrary/history.htm|title=Genesis and history|publisher=Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Gaekwad Library is a designated ''Manuscript Conservation Centre'' (MCC) of the [[National Mission for Manuscripts]],<ref name=namami-mcc>{{cite web|url=http://www.namami.org/convervation.htm |title=Manuscript Conservation Centres |publisher=National Mission for Manuscripts |accessdate=4 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506234603/http://www.namami.org/convervation.htm |archivedate=6 May 2012 }}</ref> established in 2003.<ref name=namami-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.namami.org/history.htm|title=History|publisher=National Mission for Manuscripts|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520182915/http://www.namami.org/history.htm|archivedate=20 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy 1931, the library had built a collection of around 60,000 volumes. The trend of donation of personal and family collection to the library continued as late as the 1940s with the result that it has unique pieces of rarities of books and journals dating back to the 18th century.\n\nAs of 2011, the BHU Library System consisted of the Central Library and 3 Institute Libraries, 8 Faculty Libraries and over 25 Departmental Libraries, with a collection of at least 1.3&nbsp;million volumes.<ref name=bhu-centrallibrary/> The digital library is available to students and staff and provides online access to thousands of journals, besides access to large collections of online resources<ref name=bhu-lib-services>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/bhulibrary/services.htm|title=Library Services|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> through the [[National Informatics Centre]]'s DELNET<ref name=delnet>{{cite web|url=http://delnet.nic.in/|title=Developing Library Network|publisher=National Informatics Centre|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> and UGC's INFLIBNET.<ref name=inflibnet>{{cite web|url=http://www.inflibnet.ac.in/|title=Information and Library Network Centre|publisher=University Grants Commission|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Protests==\n{{main|Banaras Hindu University women's rights protest }}\nOn 21 September 2017 a woman reported sexual harassment to the university. She claimed that the university responded by blaming her.<ref name=\"Mishra October 2017\">{{cite web |last1=Mishra |first1=Bishnu |title=Student Protests Have Challenged the Ideological Stagnation of BHU |url=https://thewire.in/education/banaras-hindu-university-protests-2 |website=[[The Wire (Indian web publication)]] |date=2 October 2017}}</ref> The next day, 22 September, students organised a protest of the university's treatment of women.\n\nThe university's administration filed a First information report against hundreds of students. Security officers used violence in an attempt to get protesters to disperse. Various protesters reported injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=What is the BHU protest? everything you need to know |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/what-is/bhu-protest-police-lathicharge-video-sexual-harassment-molestation-4860135/ |website=The Indian Express |language=en-IN |date=25 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Admissions==\nBanaras Hindu University conducts national level undergraduate (UET) and postgraduate (PET) entrance tests usually during May\u2013June for admission for which registrations begin usually in February\u2013March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bhuonline.in/pdfs17/Notification-for-session2017-18.pdf|title=Application process|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Admissions are done according to merit in the entrance tests, subject to fulfilling of other eligibility requirements.  Admissions to BTech/B.Pharm., MTech/M.Pharm. are done through JEE and GATE respectively. Admission to MBA and MBA-IB are done through IIM-CAT score and also through separate BHU-MBA entrance tests. Admissions for PhD are done on the basis of either qualification of [[National Eligibility Test]] (NET) by the candidates or through the scores of CRET (Common Research Entrance Test). Admissions in [[Institute of Medical Sciences, Banaras Hindu University|IMS]] are done through PMT exam.\n \nBHU attracts a number of foreign learners. Foreign students are admitted through the application submitted to the Indian mission in his/her country or by his/her country's mission in India.\n\nBHU conducts UG entrance exam every year in May. The offline exam is held for 5166 seats. The total exam duration is two hours with 150 MCQs and the total marks is 450. There are seven participating colleges including BHU Faculty of Law and six constituent colleges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://university.careers360.com/articles/bhu-uet|title=BHU UET 2019 \u2013 Check Results, Cut Off, Scorecard, Merit List, Counselling|website=university.careers360.com}}</ref>\n\n==Halls of residence==\n\nBHU is a fully residential University with a total of 62 hostels - 41 hostels for male and 21 hostels for female students.\n\nThere are four separate hostels for international students. These four include an International House Annexe for female students with an intake capacity of 24. Hostels are named after several historically important figures such as [[Kumaramangalam Birla]], [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]], [[Rani Laxmibai]] and [[M. Visvesvaraya]].\n\n==Festivals==\nBHU observes [[Saraswati]] puja day (also known as [[Vasant Panchami]]) as its foundation day. Goddess [[Saraswati]] is the Hindu goddess of knowledge, music, arts, wisdom and nature. She is a part of the trinity of [[Saraswati]], [[Lakshmi]] and [[Parvati]].\n\nThere is also an intra-university fest 'Spandan', where students represent their faculty/institute in various arts competition like literature (writing essay, poem, debates), painting, sketches, vocal music, dancing, singing, drama, and mimicry. It is held every year after Vasant Panchami in month of February or March.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n| type = University\n<!----------International---------->\n| QS_W_2020 = 801-1000\n| QS_A_2019 = 156\n| QS_BRICS_2019 = 90\n| THE_W_2020 = 601-800\n| THES_A_2019 = 140\n|THES_E_2019 = 134\n<!----------General---------->\n| NIRF_U_2019 = 3\n| NIRF_O_2019 = 10\n<!----------Engineering---------->\n| NIRF_E_2019 = 11\n| WEEK_E_2019 = 9\n<!----------Law---------->\n| OUTLOOK_L_2018 = 6\n| WEEK_L_2019 = 7\n<!----------Medical---------->\n| IT_M_2018 = 7\n| OUTLOOK_M_2018 = 8\n| WEEK_M_2019 = 6\n<!----------Management---------->\n| NIRF_B_2019 = 39\n}}\nInternationally, BHU was ranked 801-1000 in the [[QS World University Rankings]] of 2020.<ref name=Rankings_QS_W_2020/> The same rankings ranked it 156 in Asia<ref name=Rankings_QS_A_2019/> and 90 among [[BRICS]] nations in 2019.<ref name=Rankings_QS_BRICS_2019/> It was ranked 601-800 in the world by the ''[[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]]'' of 2020<ref name=Rankings_THE_W_2020/> and 140 in Asia in 2019.<ref name=Rankings_THES_A_2019/>\n\nIn India, the [[National Institutional Ranking Framework]] (NIRF) ranked it tenth overall in 2019<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_O_2019/> and third among universities.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_U_2019/> It also ranked it 39 in the management ranking.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_B_2019/>\n\nIts engineering institute, [[IIT (BHU)|IIT]], was ranked 11 by the NIRF Engineering ranking for 2019.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_E_2019 /> In 2019, it was ranked 9th among engineering colleges in India by ''[[The Week (Indian magazine)|The Week]]''.<ref name=Rankings_WEEK_E_2019 />\n\nThe [[Faculty of Law, Banaras Hindu University]] was ranked sixth in India by ''[[Outlook India]]''{{'}}s  \"Top 25 Law Colleges in 2018\"<ref name=Rankings_OUTLOOK_L_2018/> and seventh in India by ''[[The Week (Indian magazine)|The Week]]''{{'}}s \"Top Law Colleges 2019\".<ref name=Rankings_WEEK_L_2019/>\n\nThe [[Institute of Medical Sciences, Banaras Hindu University]] was ranked seventh among medical colleges in India in 2018 by ''[[India Today]]'',<ref name=Rankings_IT_M_2018 /> sixth by ''[[The Week (Indian magazine)|The Week]]''<ref name=Rankings_WEEK_M_2019 /> and eight by ''[[Outlook India]]''.<ref name=Rankings_OUTLOOK_M_2018 />\n\n==Awards and medals==\nThe following awards and medals are given to meritorious students in BHU:\n\n* BHU Medal is given to students who secure the first position in their respective departments or faculties.\n[[File:BHU Medal for meritorious students.png|50px]]\n\n==Notable alumni, faculty and staff==\n{{alumni|date=June 2017}}\n{{main|List of Banaras Hindu University people|List of Vice-Chancellors of Banaras Hindu University}}\n\nAlumni and faculty of BHU have gained prominence in India and across the world. Among BHU's administrators was [[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]], who went on to become the [[President of India]]. Other famous administrators include [[Sir Sunder Lal]], [[K. L. Shrimali]], [[Moti Lal Dhar]].\n\nThe university's alumni include [[Raj Narain]], [[Rakhaldas Bandyopadhyay]], [[C.N.R Rao]], [[Madhav Sadashiv Golwalkar]], [[Harivansh Rai Bachchan]], [[Bhupen Hazarika]], [[Shyam Sunder Surolia]], [[Veena Pandey]], [[A. K. Narain]], [[Kamalesh Chandra Chakrabarty]], [[Ashok Agarwal]], [[Jagdish Kashyap]], [[T. V. Ramakrishnan]], [[Harkishan Singh]], [[Narla Tata Rao]], [[Patcha Ramachandra Rao]], [[Jayant Vishnu Narlikar]], [[Basanti Dulal Nagchaudhuri]], [[Ahmad Hasan Dani]], [[Kota Harinarayana]], [[Kothapalli Jayashankar]], [[Krishan Kant]], [[Manick Sorcar]], [[Satish K. Tripathi]], [[Shashi P. Karna]] and [[Prem Saran Satsangi]]. Amongst its famous international students are [[Robert M. Pirsig]] and [[Koenraad Elst]].\n\nBHU's faculty have included [[Ganesh Prasad]], [[Birbal Sahni]], [[Shanti Swaroop Bhatnagar]], [[Prafulla Kumar Jena]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.iates.org.in/BIODATA_AND_ACHIEVEMENTS%20OF%20PROF%20DR.%20P.%20K.%20JENA.pdf | title=Institute of Advanced Technology and Environmental Studies profile | publisher=Institute of Advanced Technology and Environmental Studies | date=2015 | accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> [[Omkarnath Thakur]], [[N. Rajam]] and [[A. K. Narain]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mahatma Gandhi Kashi Vidyapith]]\n*[[Aligarh Muslim University]]\n{{Portal bar|India|Education}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Leah Renold, ''A Hindu Education: Early Years Of The Banaras Hindu University'' (Oxford University Press).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Banaras_Hindu_University|Banaras Hindu University}}\n* {{official|http://bhu.ac.in}}\n\n{{Banaras Hindu University}}\n{{Varanasi}}\n{{Normdaten}}\n\n[[Category:Banaras Hindu University| ]]\n[[Category:Hindu universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Central universities in India]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Varanasi]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1916]]\n[[Category:1916 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Madan Mohan Malaviya]]\n[[Category:Universities in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Donations by Nizams of Hyderabad]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|University in Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh, India}} \n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name            = Banaras Hindu University\n| nickname        = \n| former_name     = Central Hindu College\n| image_name      = Banaras Hindu University seal.svg\n| image_size      = 150\n| caption         = The seal of Banaras Hindu University, depicting Goddess [[Saraswati]]\n| motto           = ''Vidyay\u0101'mritama\u0219nute''\n| mottoeng        = \"Knowledge imparts immortality\"\n| established     = {{start date and age|1916}}\n| type            = [[Public university|Public]]\n| chancellor      = Giridhar Malaviya<ref>{{cite web |title=Banaras Hindu University, Varanasi |url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/admin/chancellor.php |website=www.bhu.ac.in |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n| vice_chancellor = [[Rakesh Bhatnagar]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Vice-Chancellor|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/admin/vc.php|website=www.bhu.ac.in|accessdate=29 March 2018}}</ref>\n| students        = 30,698<ref name=\"BHU\">{{cite web |title=University |url=https://www.ugc.ac.in/centralniversitylist.aspx?id=33&Unitype=1 |website=www.ugc.ac.in |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n| undergrad       = 15,746<ref name=\"BHU\"/>\n| postgrad        = 7,557<ref name=\"BHU\"/>\n| doctoral        = 4,555<ref name=\"BHU\"/>\n| city            = [[Varanasi]]\n| state           = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| country         = [[India]]\n| campus          = Multiple sites\n| mascot          = [[Goddess Saraswati]]\n| affiliations    = {{hlist|[[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]]|[[Association of Indian Universities|AIU]]|[[National Assessment and Accreditation Council|NAAC]]|[[University Grants Commission (India)|UGC]]}}\n| website         = {{URL|bhu.ac.in}}\n| founder         = [[Madan Mohan Malaviya]]<br /> [[Annie Besant]]\n| logo            = \n}}\n{{coords|25.2677203|82.9890695|display=title}}\n\n'''Banaras Hindu University''' ([[Hindi]]: [ka\u0283i hind\u032au vi\u0283v\u0259vid\u032ayal\u0259y], '''BHU'''), formerly '''Central Hindu College''', is a [[Public university|public]] [[Central University (India)|central university]] located in [[Varanasi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. It was established in 1916 by [[Madan Mohan Malaviya]], with co-operation from [[Annie Besant]].<ref name=bhu-history>{{cite web |title=History of BHU |url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/history1.htm |publisher=Banaras Hindu University website |access-date=8 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923184751/http://www.bhu.ac.in/history1.htm |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> With over 30,000 students residing in campus, it is the largest [[residential college|residential university]] in Asia.<ref name=red>{{cite web |title=University at Buffalo, BHU sign exchange programme |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/oct/04univ.htm|publisher=[[Rediff]] News |date=4 October 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe university's main campus spread over {{convert|1300|acre|km2}} was built on land donated by the [[Kashi Naresh]] [[Prabhu Narayan Singh]], the hereditary ruler of Banaras (\"Kashi\" being an alternative name for Banaras or Varanasi). The south campus, spread over {{convert|2700|acre|km2}},<ref name=bhu-rgsc-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/aboutrgsc.html|title=About the Campus|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=3 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618042838/http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/aboutrgsc.html|archivedate=18 June 2012}}</ref> hosts the Krishi Vigyan Kendra (Agriculture Science Centre)<ref name=bhu-rgsc>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/index.html|title=Rajiv Gandhi South Campus|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> and is located in Barkachha in [[Mirzapur district]], about {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} from Banaras.  .<ref>{{cite web|title=Banaras Hindu University keen to {{sic|hide=y|set|up}} its Center in Bihar|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/banaras-hindu-university-keen-to-setup-its-center-in-bihar/|work=IANS|publisher=Biharprabha News|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nBHU is organised into 6 institutes and 14 faculties (streams) and about 140 departments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/Annexure-I%20(A%20brief%20note%20about%20the%20University).doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211052710/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/Annexure-I%20(A%20brief%20note%20about%20the%20University).doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 December 2018|title=UGC BHU Fact Sheet}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723094026/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ugc/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2018|title=UGC Fact Sheet}}</ref><!-- Due to non-updation at official website of university, it shows there 3 institutes and/or 16 faculties etc. \nHowever calculating these numbers on the basis of printed brochures being circulated in university, on the basis of the speech-mentions of the Vice-Chancellor himself and other official printed (but non- electronic) sources, the data mentioned here is correct. --> {{as of|2017}}, the total student enrolment at the university is 27,359<ref>{{cite web|title=Submitted Institute Data for National Institute Ranking Framework - Banaras Hindu University, Varanasi|url=https://nirfcdn.azureedge.net/2018/pdf/UNIVERSITY/IR-3-O-OMD-U-0500.pdf|publisher=NIRF|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> coming from 48 countries.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Banaras Hindu University: All rounder : 2011 - India Today|url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/indias-best-universities-banaras-hindu-university/1/147177.html|website = indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate = 10 November 2015}}</ref> It has over 75 [[hostel]]s for resident students. Several of its faculties and institutes include arts ([[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University|FA - BHU]]), commerce ([[Faculty of Commerce, Banaras Hindu University]]), management studies (Institute of Management Studies Banaras Hindu University|I.M.St. - BHU), science ([[Institute of Science, Banaras Hindu University|I.Sc. - BHU]]), performing arts (FPA-BHU), law ([[Faculty of Law, Banaras Hindu University|FL-BHU]]), agricultural science (Institute of Agricultural Science, Banaras Hindu University|I.A.S. - BHU), medical science (Institute of Medical Science, Banaras Hindu University|I.M.S. - BHU) and environment and sustainable development (Institute of Environment And Sustainable Development, Banaras Hindu University|I.E.S.D. - BHU) along with departments of linguistics, journalism & mass communication, among others. The university's engineering institute was designated as an [[Indian Institute of Technology]] ([[IIT BHU]]) in June 2012.\n\nBHU celebrated its centenary year in 2015-2016. The Centenary Year Celebration Cell organised various programs including cultural programs, feasts, competitions and Mahamana Madan Mohan Malviya Birth Anniversary on 25 December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 things to know about Madan Mohan Malviya|url = http://www.abplive.in/india-news/10-things-to-know-about-madan-mohan-malviya-23228|website = ABP Live|accessdate = 10 November 2015|date = 24 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n[[File: Madan Mohan Malaviya 01.JPG|right|upright|thumb|Statue of [[Madan Mohan Malviya]] at the entrance of Shri Vishwanath Mandir]]\n\nThe Banaras Hindu University was established by [[Madan Mohan Malviya]]. A prominent lawyer and an [[Indian independence activist]], Malviya considered education as the primary means for achieving a national awakening.<ref name=bhu-founder-18>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=18|year=2006|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the 21st Conference of the [[Indian National Congress]] in [[Benares]] in December 1905, Malviya publicly announced his intent to establish a university in Varanasi. On the request of Malviya, Sant baba Attar Singh ji Mastuana sahib, Sangrur Punjab laid the foundation stone of Banaras Hindu University at Varanasi in 1914. Malviya continued to develop his vision for the university with inputs from other Indian nationalists and educationists. He published his plan in 1911. The focus of his arguments was the prevailing poverty in India and the decline in income of Indians compared to Europeans. The plan called for the focus on technology and science, besides the study of India's religion and culture:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The millions mired in poverty here can only get rid (of it) when science is used in their interest. Such maximum application of science is only possible when scientific knowledge is available to Indians in their own country.\"<ref name=bhu-founder-19>{{cite web |url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=19|year=2006|accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nMalviya's plan evaluated whether to seek government recognition for the university or operate without its control. He decided in favour of the former for various reasons. Malviya also considered the question of medium of instruction and decided to start with English given the prevalent environment, and gradually add [[Hindi language|Hindi]] and other [[Languages of India|Indian languages]]. A distinguishing characteristic of Malviya's vision was the preference for a [[residential college|residential university]]. All other Indian universities of the period, such as the universities in [[University of Mumbai|Bombay]], [[University of Calcutta|Calcutta]], [[University of Madras|Madras]], etc., were affiliating universities which only conducted examinations and awarded degrees to students of their affiliated colleges.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite book |title=Banaras Region: A Spiritual and Cultural Guide |last=Singh |first=Rana P.B. |authorlink= |author2=Pravin S. Rana |year=2002 |publisher=Indica Books |location=Varanasi |isbn=81-86569-24-3 |page=141 |url= }}<!--|accessdate=1 April 2011--></ref> Malviya had supported [[Annie Besant]]'s cause and in 1903, he had raised 250,000 Rupees in donations to finance the construction of the school's [[dormitory|hostel]].<ref name=bhu-founder-12>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM1.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=12|year=2006|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> In 1907 Besant had applied for a [[Royal charter#United Kingdom|royal charter]] to establish a university. However, there was no response from the British government.\n\nFollowing the publication of Malviya's plan, Besant met Malviya and in April 1911 they agreed to unite their forces to build the university in Varanasi.<ref name=bhu-mahamana>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/mahamana.htm|title= Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya: The Man, The Spirit, The Vision|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nMalviya soon left his legal practice to focus exclusively on developing the university and his independence activities.<ref name=bhu-founder-11>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Bharat Ratna Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=11|year=2006|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> On 22 November 1911, he registered the Hindu University Society to gather support and raise funds for building the university.<ref name=bhu-founder-30>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/MMMMM1.pdf|title=Founder of Banaras Hindu University: Mahamana Pandit Madan Mohan Malviya|publisher=Banarash Hindu University|page=30|year=2006|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> He spent the next 4 years gathering support and raising funds for the university. Malviya sought and received early support from the [[Kashi Naresh]] [[Prabhu Narayan Singh]] and Maharaja Sir [[Rameshwar Singh Bahadur]] of [[Raj Darbhanga]].<ref name=\"Singh\"/> Thakur Jadunath Singh of [[Arkha]] along with other noble houses of United Provinces contributed for the development of the university.\n\nIn October 1915, with support from Malviya's allies in the Indian National Congress, the ''Banaras Hindu University Bill'' was passed by the [[Imperial Legislative Council]].<ref name=ik-bhu-act>{{cite web|url=http://indiankanoon.org/doc/1421454/|title=The Banaras Hindu University Act, 1915|publisher=Indian Kanoon|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBHU was finally established in 1916, the first university in India that was the result of a private individual's efforts. The foundation for the main campus of the university was laid by [[Charles Hardinge, 1st Baron Hardinge of Penshurst|Lord Hardinge]], the then [[Viceroy of India]], on [[Vasant Panchami]] 4 February 1916.<ref name=bhu-mahamana/><ref name=cs-bhu>{{cite journal|url=http://cs-test.ias.ac.in/cs/Volumes/101/08/1091.pdf|title=Madan Mohan Malaviya and Banaras Hindu University|journal=Current Science|publisher=Indian Academy of Sciences|volume=101|issue=8|date=25 October 2011|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> To promote the university's expansion, Malviya invited eminent guest speakers such as [[Mahatma Gandhi]], Sir [[Jagadish Chandra Bose]], Prof [[C. V. Raman]], [[Prafulla Chandra Roy]], Prof [[Sam Higginbottom]], Sir [[Patrick Geddes]], and Besant to deliver a series of what are now called ''The University Extension Lectures'' between 5\u20138 February 1916. Gandhi's lecture on the occasion was his first public address in India.<ref name=cs-bhu/>\n\n[[Sir Sunder Lal]] was appointed the first Vice-Chancellor, and the university began its academic session<ref name=bhu-history/> the same month with classes initially held at the Central Hindu School in the Kamachha area, while the campus was being built on over {{convert|1300|acres|km2}} of land donated by the Kashi Naresh on the outskirts of the city. The [[Nizam]] of [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] and [[Central Provinces and Berar|Berar]], [[Mir Osman Ali Khan]], also made a donation of {{INR|1}} lakh for the university.<ref>{{cite news|url =https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/A-lsquomiser-who-donated-generously/article15988076.ece |title = A 'miser' who donated generously|newspaper=thehindu|date= 24 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telanganatoday.com/reminiscing-seventh-nizam-enormous-contribution-education|title=Reminiscing the seventh Nizam's enormous contribution to education|first=AuthorJS|last=Ifthekhar|website=Telangana Today}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://missiontelangana.com/nizam-gave-funding-for-temples-and-hindu-educational-institutions|title=Nizam gave funding for temples, and Hindu educational institutions|date=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe university's anthem, known as the ''Kulgeet'', was composed by Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar.<ref name=bhu-heritage>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/malviyaheritage/heritage.html|title=Heritage Complex|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Main campus===\n[[File:Dept of Electrical Engineering IIT-BHU.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|Dept of Electrical Engineering IIT-BHU]]\n[[File:Sir sundar lal hospital.jpg|thumb|Sir Sundarlal Hospital]]\n[[File:Birla Hostel, BHU.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|Birla Hostel, BHU]]\n\nBHU is located on the southern edge of Varanasi, near the banks of the river [[Ganges]]. Development of the main campus, spread over {{convert|1300|acre|km2}}, started in 1916 on land donated by the then Kashi Naresh [[Prabhu Narayan Singh]]. The campus layout approximates a [[semicircle]], with intersecting roads laid out along the radii or in arcs. Buildings built in the first half of the 20th century are fine examples of [[Indo-Gothic]] architecture.\n\nThe campus has over 60 hostels offering residential accommodation for over 12,000 students.<ref name=bhu-amenities>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/student/index.html|title=Student Amenities|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> On-campus housing is also available to a majority of the full-time faculty.\n \nThe main entrance gate and boundary wall was built on the donation made by Maharaja of [[Balrampur]], Maharaja Pateshvari Prashad Singh.\n\nThe [[Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library, BHU|Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library]] is the main library on campus and houses over 1.3&nbsp;million volumes as of 2011. Completed in 1941, its construction was financed by Maharaja [[Sayajirao Gaekwad III]] of [[Baroda]]. In addition to the main library, there are three institute libraries, eight faculty libraries and over 25 departmental libraries available to students and staff.\n\n[[Sir Sunderlal Hospital]] on the campus is a [[teaching hospital]] for the Institute of Medical Sciences. Established in 1926 with 96 beds, it has since been expanded to over 900 beds and is the largest [[tertiary referral hospital]] in the region.\n\n[[File:New Vishwanath Temple at BHU.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|left|[[Shri Vishwanath Mandir]] has the tallest temple tower in the world.<ref name=\"Brief description\">{{cite news|title=Brief description|publisher=[[Benaras Hindu University]] website|accessdate=7 March 2015|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/VT/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425201106/http://www.bhu.ac.in/VT/|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 April 2018}}</ref>]]\nThe most prominent landmark is the [[Shri Vishwanath Mandir]], located in the centre of the campus. The foundation for this {{convert|252|ft|m}} high complex of seven temples was laid in March 1931, and took almost three decades to complete.<ref name=bhu-landmarks>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/aboutbhu/landmarks.html|title=Landmarks and Heritage of BHU|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614160823/http://www.bhu.ac.in/aboutbhu/landmarks.html|archivedate=14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Bharat Kala Bhavan]] is an art and archaeological museum on the campus. Established in January 1920, its first chairman was [[Nobel laureate]] [[Rabindranath Tagore]], with his nephew [[Abanindranath Tagore]] as the vice-chairman. The museum was expanded and gained prominence with the efforts of [[Rai Krishnadasa]].<ref name=kala-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/kala/history.htm|title=History|publisher=Bharat Kala Bhavan|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The museum is best known for its collection of Indian paintings, but also includes archaeological artefacts, textiles and costumes, Indian philately as well as literary and archival materials.<ref name=kala-collection>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/kala/history.htm|title=Collection|publisher=Bharat Kala Bhavan|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The Alice Boner Gallery was also set up at Bharat Kala Bhavan with the assistance of the Alice Boner Foundation in 1989 to mark the birth centenary of [[Alice Boner]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/kala/gallery_aliceboner.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817193547/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/kala/gallery_aliceboner.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 August 2018|title=Alice Boner Gallery}}</ref>\n\n=== Rajiv Gandhi South Campus ===\nThe south campus is located in Barkachha in [[Mirzapur district]],<ref name=\"bhu-rgsc-history\" /> about {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwest of the main campus. Spread over an area of over {{convert|2700|acre|km2}}, it was transferred as a lease in perpetuity to BHU by the Bharat Mandal Trust in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/barkachha/index.html|title=History|publisher=RGSC, Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt hosts the Krishi Vigyan Kendra (Agricultural Science Centre), with focus on research in agricultural techniques, agro-forestry and bio-diversity appropriate to the [[Vindhya Range]] region.<ref name=\"bhu-rgsc-projects\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/projects.html|title=Research Projects|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> The South Campus features a lecture complex, library, student hostels and faculty housing, besides administrative offices.<ref name=\"bhu-rgsc-infra\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/barkachha/infrastructure.html|title=Infrastructure|publisher=Krishi Vigyan Kendra, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nBHU is organised into 6 institutes and 14 faculties (streams). The institutes are administratively autonomous, with their own budget, management and academic bodies.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090417011232/http://education.nic.in/cd50years/x/7H/8I/7H8I0201.htm]\n</ref>\n\n==Institutes==\n\n===Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi===\n\n{{main|Indian Institute of Technology, BHU}}\nThe [[Indian Institute of Technology, BHU|Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi]] (IIT-BHU) is an engineering institute under the aegis of BHU. IIT-BHU has 14 departments and 3 inter-disciplinary schools,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iitbhu.ac.in/dept|title=Departments|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> providing technology education with an emphasis on its industrial applications. Established in 1919, it is one of the oldest engineering institutes in India.<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction|url=http://www.jee.iitk.ac.in/|publisher=IIT Kanpur|accessdate=6 October 2011}}</ref> The institute in its present form was created by the merger of three BHU colleges \u2013 the Banaras Engineering College, the College of Mining and Metallurgy, and the College of Technology.\n\nIt was designated as [[Indian Institutes of Technology|Indian Institute of Technology]] (IIT) by The Institutes of Technology (Amendment) Act, 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iitbhu.ac.in/institute/IT_Act_Amended.pdf|title=IIT-BHU Act|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> of [[Parliament of India|Parliament]] in 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iitmandi.ac.in/news/articles/files/IT-Amendment-Act-2012.pdf |title=IT-Amendment-Act-2012|author= Ministry of Law and Justice (Legislative Department)|date=21 June 2012|publisher=[[The Gazette of India]] |accessdate=21 September 2012}}</ref> and is declared as [[List of Institutes of National Importance|Institute of National Importance]] by [[Government of India]] under IIT Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Institutions of National Importance|url=http://mhrd.gov.in/institutions-national-importance|publisher=Ministry of Human Resource Development, Government of India|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Institute of Science ===\n{{main|Institute of Science, Banaras Hindu University}}\nThe Institute of Science (ISc) comprises 13 departments covering various branches of modern science, and several inter-disciplinary schools and research centres. It offers undergraduate, postgraduate and PhD in most disciplines, MSc (Tech.) in Geophysics, MCA, and conducts research programmes in all areas.Two vocational courses, Industrial Microbiology and Electronics Instrumentation and Maintenance have been introduced in recent years at U.G. level. Aakanksha is its annual cultural fest organised every year in the month of February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amarujala.com/photo-gallery/uttar-pradesh/varanasi/bhu-youth-festival-akansha-start-from-today|title=Amar Ujala|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Institute of Agricultural Sciences===\n\n{{main|Institute of Agricultural Sciences, Banaras Hindu University}}\nThe Institute of Agricultural Sciences (IAS) was founded as Institute of Agricultural Research in 1931 and was the first institute in India to provide postgraduate programs (MSc and PhD) in [[agricultural science]]. In 1945, undergraduate degrees were introduced and it was renamed as the College of Agriculture. It was renamed as the Faculty of Agriculture in 1968 and was raised to the status of the Institute of Agricultural Sciences in August 1980. It is involved in both education and research in agricultural science.<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/ias/|publisher=Institute of Agricultural Sciences, BHU|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Institute of Medical Sciences===\n\n[[File:Institute Of Medical Sciences BHU.jpg|thumb|right|Institute of Medical Sciences, BHU]]\n{{Main|Institute of Medical Sciences, Banaras Hindu University}}\nThe Institute of Medical Sciences (IMS) is a residential, co-educational medical institute. It admits students for its programs in medicine through the NEET entrance examination held across India. In addition to the [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MBBS]] programs, it offers specialisations and PhD programs for physicians in medicine and surgery. It also offers graduate and post-graduate programs in [[Nursing]], [[Ayurvedic medicine]], [[Dentistry]] and [[Medical statistics|Health Statistics]]. It is one of the finest institutes in the country. It produces some of the best physicians and results across the country. There are three faculties viz. Medicine, Ayurveda and Dental Sciences.\n\n===Institute of Environment and Sustainable Development===\n\nThe Institute of Environment & Sustainable Development (IESD) aiming to develop and advance the knowledge of technology and processes for sustainable development was started in 2010 in the tenure of the then Vice-Chancellor of BHU, D.P. Singh.<ref name=iesd-welcome>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/institute_enviroment_sustanable/|title=Welcome|publisher=Institute of Environment & Sustainable Development, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518100351/http://www.bhu.ac.in/institute_enviroment_sustanable/|archivedate=18 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn accordance with the UN visualisation that higher education should contribute significantly to the development of appropriate knowledge and competencies in the area of sustainable development, a nation-level Institute of Environment & Sustainable Development has been established in the Banaras Hindu University. The institute will cover education about sustainable development (developing an awareness of what is involved) and education for sustainable development (using education as a tool to achieve sustainability). The institute will be dedicated to a better understanding of critical scientific and social issues related to sustainable development goals through guided research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/iesd/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723093238/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/iesd/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2018|title=IESD}}</ref>\n\n===Institute of Management Studies===\nThe Institute of Management Studies is the [[business school]] of Banaras Hindu University. Established in 1968 as the Faculty of Management Studies (FMS, BHU), it is among the earliest management schools in [[India]]. It was renamed to its current name on 16 December 2015.<ref>http://www.bhu.ac.in/fms/NofIoMS-BHU16Dec2015.pdf</ref>\n\nThe institute offers several two-year [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA) programmes. Admission is based on the combined merit acquired by a candidate in [[Common Admission Test|CAT]], group discussion and interview. Eligibility requirements are a graduate degree under 10+2+3 Pattern / degree in Agriculture, Technology, Medicine, Education or Law / Post-graduate degree in any discipline under 10+2+3+2 pattern from any Indian University/Institution recognised by AIU/AICTE with at least 50% marks in aggregate (at least 45% for SC/ST candidates).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/fms/admissions.php|title=Welcome to Institute of Management Studies, BHU.|website=www.bhu.ac.in|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Faculties==\n[[File:Faculty of Arts, BHU.JPG|thumb|Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University]]\n\nAcademic faculties of the university include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/education/faculty.html |title=Faculty & Institute, BHU |publisher=Bhu.ac.in |date=19 August 2006 |accessdate=19 August 2011}}</ref>\n*[[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Arts]]\n*Faculty of Ayurveda\n*[[Faculty of Commerce, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Commerce]]\n*Faculty of Education\n*[[Faculty of Law, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Law]]\n*Faculty of Performing Arts\n*[[Faculty of Sanskrit Vidya Dharma Vijnan, Banaras Hindu University|Sanskrit Vidya Dharma Vijnan Sankaya]]\n*Faculty of Social Sciences\n*Faculty of Visual Arts\n\n=== Faculty of Performing Arts ===\nThe Faculty of Performing Arts offers [[Undergraduate education#Indian system|undergraduate]], [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] and [[doctorate]] courses in [[performing arts]]. It was founded in 1950 and had several renowned and award-winning artists and musicians as faculty members.<ref name=\"Faculty of Performing Arts\">{{cite news|title=Faculty of Performing Arts|publisher=BHU website|accessdate=25 June 2015|url=http://bhu.ac.in/performing_arts/}}</ref><ref name=\"Location\">{{cite news|title=Location|publisher=Latlong.net|accessdate=25 June 2015|url=http://www.latlong.net/}}</ref> Faculty of Performing Arts was started by [[Omkarnath Thakur]] in 1950. It was initially instituted as a college called \"Music and Fine Arts\". In 1966, under Govind Malviya and founding principal Omkarnath Thakur, the college was restructured to a faculty, with three departments ([[Vocal music]], [[Instrumental music]] and [[Musicology]]). Faculty of Performing Arts claims to start the first department of Musicology in India headed by musicologists [[Prem Lata Sharma]].<ref name=\"Faculty of Performing Arts\"/>\n\n=== Faculty of Social Sciences ===\n[[File:Fss vasu.jpg|thumb|upright|Samanvaya Bhawan, Faculty of Social Sciences (Old PG Building) as seen from Faculty of Arts building]]\nThe Faculty of Social Sciences offers [[Undergraduate education#Indian system|undergraduate]] and [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] courses in [[Social science]]. It was bifurcated from the [[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Arts]] in 1971. It includes the departments of Economics, History, Political Science, Psychology and Sociology.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to \"Faculty of Social Sciences\"|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther than the departments, there are five centres which carry on the studies in various fields, namely the Centre for the Study of Nepal, Centre for Women's Study and Development, Centre for Integrated Rural Development, Centre for the Study of Social Exclusion and Inclusion Policy and the Malviya Centre for Peace Research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to \"Faculty of Social Sciences\"|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}} Click \"Centers\".</ref>\n\nThe faculty holds three chairs, the currently ({{as of|2018|lc=y}}) vacant Babu Jagjivan Ram Chair for Social Research, commemorating [[Jagjivan Ram]] and his contributions,<ref>{{cite web|title=Babu Jagjivan Ram Chair for Social Research (BJRC)|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/chair.php|website=bhu.ac.in|publisher=Banaras Hindu University, Faculty of Social Sciences Varanasi|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> the Dr. Ambedkar Chair for Nationalism & National Integration established in 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dr. B.R. Ambedkar Chair|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/ambedkar/|website=bhu.ac.in|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> and the Pt. Deendayal Upadhyay Chair, established in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pt. Deendayal Upadhyay Chair|url=http://bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/deendayal/|website=bhu.ac.in|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nFSS Connect, a project website for students was launched in 2018. Abhikalpan is the annual Youth Fest of Faculty of Social Sciences, BHU. In 2018, Innovation Unit for students, that is Innovision is under DIC, MIC-IIC BHU, Atal Incubation Centre and Media and Publishing Council of Students keep indulging students in a creative way. And every year FSS-BHU can see changes in inter-disciplinary and co-curricular activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=FSS Connect - Faculty of Social Sciences, BHU |url=https://www.fssconnect.org/home |website=fssconnect.org/ |publisher=Faculty of Social Sciences, BHU |accessdate= 31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty of Visual Arts ===\nThe Faculty of Visual Arts offers undergraduate and postgraduate courses in [[Applied arts|applied]] and [[visual arts]]. It was founded in 1916.<ref name=\"About Faculty\">{{cite news|title=About Faculty of Visual Arts|publisher=BHU website|accessdate=1 October 2015|url=http://bhu.ac.in/visualarts/}}</ref> It includes five departments:\n\n:*[[Painting]]\n:*[[Applied arts]]\n:*[[Plastic arts]]\n:*[[Pottery]] and [[Ceramics]]\n:*Textile designing\n\n==Inter-disciplinary schools==\n\n===School of Biotechnology===\n\n[[File:School of Biotechnology, Banaras Hindu University (BHU).jpg|thumb|School of Biotechnology, Faculty of Science, Banaras Hindu University]]\nThe School of Biotechnology (SBT) is a center for postgraduate teaching and research under the aegis of Institute of Science of the BHU.<ref>{{cite web|title=Home Page of Faculty of Science, BHU|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/science/index.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402213023/http://www.bhu.ac.in/science/index.html|archivedate=2 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=bhu-biotech>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/biotechnology/|title=About the department - School of Biotechnology, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609022459/http://www.bhu.ac.in/biotechnology/|archivedate=9 June 2012}}</ref> It was established in 1986 with funding from the [[Department of Biotechnology]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Human Resource Development, Department of Biotechnology, Government of India|url=http://dbtindia.nic.in/uniquepage.asp?id_pk=16#1|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124075204/http://dbtindia.nic.in/uniquepage.asp?id_pk=16#1|archivedate=24 November 2011}}</ref> of the Ministry of Science and Technology, [[Government of India]]. It offers MSc and PhD programmes in [[Biotechnology]].\n\nThe interdisciplinary program involves the partnership between the Institute of Science, the Institute of Medical Sciences and the Indian Institute of Technology at BHU. Notable faculty include [[Arvind Mohan Kayastha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/biotechnology/amkayastha.neraj|title=Lab web page of Prof. A. M. Kayastha, School of Biotechnology|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===DBT-BHU Interdisciplinary School of Life Sciences===\n\nThe Interdisciplinary School of Life Sciences (ISLS) is a joint initiative of the Department of Biotechnology (DBT), Government of India and the BHU. It was established with a grant of INR 238.9&nbsp;million from the DBT.<ref name=toi-lifesci>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-10-07/varanasi/28089134_1_life-sciences-bd-singh-dp-singh|title=Central grant to BHU for school of life sciences|publisher=The Times of India|date=7 October 2009|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===DST Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences===\n\nThe Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences (CIMS) focuses on research and education in mathematics, modelling and statistics. It was established under the management of the Faculty of Science, with support from the [[Department of Science and Technology (India)|Department of Science and Technology]] (DST).<ref name=bhu-cims>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/CIMS/|title=About us|publisher=DST Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619075814/http://www.bhu.ac.in/CIMS/|archivedate=19 June 2012}}</ref> The centre imparts post-graduate education and research with participation from the Department of Mathematics, Department of Statistics and Department of Computer Science of the Institute of Science and the Department of Applied Mathematics of the IIT-BHU. It regularly organises training programmes, workshops, Seminars and conferences.\n\n===Centre of Food Science and Technology===\n\nThe Centre of Food Science & Technology (CFST) is an inter-disciplinary research centre with collaboration between the Institute of Agricultural Sciences and the Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) focusing on food processing technology.<ref name=bhu-cfst>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/CFST/|title=Overview|publisher=Centre of Food Science & Technology, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Research centres==\nApart from specialised centres directly funded by DBT, DST, ICAR and ISRO, a large number of departments under the Institutes of Sciences, Engineering & Technology and Faculty of Social Sciences receive funding from the DST Fund for Improvement of Science & Technology Infrastructure (FIST) and the University Grants Commission (UGC) Special Assistance Programme (SAP). UGC SAP provides funds under its Centre of Advanced Study (CAS), Department of Special Assistance (DSA) and Departmental Research Support (DRS) programmes.<ref name=ugc-financial>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugc.ac.in/financialsupport/guideline_24.html|title=Financial Support: Special Assistance Programme (SAP)|publisher=University Grants Commission|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBHU research centres include:\n* DBT Centre of Genetic Disorders<ref name=\"bhu-cgd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/CGD/CGD%20website.htm|title=About CGD|publisher=Centre for Genetic Disorders, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511063704/http://www.bhu.ac.in/CGD/CGD%20website.htm|archivedate=11 May 2012}}</ref>\n* Center for Environmental Science and Technology<ref name=\"bhu-cest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/cest|title=Welcome|publisher=Centre for Environmental Science & Technology, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n* Nano science and Technology Center\n* Hydrogen Energy Center\n* UGC Advanced Immunodiagnostic Training and Research Center\n* Centre for Experimental Medicine and Surgery\n* Center for Women's Studies and Development (CWSD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cwsd/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215122712/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cwsd/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=CWSD}}</ref>\n* Center for the Study of Nepal (CNS)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/csn/|title=CSN|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* Malviya Center for Peace Research (MCPR)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/mcpr/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215123122/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/mcpr/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=MCPR}}</ref>\n* Center for Rural Integrated Development (CIRD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cird/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215171356/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/cird/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=CIRD}}</ref>\n* Centre for Study of Social Exclusion and Inclusive Policy (CSSEIP)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/csseip/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215122901/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/social_sciences/csseip/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 December 2018|title=CSSEIP}}</ref>\n* DST Centre for Interdisciplinary Mathematical Sciences\n\n== Affiliated colleges and schools ==\n\n===Colleges===\n\n[[File:Women's College, Banaras Hindu University, Varanasi.jpg|thumb|160px|[[Mahila Maha Vidyalaya]], Banaras Hindu University]]\n\n* [[Mahila Maha Vidyalaya]] (within main campus)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/mmv/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721172857/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/mmv/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2018|title=MMV}}</ref>\n* [[Arya Mahila Mahavidyalaya]]\n* [[DAV Post Graduate College]]\n* [[Vasanta College for Women]]\n* [[Vasant Kanya Mahavidyalaya]]\n\n===Schools===\n\n* Ranvir Sanskrit Vidyalaya,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ranvir/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723093419/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/ranvir/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2018|title=RSV}}</ref>\n* [[Central Hindu Boys School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/chs/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721172601/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/chs/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2018|title=CHS}}</ref> \n* [[Central Hindu Girls School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internet.bhu.ac.in/CHGS/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721173326/http://internet.bhu.ac.in/CHGS/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2018|title=CHGS}}</ref>\n\n==Library system==\n{{main|Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library, BHU}}\n[[File:Central Library BHU.jpg|thumb|200px|Central Library, BHU]]\nThe Banaras Hindu University Library system was established from a collection donated by P.K. Telang in the memory of his father Justice [[Kashinath Trimbak Telang]] in 1917. The collection was housed in the Telang Hall of the Central Hindu College, Kamachha. In 1921, the library was moved to the Central Hall of the Arts College (now the Faculty of Arts).\n\nThe present Central Library of BHU was established with a donation from Maharaja [[Sayajirao Gaekwad III]] of [[Baroda]]. Upon his return from the [[Round Table Conferences (India)|First round Table Conference]], Gaekwad wanted a library built on the pattern of the [[British Library]] and [[British Museum Reading Room|its reading room]], which was then located in the [[British Museum]]. On Malviya's suggestion, he made the donation to build the library on the BHU campus.<ref name=bhu-centrallibrary>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/bhulibrary/history.htm|title=Genesis and history|publisher=Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library, BHU|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Gaekwad Library is a designated ''Manuscript Conservation Centre'' (MCC) of the [[National Mission for Manuscripts]],<ref name=namami-mcc>{{cite web|url=http://www.namami.org/convervation.htm |title=Manuscript Conservation Centres |publisher=National Mission for Manuscripts |accessdate=4 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506234603/http://www.namami.org/convervation.htm |archivedate=6 May 2012 }}</ref> established in 2003.<ref name=namami-history>{{cite web|url=http://www.namami.org/history.htm|title=History|publisher=National Mission for Manuscripts|accessdate=4 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520182915/http://www.namami.org/history.htm|archivedate=20 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy 1931, the library had built a collection of around 60,000 volumes. The trend of donation of personal and family collection to the library continued as late as the 1940s with the result that it has unique pieces of rarities of books and journals dating back to the 18th century.\n\nAs of 2011, the BHU Library System consisted of the Central Library and 3 Institute Libraries, 8 Faculty Libraries and over 25 Departmental Libraries, with a collection of at least 1.3&nbsp;million volumes.<ref name=bhu-centrallibrary/> The digital library is available to students and staff and provides online access to thousands of journals, besides access to large collections of online resources<ref name=bhu-lib-services>{{cite web|url=http://bhu.ac.in/bhulibrary/services.htm|title=Library Services|publisher=Banaras Hindu University|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> through the [[National Informatics Centre]]'s DELNET<ref name=delnet>{{cite web|url=http://delnet.nic.in/|title=Developing Library Network|publisher=National Informatics Centre|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> and UGC's INFLIBNET.<ref name=inflibnet>{{cite web|url=http://www.inflibnet.ac.in/|title=Information and Library Network Centre|publisher=University Grants Commission|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Protests==\n{{main|Banaras Hindu University women's rights protest }}\nOn 21 September 2017 a woman reported sexual harassment to the university. She claimed that the university responded by blaming her.<ref name=\"Mishra October 2017\">{{cite web |last1=Mishra |first1=Bishnu |title=Student Protests Have Challenged the Ideological Stagnation of BHU |url=https://thewire.in/education/banaras-hindu-university-protests-2 |website=[[The Wire (Indian web publication)]] |date=2 October 2017}}</ref> The next day, 22 September, students organised a protest of the university's treatment of women.\n\nThe university's administration filed a First information report against hundreds of students. Security officers used violence in an attempt to get protesters to disperse. Various protesters reported injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=What is the BHU protest? everything you need to know |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/what-is/bhu-protest-police-lathicharge-video-sexual-harassment-molestation-4860135/ |website=The Indian Express |language=en-IN |date=25 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Admissions==\nBanaras Hindu University conducts national level undergraduate (UET) and postgraduate (PET) entrance tests usually during May\u2013June for admission for which registrations begin usually in February\u2013March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bhuonline.in/pdfs17/Notification-for-session2017-18.pdf|title=Application process|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Admissions are done according to merit in the entrance tests, subject to fulfilling of other eligibility requirements.  Admissions to BTech/B.Pharm., MTech/M.Pharm. are done through JEE and GATE respectively. Admission to MBA and MBA-IB are done through IIM-CAT score and also through separate BHU-MBA entrance tests. Admissions for PhD are done on the basis of either qualification of [[National Eligibility Test]] (NET) by the candidates or through the scores of CRET (Common Research Entrance Test). Admissions in [[Institute of Medical Sciences, Banaras Hindu University|IMS]] are done through PMT exam.\n \nBHU attracts a number of foreign learners. Foreign students are admitted through the application submitted to the Indian mission in his/her country or by his/her country's mission in India.\n\nBHU conducts UG entrance exam every year in May. The offline exam is held for 5166 seats. The total exam duration is two hours with 150 MCQs and the total marks is 450. There are seven participating colleges including BHU Faculty of Law and six constituent colleges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://university.careers360.com/articles/bhu-uet|title=BHU UET 2019 \u2013 Check Results, Cut Off, Scorecard, Merit List, Counselling|website=university.careers360.com}}</ref>\n\n==Halls of residence==\n\nBHU is a fully residential University with a total of 62 hostels - 41 hostels for male and 21 hostels for female students.\n\nThere are four separate hostels for international students. These four include an International House Annexe for female students with an intake capacity of 24. Hostels are named after several historically important figures such as [[Kumaramangalam Birla]], [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]], [[Rani Laxmibai]] and [[M. Visvesvaraya]].\n\n==Festivals==\nBHU observes [[Saraswati]] puja day (also known as [[Vasant Panchami]]) as its foundation day. Goddess [[Saraswati]] is the Hindu goddess of knowledge, music, arts, wisdom and nature. She is a part of the trinity of [[Saraswati]], [[Lakshmi]] and [[Parvati]].\n\nThere is also a festival called SPANDAN (Inter university youth festival). Students represent their faculty/institute in various arts competition like literature (writing essay, poem, debates), painting, sketches, vocal music, dancing, singing, drama, and mimicry. It is held every year after Vasant Panchami in month of February or March.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n| type = University\n<!----------International---------->\n| QS_W_2020 = 801-1000\n| QS_A_2019 = 156\n| QS_BRICS_2019 = 90\n| THE_W_2020 = 601-800\n| THES_A_2019 = 140\n|THES_E_2019 = 134\n<!----------General---------->\n| NIRF_U_2019 = 3\n| NIRF_O_2019 = 10\n<!----------Engineering---------->\n| NIRF_E_2019 = 11\n| WEEK_E_2019 = 9\n<!----------Law---------->\n| OUTLOOK_L_2018 = 6\n| WEEK_L_2019 = 7\n<!----------Medical---------->\n| IT_M_2018 = 7\n| OUTLOOK_M_2018 = 8\n| WEEK_M_2019 = 6\n<!----------Management---------->\n| NIRF_B_2019 = 39\n}}\nInternationally, BHU was ranked 801-1000 in the [[QS World University Rankings]] of 2020.<ref name=Rankings_QS_W_2020/> The same rankings ranked it 156 in Asia<ref name=Rankings_QS_A_2019/> and 90 among [[BRICS]] nations in 2019.<ref name=Rankings_QS_BRICS_2019/> It was ranked 601-800 in the world by the ''[[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]]'' of 2020<ref name=Rankings_THE_W_2020/> and 140 in Asia in 2019.<ref name=Rankings_THES_A_2019/>\n\nIn India, the [[National Institutional Ranking Framework]] (NIRF) ranked it tenth overall in 2019<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_O_2019/> and third among universities.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_U_2019/> It also ranked it 39 in the management ranking.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_B_2019/>\n\nIts engineering institute, [[IIT (BHU)|IIT]], was ranked 11 by the NIRF Engineering ranking for 2019.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_E_2019 /> In 2019, it was ranked 9th among engineering colleges in India by ''[[The Week (Indian magazine)|The Week]]''.<ref name=Rankings_WEEK_E_2019 />\n\nThe [[Faculty of Law, Banaras Hindu University]] was ranked sixth in India by ''[[Outlook India]]''{{'}}s  \"Top 25 Law Colleges in 2018\"<ref name=Rankings_OUTLOOK_L_2018/> and seventh in India by ''[[The Week (Indian magazine)|The Week]]''{{'}}s \"Top Law Colleges 2019\".<ref name=Rankings_WEEK_L_2019/>\n\nThe [[Institute of Medical Sciences, Banaras Hindu University]] was ranked seventh among medical colleges in India in 2018 by ''[[India Today]]'',<ref name=Rankings_IT_M_2018 /> sixth by ''[[The Week (Indian magazine)|The Week]]''<ref name=Rankings_WEEK_M_2019 /> and eight by ''[[Outlook India]]''.<ref name=Rankings_OUTLOOK_M_2018 />\n\n==Awards and medals==\nThe following awards and medals are given to meritorious students in BHU:\n\n* BHU Medal is given to students who secure the first position in their respective departments or faculties.\n[[File:BHU Medal for meritorious students.png|50px]]\n\n==Notable alumni, faculty and staff==\n{{alumni|date=June 2017}}\n{{main|List of Banaras Hindu University people|List of Vice-Chancellors of Banaras Hindu University}}\n\nAlumni and faculty of BHU have gained prominence in India and across the world. Among BHU's administrators was [[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]], who went on to become the [[President of India]]. Other famous administrators include [[Sir Sunder Lal]], [[K. L. Shrimali]], [[Moti Lal Dhar]].\n\nThe university's alumni include [[Raj Narain]], [[Rakhaldas Bandyopadhyay]], [[C.N.R Rao]], [[Madhav Sadashiv Golwalkar]], [[Harivansh Rai Bachchan]], [[Bhupen Hazarika]], [[Shyam Sunder Surolia]], [[Veena Pandey]], [[A. K. Narain]], [[Kamalesh Chandra Chakrabarty]], [[Ashok Agarwal]], [[Jagdish Kashyap]], [[T. V. Ramakrishnan]], [[Harkishan Singh]], [[Narla Tata Rao]], [[Patcha Ramachandra Rao]], [[Jayant Vishnu Narlikar]], [[Basanti Dulal Nagchaudhuri]], [[Ahmad Hasan Dani]], [[Kota Harinarayana]], [[Kothapalli Jayashankar]], [[Krishan Kant]], [[Manick Sorcar]], [[Satish K. Tripathi]], [[Shashi P. Karna]] and [[Prem Saran Satsangi]]. Amongst its famous international students are [[Robert M. Pirsig]] and [[Koenraad Elst]].\n\nBHU's faculty have included [[Ganesh Prasad]], [[Birbal Sahni]], [[Shanti Swaroop Bhatnagar]], [[Prafulla Kumar Jena]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.iates.org.in/BIODATA_AND_ACHIEVEMENTS%20OF%20PROF%20DR.%20P.%20K.%20JENA.pdf | title=Institute of Advanced Technology and Environmental Studies profile | publisher=Institute of Advanced Technology and Environmental Studies | date=2015 | accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> [[Omkarnath Thakur]], [[N. Rajam]] and [[A. K. Narain]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mahatma Gandhi Kashi Vidyapith]]\n*[[Aligarh Muslim University]]\n{{Portal bar|India|Education}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Leah Renold, ''A Hindu Education: Early Years Of The Banaras Hindu University'' (Oxford University Press).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Banaras_Hindu_University|Banaras Hindu University}}\n* {{official|http://bhu.ac.in}}\n\n{{Banaras Hindu University}}\n{{Varanasi}}\n{{Normdaten}}\n\n[[Category:Banaras Hindu University| ]]\n[[Category:Hindu universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Central universities in India]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Varanasi]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1916]]\n[[Category:1916 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Madan Mohan Malaviya]]\n[[Category:Universities in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Donations by Nizams of Hyderabad]]\n", "name_user": "Seomelono", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banaras_Hindu_University"}
{"title_page": "Leafield", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|official_name= Leafield\n|static_image_name= Leafield StMichael WestFront.JPG\n|static_image_caption= St Michael's parish church\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.839|-1.545|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference= SP3115\n|label_position= bottom\n|population= 945\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|civil_parish= Leafield\n|shire_district= [[West Oxfordshire]]\n|shire_county= [[Oxfordshire]]\n|region= South East England\n|country= England\n|post_town= [[Witney]]\n|postcode_area= OX\n|postcode_district= OX29\n|dial_code= 01993\n|constituency_westminster= [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]] \n|website= [http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/ Leafield Village]\n}}\n'''Leafield''' is a village and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] about {{convert|4|mi}} northwest of [[Witney]] in [[West Oxfordshire]]. The parish includes the [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of '''Langley''', {{convert|1|mi}} west of Leafield village. The [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] recorded the parish's population as 945.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11125507&c=Leafield&d=16&e=62&g=6460027&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1418408154062&enc=1 |title=Area: Leafield (Parish): Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics |work=[[Neighbourhood Statistics]] |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe village is {{convert|635|ft|m}} above sea level in the [[Cotswolds|Cotswold Hills]]. It was the highest point in Oxfordshire until the [[Local Government Act 1972|1974 county boundary changes]] enlarged the county.\n\n==Archaeology==\nThere are a number of [[Tumulus|tumuli]] in the parish, including Leafield Barrow, locally called Barry's Hill Tump, on top of the hill just to the north of the village.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://historicoxfordshire.ashmolean.org/SitePages/leafield.html |title=Site Name: Leafield |work=Oxfordshire's Historic Archives |publisher=[[Ashmolean Museum]] |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nLeafield Barrow also has archaeological evidence for being the site of a Medieval Motte and Bailey Castle. <ref>{{cite web |url= https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1008405|title=Site Name: Leafield |work=Historic England Listings |publisher=[[Historic England]]     |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe parish is within the former limits of the [[Wychwood]] forest. The area of forest south of Langley was cleared in 1857\u201358, leaving straight, regular field boundaries typical of the 18th and 19th century [[enclosure]]s.{{sfn|Taylor|1975|p=145\u2013146}}\n[[File:Leafield PreachingCross.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Gothic Revival preaching cross on medieval steps and base]]\nThe village has the remains of a [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[preaching cross]].{{sfn|Marples|1973|p=307}} The steps and lower part of its base are old.{{sfn|Marples|1973|p=307}} A new [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] shaft and top were added in 1873 in thanksgiving for the village escaping a [[smallpox]] epidemic.{{sfn|Marples|1973|p=307}}\n\n[[James VI and I|King James I]] stayed at Langley in August 1605.<ref>John Nichols, ''The Progresses, Processions, and Magnificent Festivities, of King James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1828), p. 529.</ref>\n\nLeafield was a dependent chapelry of the [[ecclesiastical parish]] of [[Shipton-under-Wychwood]] until the 19th century. Leafield's [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Michael (archangel)|Saint Michael]] and All Angels was designed by Sir [[George Gilbert Scott]], built in 1859 and consecrated in 1860. The [[bell tower]] was completed in 1874{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=682}} and has a [[Change ringing|ring]] of six bells, all cast that year by [[John Taylor & Co]] of [[Loughborough]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Davies |first=Peter |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Leafield&numPerPage=10&Submit=Go&searchAmount=%3D&searchMetric=cwt&sortBy=Place&sortDir=Asc&DoveID=LEAFIELD |title=Leafield S Michael & All Angels |author= |date=7 January 2009 |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher= |accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref> St. Michael's is now a member of the Forest Edge [[Benefice#Church of England|Benefice]].<ref>[http://www.forestedgebenefice.co.uk/churches/leafield.htm Forest Edge Benefice: Leafield with Wychwood]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nLeafield Church of England Primary School opened in 1839.<ref name=SchoolPast>{{cite web |url=http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/school_past.html |title=School Past |author= |date=2010 |work=Leafield Village |publisher= |accessdate=27 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130421035442/http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/school_past.html |archivedate=21 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was expanded by the building of additional classrooms in 1871, 1897 and 1904.<ref name=SchoolPast/> The 1871 classroom was designed by the architect [[Clapton Crabb Rolfe|C.C. Rolfe]].{{sfn|Saint|1970|p=98}} Leafield's school district was expanded in 1873 to include [[Asthall]], Langley and [[Wychwood]].<ref name=SchoolPast/> Leafield C of E School resisted [[Oxfordshire County Council]]'s attempts to reorganise it as a junior school until after the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref name=SchoolPast/> The school's catchment area was expanded in 1986 to include [[Ascott-under-Wychwood]].<ref name=SchoolPast/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Leafield Technical Centre==\n{{main|Leafield Technical Centre}}\nA large radio transmission station was sited at Langley from 1912 until 1986.<ref name=TechCent>{{cite web |url=http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/bt_radio_station.html |title=The BT Radio Station |author= |date=2010 |work=Leafield Village |publisher= |accessdate=27 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130114030323/http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/bt_radio_station.html |archivedate=14 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[BT Group|British Telecom]] redeveloped the site as a training college, but then closed the site in 1993.<ref name=TechCent/> It was then used by [[Tom Walkinshaw Racing]] (TWR) as a motorsport development centre for the [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]] [[Formula One]] team,<ref name=TechCent/> until the team's demise in the [[2002 Formula One season|2002 season]]. From the [[2006 Formula One season|2006 season]] until the [[2008 Formula One season|2008 season]] Leafield Technical Centre was the headquarters of the now-defunct [[Super Aguri F1]] team.\n\nMenard Competition Technologies is now based at Leafield Technical Centre.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mctuk.com/ |title=Menard Competition Technologies (MCT) |access-date=27 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206155801/http://www.mctuk.com/ |archive-date=6 February 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> MCT has made the engines for [[Norton Motorcycle#Replicas and revival|Norton Motorcycles']] range of [[Norton Commando#New Commando in production|Commando 961]] models<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nortonmotorcycles.com/news/?p=54 |title=MCT powers the re-birth of Norton |author= |date=2009 |work=News |publisher=[[Norton Motorcycle#Replicas and revival|Norton Motorcycles]] |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref> since 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Production of Norton Engines Starts at Leafield |author= |url=http://www.witneygazette.co.uk/news/wgheadlines/witney/4371991.Production_of_Norton_engines_starts_at_Leafield/ |newspaper=[[The Oxford Times|Witney Gazette]] |date=15 May 2009 |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012 [[Caterham F1]] announced that they would be moving to Leafield from their original base at [[Hingham, Norfolk]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/97073 |last=Elizalde |first=Pablo |work=[[Autosport]] |date=12 January 2012 |title=Caterham F1 team confirms proposed move to Leafield |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Amenities==\n[[File:Leafield TheFox.JPG|thumb|The Fox public house]]\nLeafield has two [[public house]]s: The Fox and The Pearl. The Fox was closed for 15 months after [[Greene King Brewery]] shut it in January 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/9610882.Future_s_bright_for_reopened_village_pub/ |last=Jennings |first=Tom |date=26 March 2012 |title=Future's bright for reopened village pub |newspaper=[[Oxford Mail]] |publisher=[[Newsquest]] |accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> An independent lessee reopened it in April 2011<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/8978112.Prime_Minister_pops_in_for_a_pint_to_toast_reopened_pub/?ref=rss |last=Jennings |first=Tom |date=17 April 2011 |title=Prime Minister pops in for a pint to toast reopened pub |newspaper=Oxford Mail |publisher=Newsquest |accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> and it is now a free house.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxleafield.co.uk/default.html |title=The Fox Inn Leafield |access-date=12 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213014423/http://www.foxleafield.co.uk/default.html |archive-date=13 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Pearl used to be the Spindleberry and is now a Chinese restaurant, takeaway and bar.<ref>[http://thepearlleafield.co.uk/ The Pearl at Leafield] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218180200/http://thepearlleafield.co.uk/ |date=18 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Wychwood Way]], a {{convert|37|mi}} circular walking trail, passes through Leafield Lower End.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite journal |last=Marples |first=B.J. |year=1973 |title=The Medieval Crosses of Oxfordshire |journal=[[Oxoniensia]] |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society]] |volume=XXXVIII |page=307 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Saint |first=Andrew |year=1970 |title=Three Oxford Architects |journal=[[Oxoniensia]] |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society|Oxford Architectural and Historical Society]] |volume=XXXV |page=98 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Sherwood |first1=Jennifer |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Oxfordshire |year=1974 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |isbn=0-14-071045-0 |page=682 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Taylor |first=Christopher |authorlink= |title=Fields in the English Landscape |series=Archaeology in the Field Series |origyear=1975 |year=1982 |publisher=[[J.M. Dent]] & Sons Ltd |location=London |isbn=0-460-02232-6 |pages=145\u2013146 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Leafield}}\n\n{{West Oxfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Villages in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:West Oxfordshire District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|official_name= Leafield\n|static_image_name= Leafield StMichael WestFront.JPG\n|static_image_caption= St Michael's parish church\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.839|-1.545|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference= SP3115\n|label_position= bottom\n|population= 945\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|civil_parish= Leafield\n|shire_district= [[West Oxfordshire]]\n|shire_county= [[Oxfordshire]]\n|region= South East England\n|country= England\n|post_town= [[Witney]]\n|postcode_area= OX\n|postcode_district= OX29\n|dial_code= 01993\n|constituency_westminster= [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]] \n|website= [http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/ Leafield Village]\n}}\n'''Leafield''' is a village and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] about {{convert|4|mi}} northwest of [[Witney]] in [[West Oxfordshire]]. The parish includes the [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of '''Langley''', {{convert|1|mi}} west of Leafield village. The [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]] recorded the parish's population as 945.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11125507&c=Leafield&d=16&e=62&g=6460027&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1418408154062&enc=1 |title=Area: Leafield (Parish): Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics |work=[[Neighbourhood Statistics]] |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe village is {{convert|635|ft|m}} above sea level in the [[Cotswolds|Cotswold Hills]]. It was the highest point in Oxfordshire until the [[Local Government Act 1972|1974 county boundary changes]] enlarged the county.\n\n==Archaeology==\nThere are a number of [[Tumulus|tumuli]] in the parish, including Leafield Barrow, locally called Barry's Hill Tump, on top of the hill just to the north of the village.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://historicoxfordshire.ashmolean.org/SitePages/leafield.html |title=Site Name: Leafield |work=Oxfordshire's Historic Archives |publisher=[[Ashmolean Museum]] |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe parish is within the former limits of the [[Wychwood]] forest. The area of forest south of Langley was cleared in 1857\u201358, leaving straight, regular field boundaries typical of the 18th and 19th century [[enclosure]]s.{{sfn|Taylor|1975|p=145\u2013146}}\n[[File:Leafield PreachingCross.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Gothic Revival preaching cross on medieval steps and base]]\nThe village has the remains of a [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[preaching cross]].{{sfn|Marples|1973|p=307}} The steps and lower part of its base are old.{{sfn|Marples|1973|p=307}} A new [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] shaft and top were added in 1873 in thanksgiving for the village escaping a [[smallpox]] epidemic.{{sfn|Marples|1973|p=307}}\n\n[[James VI and I|King James I]] stayed at Langley in August 1605.<ref>John Nichols, ''The Progresses, Processions, and Magnificent Festivities, of King James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1828), p. 529.</ref>\n\nLeafield was a dependent chapelry of the [[ecclesiastical parish]] of [[Shipton-under-Wychwood]] until the 19th century. Leafield's [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Michael (archangel)|Saint Michael]] and All Angels was designed by Sir [[George Gilbert Scott]], built in 1859 and consecrated in 1860. The [[bell tower]] was completed in 1874{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=682}} and has a [[Change ringing|ring]] of six bells, all cast that year by [[John Taylor & Co]] of [[Loughborough]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Davies |first=Peter |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Leafield&numPerPage=10&Submit=Go&searchAmount=%3D&searchMetric=cwt&sortBy=Place&sortDir=Asc&DoveID=LEAFIELD |title=Leafield S Michael & All Angels |author= |date=7 January 2009 |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher= |accessdate=30 December 2010}}</ref> St. Michael's is now a member of the Forest Edge [[Benefice#Church of England|Benefice]].<ref>[http://www.forestedgebenefice.co.uk/churches/leafield.htm Forest Edge Benefice: Leafield with Wychwood]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nLeafield Church of England Primary School opened in 1839.<ref name=SchoolPast>{{cite web |url=http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/school_past.html |title=School Past |author= |date=2010 |work=Leafield Village |publisher= |accessdate=27 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130421035442/http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/school_past.html |archivedate=21 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was expanded by the building of additional classrooms in 1871, 1897 and 1904.<ref name=SchoolPast/> The 1871 classroom was designed by the architect [[Clapton Crabb Rolfe|C.C. Rolfe]].{{sfn|Saint|1970|p=98}} Leafield's school district was expanded in 1873 to include [[Asthall]], Langley and [[Wychwood]].<ref name=SchoolPast/> Leafield C of E School resisted [[Oxfordshire County Council]]'s attempts to reorganise it as a junior school until after the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref name=SchoolPast/> The school's catchment area was expanded in 1986 to include [[Ascott-under-Wychwood]].<ref name=SchoolPast/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Leafield Technical Centre==\n{{main|Leafield Technical Centre}}\nA large radio transmission station was sited at Langley from 1912 until 1986.<ref name=TechCent>{{cite web |url=http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/bt_radio_station.html |title=The BT Radio Station |author= |date=2010 |work=Leafield Village |publisher= |accessdate=27 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130114030323/http://www.leafieldvillage.co.uk/bt_radio_station.html |archivedate=14 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[BT Group|British Telecom]] redeveloped the site as a training college, but then closed the site in 1993.<ref name=TechCent/> It was then used by [[Tom Walkinshaw Racing]] (TWR) as a motorsport development centre for the [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]] [[Formula One]] team,<ref name=TechCent/> until the team's demise in the [[2002 Formula One season|2002 season]]. From the [[2006 Formula One season|2006 season]] until the [[2008 Formula One season|2008 season]] Leafield Technical Centre was the headquarters of the now-defunct [[Super Aguri F1]] team.\n\nMenard Competition Technologies is now based at Leafield Technical Centre.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mctuk.com/ |title=Menard Competition Technologies (MCT) |access-date=27 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206155801/http://www.mctuk.com/ |archive-date=6 February 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> MCT has made the engines for [[Norton Motorcycle#Replicas and revival|Norton Motorcycles']] range of [[Norton Commando#New Commando in production|Commando 961]] models<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nortonmotorcycles.com/news/?p=54 |title=MCT powers the re-birth of Norton |author= |date=2009 |work=News |publisher=[[Norton Motorcycle#Replicas and revival|Norton Motorcycles]] |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref> since 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Production of Norton Engines Starts at Leafield |author= |url=http://www.witneygazette.co.uk/news/wgheadlines/witney/4371991.Production_of_Norton_engines_starts_at_Leafield/ |newspaper=[[The Oxford Times|Witney Gazette]] |date=15 May 2009 |accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012 [[Caterham F1]] announced that they would be moving to Leafield from their original base at [[Hingham, Norfolk]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/97073 |last=Elizalde |first=Pablo |work=[[Autosport]] |date=12 January 2012 |title=Caterham F1 team confirms proposed move to Leafield |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Amenities==\n[[File:Leafield TheFox.JPG|thumb|The Fox public house]]\nLeafield has two [[public house]]s: The Fox and The Pearl. The Fox was closed for 15 months after [[Greene King Brewery]] shut it in January 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/9610882.Future_s_bright_for_reopened_village_pub/ |last=Jennings |first=Tom |date=26 March 2012 |title=Future's bright for reopened village pub |newspaper=[[Oxford Mail]] |publisher=[[Newsquest]] |accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> An independent lessee reopened it in April 2011<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/8978112.Prime_Minister_pops_in_for_a_pint_to_toast_reopened_pub/?ref=rss |last=Jennings |first=Tom |date=17 April 2011 |title=Prime Minister pops in for a pint to toast reopened pub |newspaper=Oxford Mail |publisher=Newsquest |accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> and it is now a free house.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxleafield.co.uk/default.html |title=The Fox Inn Leafield |access-date=12 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213014423/http://www.foxleafield.co.uk/default.html |archive-date=13 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Pearl used to be the Spindleberry and is now a Chinese restaurant, takeaway and bar.<ref>[http://thepearlleafield.co.uk/ The Pearl at Leafield] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218180200/http://thepearlleafield.co.uk/ |date=18 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Wychwood Way]], a {{convert|37|mi}} circular walking trail, passes through Leafield Lower End.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite journal |last=Marples |first=B.J. |year=1973 |title=The Medieval Crosses of Oxfordshire |journal=[[Oxoniensia]] |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society]] |volume=XXXVIII |page=307 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Saint |first=Andrew |year=1970 |title=Three Oxford Architects |journal=[[Oxoniensia]] |publisher=[[Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society|Oxford Architectural and Historical Society]] |volume=XXXV |page=98 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Sherwood |first1=Jennifer |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Oxfordshire |year=1974 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |isbn=0-14-071045-0 |page=682 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Taylor |first=Christopher |authorlink= |title=Fields in the English Landscape |series=Archaeology in the Field Series |origyear=1975 |year=1982 |publisher=[[J.M. Dent]] & Sons Ltd |location=London |isbn=0-460-02232-6 |pages=145\u2013146 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Leafield}}\n\n{{West Oxfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Villages in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:West Oxfordshire District]]\n", "name_user": "Freddie Gray", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArchaeology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leafield"}
{"title_page": "HIV/AIDS in Asia", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expert needed|Medicine|date=November 2008}}\n[[Image:People living with HIV AIDS world map.PNG|thumb|400px|People living with HIV/AIDS ([[World Factbook|CIA]]), in absolute numbers for the year of 2008. Large numbers of people live with HIV even in countries with relatively low HIV prevalence levels.]]\n[[File:AIDS and HIV prevalence 2008.svg|thumb|400px|Estimated prevalence in % of HIV among young adults (15\u201349) per country as of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=AIDSinfo|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/dataanalysis/datatools/aidsinfo/|work=UNAIDS|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2008, 4.7 million people in [[Asia]] were living with [[HIV]] according to the [[United Nations]] (UN).<ref name=\"unaids.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Regions/default.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702230305/http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Regions/default.asp |archivedate=2010-07-02 }}</ref> The UN believes that Asia's epidemic peaked in the mid-1990s, and annual HIV incidence has subsequently declined by more than half.<ref name=\"unaids.org\"/> Regionally, the epidemic has remained somewhat stable since 2000.<ref name=\"unaids.org\"/>\n\n==South Asia==\nCompared with other regions, notably Africa and the Americas, the national HIV prevalence levels in South Asia are very low (0.3% in the adult (15-49) group). However, due to the large populations of many South Asian nations, this low national HIV prevalence still means that large numbers of people are living with HIV.\n\nIn South Asia, the HIV epidemic remains largely concentrated in [[injecting drug user]]s, [[men who have sex with men]], [[sex workers]], and clients of sex workers and their immediate sexual partners. Prevention strategies in these populations are, for the most part, inadequate.\n\n===Bangladesh===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Bangladesh}}\nWith less than 0.1 percent of the population estimated to be HIV-positive, Bangladesh is a low HIV-prevalence country. [[UNAIDS]] estimates the number of people living with HIV in the country to be at 11,000 people.<ref name=usaid>[http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/bangladesh_profile.pdf \"Health Profile: Bangladesh\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817052600/http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/bangladesh_profile.pdf |date=17 August 2008 }}. [[United States Agency for International Development]] (March 2008). Accessed 25 August 2008. {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n===Bhutan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Bhutan}}\nIn 2011, there were 246 reported cases of [[HIV]] in [[Bhutan]], representing just over 0.03% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhutanobserver.bt/ministry-health-detected/ |title=The Ministry of Health has Detected\u2026 |publisher=[[Bhutan Observer]] online |date=2011-08-01 |accessdate=2011-11-21}}</ref> However Health Ministry sources indicated actual numbers were estimated at more than 500 by [[UNAIDS]].<ref name=update>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.gov.bt/doph/cdd/update_HIV2010.pdf |format=PDF |title=An Update on Human Immuno Deficiency Virus/Acquired Immuno Deficiency Syndrome (HIV/AIDS) |date=2010-07-01 |accessdate=2011-11-22 |publisher=Bhutan Ministry of Health |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508032703/http://www.health.gov.bt/doph/cdd/update_HIV2010.pdf |archivedate=2012-05-08 }}</ref>\n\n===India===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in India}}\nThe [[National AIDS Control Organisation|NACO]] estimated that 2.11 million people live with HIV/AIDS in India in 2015.<ref name=\"naco\">{{cite web |url=http://nacoonline.org/upload/REPORTS/NACO%20Annual%20Report%202010-11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020144705/http://nacoonline.org/upload/REPORTS/NACO%20Annual%20Report%202010-11.pdf |archive-date=20 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> India has the third largest number of people with HIV after South Africa and Nigeria.<ref name=\"CIA1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/364rank.html|website=The World Factbook\u2014Central Intelligence Agency|title=Country comparison: people living with HIV/AIDS|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Despite being home to the world's third-largest population suffering from HIV/AIDS (as of 2018, with South Africa and Nigeria having more),<ref name=\"CIA1\"/> the AIDS prevalence rate in India is lower than in many other countries. In 2016, India's AIDS prevalence rate stood at approximately 0.30%\u2014the 80th highest in the world.<ref name=\"CIA2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2155rank.html|website=The World Factbook\u2014Central Intelligence Agency|title=Country comparison AIDS/HIV prevalence|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Nepal}}\n[[UNAIDS]] estimates from 2007 indicate that approximately 75,000 people in Nepal are HIV-positive, including all age groups. The Government of Nepal's National Center for AIDS & STD Control (NCASC) estimated that number to be closer to 70,000 in December 2007. In a study from 2014, an overall national HIV prevalence was 0.20% (adult male 0.28%, adult female 0.13%). According to UNAIDS, by the end of 2015, the number of people living with [[HIV]] was 39,000 [34,000 - 46,000]<ref name=usaid/> NCASC (2010) reports that estimated number of HIV infections by risk groups is 59,984.<ref>[http://www.ncasc.gov.np/]</ref><ref name=UNAIDS/>\n\n===Pakistan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Pakistan}}\nThe National AIDS Program's latest figures show that by the mid of first decade in new millennium, the number of HIV cases have increased to approximately 0,102 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nacp.gov.pk/|title=National AIDS Control Programme|website=www.nacp.gov.pk}}</ref> This number was estimated little over 4,000, as the HIV cases reported since 1986. The UN and government estimated the number of HIV/AIDS cases around 97,000 ranging from a lowest estimate of 46,000 to a highest estimate of 210,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aids.gov.br/data/documents/storedDocuments/%7BB8EF5DAF-23AE-4891-AD36-1903553A3174%7D/%7BFD4B5F2E-FB97-4749-BDA2-1C2360F59870%7D/2007_epiupdate_en.pdf |title=UNAIDS Epidemic update 2007 |accessdate=June 14, 2008 |archive-date=October 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002144331/http://www.aids.gov.br/data/documents/storedDocuments/%7BB8EF5DAF-23AE-4891-AD36-1903553A3174%7D/%7BFD4B5F2E-FB97-4749-BDA2-1C2360F59870%7D/2007_epiupdate_en.pdf |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> More realistic estimates that are based on actual [[surveillance]] figures, however, suggest that this number may be closer to 40,000\u201345,000. The overall [[prevalence]] of HIV infection in adults aged 15 to 49 is 0.1%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacp.gov.pk/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/pakistan_2008_country_progress_report_en.pdf |title=Pakistan UNGASS Report 2007 |accessdate=June 14, 2008 |archive-date=October 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002144338/http://www.nacp.gov.pk/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/pakistan_2008_country_progress_report_en.pdf |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> (0.05% if one accepts the lower estimates).\n\n===Sri Lanka===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Sri Lanka}}\n\n==East Asia==\nCompared with other regions, notably Africa and the Americas, the national HIV prevalence levels in [[East Asia]] are very low (0.1% in the adult (15-49) group). However, due to the large populations of many East Asian nations, this low national HIV prevalence still means that large numbers of people are living with HIV.\n\n===China===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in the People's Republic of China}}\n[[File:ChinaHIVAIDSmap.svg|thumb|Cases of HIV in Chinese provinces by December 2005; high number of cases near Eastern and Western borders.]]\nMuch of the current spread of HIV in the [[People's Republic of China]] is through intravenous [[drug abuse]] and [[paid sex]]. <!-- Citation needed --> In the rural areas, especially in [[Henan]] province, large numbers of farmers participated in contaminated [[blood transfusion]]s; estimates of those infected are in the tens of thousands.\n\n===Japan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Japan}}\n[http://api-net.jfap.or.jp/mhw/survey/mhw_survey.htm Official figures] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20081213003434/http://www.japanetwork.org/aidsnews/stats/06jul-sep.html English]) for July\u2013October 2006 showed that just over half of domestic HIV/AIDS cases were among [[homosexuality|homosexual men]], with the remainder transmitted through heterosexual intercourse, [[drug abuse]], [[perinatal|in the womb]] or via unknown means. As of 2015, there have been a total of 17,909 HIV and 8,086 AIDS cases reported in Japan since 1985. [https://www.niid.go.jp/niid/en/iasr-vol33-e/865-iasr/6775-439te.html IASR 37(9)\u30012016\u3010TOPIC\u3011HIV/AIDS in Japan, 2015]\n\n===North Korea===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in North Korea}}\nAccording to UNAIDS, less than 0.2% of [[North Korea]]'s adult population has HIV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.unaids.org/pub/Report/2006/2006_gr_en.pdf#342 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208200442/http://data.unaids.org/pub/Report/2006/2006_gr_en.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-12-08 |title=2006 Report on the global AIDS epidemic : A UNAIDS 10th anniversary special edition |date=2006 |publisher=UNAIDS |page=343 |access-date=7 December 2015 }}</ref> WHO estimates that North Korea has less than 100 people with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.searo.who.int/PDS_DOCS/B0367.pdf |title=Young People and HIV/AIDS : Fact Sheet : DPR Korea |date=20 November 2006 |publisher=Regional Office for South East Asia, World Health Organization |access-date=7 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208142659/http://apps.searo.who.int/PDS_DOCS/B0367.pdf |archivedate=8 December 2015 }}</ref> Officially, the country maintains that it is completely free of AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web | title = North Korea fights AIDS | publisher= ABC Radio National | last=O'Byrne|first=Tom| date = 2 December 2001 | accessdate = 2015-12-08 | url = http://www.abc.net.au/correspondents/s430901.htm }}</ref>\n\n===South Korea===\nSouth Korea cumulative ''reported'' cases of HIV surpassed 6,000, and 797 reported in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kaisernetwork.org/daily_reports/rep_index.cfm?DR_ID=56908|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090623135428/http://www.kaisernetwork.org/daily_reports/rep_index.cfm?DR_ID=56908|url-status=dead|title=KaiserNetwork: Korea cases|archivedate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention'', the prevalence of HIV in South Korea is rising. The first case of HIV was in 1985 <ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/29/6/1524/307521 |jstor=4482066|title=Spectrum of Opportunistic Infections and Malignancies in Patients with Human Immunodeficiency Virus Infection in South Korea|last=Oh|first=Myoung-don|date=December 1999}}</ref> In 2000, the number of people diagnosed with HIV was 219, and has risen to 797 diagnoses in 2008.<ref name=\"bmc\">{{Cite web|url=https://bmcpublichealth.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1471-2458-10-411|title=Increasing Late Diagnosis in Hiv Infection in South Korea: 2000-2007|last=Lee|first=Jin-Hee|date=December 2009|website=BIO MED CENTRAL|accessdate=}}</ref> Males were found to have a much higher infection rate.<ref name=\"bmc\"/> In order to prevent Korean women from contracting HIV, HIV positive males should be detected early on.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/40542225?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents |jstor=40542225|title=Epidemiological Characteristics of HIV-Infected Women in the Republic of Korea: A Low HIV Prevalence Country|last=Lee|first=Jin-Hee|date=September 2009}}</ref> The most common transmission mode in South Korea is through heterosexual sexual contacts, because homosexuality is uncommon and socially unacceptable.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nDue to the lower prevalence of HIV in South Korea, the Korean media has represented HIV as a disease brought to Korea by foreigners from other countries.<ref name=\"Cheng 2004\">{{cite web |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4065354?seq=1 |jstor=4065354|title=Interrogating the Absence of HIV/AIDS Interventions for Migrant Sex Workers in South Korea|last=Cheng|first=Sealing|date=2004}}</ref> The Korean government has created policies to incorporate these ideas. Any foreigners who plan to stay in South Korea must test for HIV, and if results show they are positive they are no longer able to stay in the country for any reason.<ref name=\"Cheng 2004\"/>\n\n===Taiwan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Taiwan}}\nAs of March 2016, there are 31,620 reported cases of Taiwanese nationals testing positive for HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/downloadfile.aspx?fid=40CE068DC7A0F111 |title=HIV\u6708\u5831105-03(\u66f4\u65b0) |publisher=Centers for Disease Control, R.O.C (Taiwan) |format=PDF |access-date=2 May 2016}}</ref> Currently, HIV/AIDS patients who are Taiwanese nationals can enjoy free medical care (including HAART therapies), with the state covering the cost. Non-governmental organizations have set up \"AIDS Half-Way Houses\" for homeless patients. The ratio of patients of drug users increases rapidly, which has led the authority to promote a harm reduction program.\n\n==South-East Asia==\nCompared with other regions, notably Africa and the Americas, the national HIV prevalence levels in South-East Asia are very low (0.3% in the adult (15-49) group). However, due to the large populations of many South-East Asian nations, this low national HIV prevalence still means that large numbers of people are living with HIV.\n\nIn [[Southeast Asia]], the HIV epidemic remains largely concentrated in [[injecting drug user]]s, [[men who have sex with men]], [[sex workers]], and clients of sex workers and their immediate sexual partners. Prevention strategies in these populations are, for the most part, inadequate.\n\n===Cambodia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Cambodia}}\n\nBetween 2003 and 2005, the estimated HIV prevalence among Cambodian adults aged 15 to 49 declined from 2.0 percent to 1.6 percent.<ref name=us/>\n\n===East Timor (Timor-Leste)===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in East Timor}}\n\n[[Timor-Leste]] is a low [[HIV]]-prevalence country with less than 0.2 percent of the adult population estimated to be HIV-positive. Forty-three cases of the disease were confirmed in 2007 and are now under treatment, according to the [[Ministry of Health (East Timor)|Ministry of Health]].\n\n===Indonesia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Indonesia}}\n\nUNAIDS has said that HIV/AIDS in [[Indonesia]] is one of Asia's fastest growing epidemics.<ref name='Document ID: 1916388651'>{{cite news | title = U.S., INDONESIA PARTNERSHIP TO FIGHT HIV/AIDS CONTINUES | date = 2009-12-07 | work = US Fed News Service, Including US State News | id = {{ProQuest|471598082}} }}</ref> In 2010, it is expected that 5 million Indonesians will have HIV/AIDS.<ref name=\"proquest\">{{cite news | title = FIVE MILLION HIV/AIDS CASES IN INDONESIA BY 2010 | date = 2009-11-15 | work = Antara | id = {{ProQuest|446446798}} }}</ref> In 2007, Indonesia was ranked 99th in the world by [[List of countries by HIV/AIDS adult prevalence rate|prevalence rate]], but because of low understanding of the symptoms of the disease and high social stigma attached to it, only 5-10% of HIV/AIDS sufferers actually get diagnosed and treated.<ref name=\"proquest\"/>\n\n===Laos===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Laos}}\n\nIn 2005, [[UNAIDS]] estimated that 3,700 people in Lao PDR were living with HIV.<ref name=usaid2>[http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/laos_profile.pdf \"Laos: HIV/AIDS Health Profile\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081115014707/http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/laos_profile.pdf |date=2008-11-15 }}. [[USAID]] (March 2008). {{PD-notice}}</ref> Lao PDR's currently faces a concentrated epidemic with an adult [[HIV]] prevalence of 0.1 percent.\n\n===Malaysia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Malaysia}}\nMalaysia for [[World AIDS Day]] 2008 ''reported'' 82,704 cumulative HIV cases since 1986 as of June 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/mysinchew.html|title=SinChew - MySinchew|website=www.sinchew.com.my}}</ref>\n\n===Myanmar===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Myanmar}}\n\nIn 2005, the estimated adult HIV prevalence rate in Burma was 1.3% (200,000 - 570,000 people), according to [[UNAIDS]], and early indicators show that the epidemic may be waning in the country, although the epidemic continues to expand in parts of the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/myanmar_statistics.html#25 |title=At a glance: Myanmar - statistics |accessdate=9 January 2007 |work=UNICEF }}</ref><ref name=\"UNAIDSasia\">{{cite web |url=http://data.unaids.org/UNA-docs/REPORT_ICAAP_01July05_en.pdf |title=A scaled-up response to AIDS in Asia and the Pacific |accessdate=10 January 2007 |date=1 July 2005 |work=UNAIDS |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223010935/http://data.unaids.org/UNA-docs/report_icaap_01july05_en.pdf |archive-date=23 February 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"06decUNAIDS\">{{cite web |url=http://data.unaids.org/pub/EpiReport/2006/05-Asia_2006_EpiUpdate_eng.pdf |title=Asia |accessdate=9 January 2007 |work=UNAIDS |date=December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070116033206/http://data.unaids.org/pub/EpiReport/2006/05-Asia_2006_EpiUpdate_eng.pdf |archive-date=16 January 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> An estimated 20,000 (range of 11,000 to 35,000) die from HIV/AIDS annually.<ref name=\"myUN2004epid\">{{cite web |url=http://data.unaids.org/Publications/Fact-Sheets01/Myanmar_EN.pdf |title=Myanmar: Epidemiological Fact Sheets\n |accessdate=10 January 2007 |year=2004 |work=UNAIDS}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in the Philippines}}\nThe Philippines has a relatively low incidence of HIV/AIDS. There have been about 2,800 reported cases since 1984, but independent estimates put the number of cases closer to 12,000.<ref>[http://www.youandaids.org/asia%20pacific%20at%20a%20glance/philippines/index.asp HIV and AIDS in Philippines,HIV in Philippines,AIDS in Philippines,social Indicators,social statistics, HIV Estimates,Figures,HIV situation in Philippines<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510215242/http://www.youandaids.org/Asia%20Pacific%20at%20a%20Glance/Philippines/index.asp |date=2008-05-10 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/92012/news/nation/rp-hiv-aids-situation-alarming-undocumented-cases-at-11-000-solon/|title=RP HIV/AIDS situation alarming; undocumented cases at 11,000 - solon|website=GMA News Online}}</ref> The majority (70-75%) of carriers are male, 25\u201339, and the predominant mode of transmission is through sexual intercourse.\n\nAlthough national incidence remains to be relatively low, an independent HIV surveillance study conducted in 2010 by Dr. [[Louie Mar Gangcuangco]] and colleagues from the [[University of the Philippines]]-[[Philippine General Hospital]] showed that out of 406 men having sex with men tested for HIV in Metro Manila, HIV prevalence was at 11.8% (95% confidence interval: 8.7- 15.0).<ref>Gangcuangco, et al. Prevalence and risk factors for HIV infection among men having sex with men in Metro Manila, Philippines. {{cite web|url=http://www.tm.mahidol.ac.th/seameo/2013-44-5/10-5743-12.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-04-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172137/http://www.tm.mahidol.ac.th/seameo/2013-44-5/10-5743-12.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iasociety.org/Abstracts/A200739361.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213252/http://www.iasociety.org/Abstracts/A200739361.aspx |archivedate=2013-10-04 }}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nThe Ministry of Health maintains a confidential registry of HIV positive individuals. The private details of 8,800 foreigners and 5,400 Singaporeans infected with HIV were exposed as a result of improper handling of the data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/government-economy/data-of-14200-people-with-hiv-leaked-online-by-american-fraudstermoh|title=Data of 14,200 people with HIV leaked online by American fraudster:MOH|date=January 28, 2019|website=The Business Times}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Thailand}}\nAround 532,522 Thais were living with HIV/AIDS in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nationmultimedia.com/2008/11/25/national/national_30089295.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126122625/http://nationmultimedia.com/2008/11/25/national/national_30089295.php|url-status=dead|title=More teenaged girls getting HIV infection|archivedate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Vietnam}}\nThe UN believes that there were approximately 290,000 people living with HIV as of 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Countries/viet_nam.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703024928/http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Countries/viet_nam.asp |archivedate=2010-07-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Middle-East and Central Asia==\n===Afghanistan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Afghanistan}}\n\nThe prevalence of [[HIV]] in Afghanistan is 0.04%.<ref name=\"Factbook\"/> According to Afghanistan's National Aids Control Program (NACP), 504 cases of HIV/AIDS were documented in late 2008.<ref>[http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/afghanistan_46717.html Children at risk of contracting HIV/AIDS in Afghanistan]. December 1, 2008.</ref> By the end of 2012, the numbers reached 1,327.<ref name=\"over-1300-hiv-cases-registered-afghanistan\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pajhwok.com/en/2012/12/01/over-1300-hiv-cases-registered-afghanistan |title=Over 1,300 HIV cases registered in Afghanistan |publisher=Pajhwok Afghan News |date=December 1, 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-02}}</ref> As of 2015, as much as 6,900 people are living in Afghanistan with HIV and about 300 have died in from the disease.<ref name=\"Factbook\"/>\n\n===Armenia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Armenia}}\n\n===Azerbaijan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Azerbaijan}}\n\nAdult prevalence rate: less than 0.2% (2012 est.)\nCountry comparison to the world: 106\nPeople living with HIV/AIDS: 10.400 (2012 est.)\nCountry comparison to the world: 102\nDeaths: 65 (2012 est.)\nCountry comparison to the world: 85\n\n===Bahrain===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Bahrain}}\n\nAdult prevalence rate: 0.01% (2016 est.), People with HIV/AIDS: Fewer than 500 (2016 est.), Deaths: Fewer than 100 (2016 est.)\n\n===Iran===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Iran}}\n\n===Iraq===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Iraq}}\n\n===Jordan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Jordan}}\n\nIn 2007, there were an estimated 380,000 people living with HIV/AIDS ([[PLWHA]]) in the region, according to UNAIDS.\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Saudi Arabia}}\n\nIn 2003 the government announced the number of known cases of HIV/AIDS in the country to be 6,700, and over 10,000 in June 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/08/world/middleeast/08saudi.html|title=Saudi Arabia Begins to Face Hidden AIDS Problem|newspaper=New York Times|author=Hassan M. Fattah|date=August 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Turkey===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Turkey}}\n\nAccording to the United Nations HIV / AIDS Theme Group's 2002 HIV / AIDS Situation Analysis report in Turkey, between 7,000 and 14,000 people have been infected with AIDS since the beginning of the pandemic. Figures released by the ([[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Ministry of Health]]) in June 2002 show that a total of 1,429 HIV / AIDS cases had been reported since 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last1=UNICEFF T\u00fcrkiye|title=Evet Deyin: K\u0131\u015f 2003 AIDS'i Anlamak|url=https://www.unicef.org/turkey/sy5/_ah10.html|website=UNICEFF T\u00fcrkiye|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===United Arab Emirates===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in United Arab Emirates}}\n\nOfficial figures show that 540 people were living with HIV/AIDS by the end of 2006, and the number of recorded new cases is about 35 annually.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[AIDS pandemic]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Africa]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Europe]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in North America]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in South America]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060723190810/http://www.unaids.org/epi/2005/doc/EPIupdate2005_pdf_en/epi-update2005_en.pdf AIDS epidemic update 2005] (PDF)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060809220625/http://www.unaids.org/en/Regions_Countries/ Specific country data from UNAIDS]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070114083834/http://www.aidsportal.org/overlay_details.aspx?nex=24 AIDSPortal Asia page] Latest research, case studies and news stories\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101205023545/http://aidsportal.org/overlay_details.aspx?nex=44 AIDSPortal Central Asia page] Latest research, case studies and news stories\n\n{{AIDS}}\n{{Asia topic|HIV/AIDS in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hiv Aids In Asia}}\n[[Category:Asian society]]\n[[Category:Health in Asia]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in Asia| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expert needed|Medicine|date=November 2008}}\n[[Image:People living with HIV AIDS world map.PNG|thumb|400px|People living with HIV/AIDS ([[World Factbook|CIA]]), in absolute numbers for the year of 2008. Large numbers of people live with HIV even in countries with relatively low HIV prevalence levels.]]\n[[File:AIDS and HIV prevalence 2008.svg|thumb|400px|Estimated prevalence in % of HIV among young adults (15\u201349) per country as of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=AIDSinfo|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/dataanalysis/datatools/aidsinfo/|work=UNAIDS|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2008, 4.7 million people in [[Asia]] were living with [[HIV]] according to the [[United Nations]] (UN).<ref name=\"unaids.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Regions/default.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702230305/http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Regions/default.asp |archivedate=2010-07-02 }}</ref> The UN believes that Asia's epidemic peaked in the mid-1990s, and annual HIV incidence has subsequently declined by more than half.<ref name=\"unaids.org\"/> Regionally, the epidemic has remained somewhat stable since 2000.<ref name=\"unaids.org\"/>\n\n==South Asia==\nCompared with other regions, notably Africa and the Americas, the national HIV prevalence levels in South Asia are very low (0.3% in the adult (15-49) group). However, due to the large populations of many South Asian nations, this low national HIV prevalence still means that large numbers of people are living with HIV.\n\nIn South Asia, the HIV epidemic remains largely concentrated in [[injecting drug user]]s, [[men who have sex with men]], [[sex workers]], and clients of sex workers and their immediate sexual partners. Prevention strategies in these populations are, for the most part, inadequate.\n\n===Bangladesh===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Bangladesh}}\nWith less than 0.1 percent of the population estimated to be HIV-positive, Bangladesh is a low HIV-prevalence country. [[UNAIDS]] estimates the number of people living with HIV in the country to be at 11,000 people.<ref name=usaid>[http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/bangladesh_profile.pdf \"Health Profile: Bangladesh\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817052600/http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/bangladesh_profile.pdf |date=17 August 2008 }}. [[United States Agency for International Development]] (March 2008). Accessed 25 August 2008. {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n===Bhutan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Bhutan}}\nIn 2011, there were 246 reported cases of [[HIV]] in [[Bhutan]], representing just over 0.03% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhutanobserver.bt/ministry-health-detected/ |title=The Ministry of Health has Detected\u2026 |publisher=[[Bhutan Observer]] online |date=2011-08-01 |accessdate=2011-11-21}}</ref> However Health Ministry sources indicated actual numbers were estimated at more than 500 by [[UNAIDS]].<ref name=update>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.gov.bt/doph/cdd/update_HIV2010.pdf |format=PDF |title=An Update on Human Immuno Deficiency Virus/Acquired Immuno Deficiency Syndrome (HIV/AIDS) |date=2010-07-01 |accessdate=2011-11-22 |publisher=Bhutan Ministry of Health |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508032703/http://www.health.gov.bt/doph/cdd/update_HIV2010.pdf |archivedate=2012-05-08 }}</ref>\n\n===India===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in India}}\nThe [[National AIDS Control Organisation|NACO]] estimated that 2.11 million people live with HIV/AIDS in India in 2015.<ref name=\"naco\">{{cite web |url=http://nacoonline.org/upload/REPORTS/NACO%20Annual%20Report%202010-11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-15 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020144705/http://nacoonline.org/upload/REPORTS/NACO%20Annual%20Report%202010-11.pdf |archive-date=20 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> India has the third largest number of people with HIV after South Africa and Nigeria.<ref name=\"CIA1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/364rank.html|website=The World Factbook\u2014Central Intelligence Agency|title=Country comparison: people living with HIV/AIDS|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Despite being home to the world's third-largest population suffering from HIV/AIDS (as of 2018, with South Africa and Nigeria having more),<ref name=\"CIA1\"/> the AIDS prevalence rate in India is lower than in many other countries. In 2016, India's AIDS prevalence rate stood at approximately 0.30%\u2014the 80th highest in the world.<ref name=\"CIA2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2155rank.html|website=The World Factbook\u2014Central Intelligence Agency|title=Country comparison AIDS/HIV prevalence|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Nepal}}\n[[UNAIDS]] estimates from 2007 indicate that approximately 75,000 people in Nepal are HIV-positive, including all age groups. The Government of Nepal's National Center for AIDS & STD Control (NCASC) estimated that number to be closer to 70,000 in December 2007. In a study from 2014, an overall national HIV prevalence was 0.20% (adult male 0.28%, adult female 0.13%). According to UNAIDS, by the end of 2015, the number of people living with [[HIV]] was 39,000 [34,000 - 46,000]<ref name=usaid/> NCASC (2010) reports that estimated number of HIV infections by risk groups is 59,984.<ref>[http://www.ncasc.gov.np/]</ref><ref name=UNAIDS/>\n\n===Pakistan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Pakistan}}\nThe National AIDS Program's latest figures show that by the mid of first decade in new millennium, the number of HIV cases have increased to approximately 0,102 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nacp.gov.pk/|title=National AIDS Control Programme|website=www.nacp.gov.pk}}</ref> This number was estimated little over 4,000, as the HIV cases reported since 1986. The UN and government estimated the number of HIV/AIDS cases around 97,000 ranging from a lowest estimate of 46,000 to a highest estimate of 210,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aids.gov.br/data/documents/storedDocuments/%7BB8EF5DAF-23AE-4891-AD36-1903553A3174%7D/%7BFD4B5F2E-FB97-4749-BDA2-1C2360F59870%7D/2007_epiupdate_en.pdf |title=UNAIDS Epidemic update 2007 |accessdate=June 14, 2008 |archive-date=October 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002144331/http://www.aids.gov.br/data/documents/storedDocuments/%7BB8EF5DAF-23AE-4891-AD36-1903553A3174%7D/%7BFD4B5F2E-FB97-4749-BDA2-1C2360F59870%7D/2007_epiupdate_en.pdf |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> More realistic estimates that are based on actual [[surveillance]] figures, however, suggest that this number may be closer to 40,000\u201345,000. The overall [[prevalence]] of HIV infection in adults aged 15 to 49 is 0.1%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacp.gov.pk/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/pakistan_2008_country_progress_report_en.pdf |title=Pakistan UNGASS Report 2007 |accessdate=June 14, 2008 |archive-date=October 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002144338/http://www.nacp.gov.pk/wp-content/uploads/2008/02/pakistan_2008_country_progress_report_en.pdf |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> (0.05% if one accepts the lower estimates).\n\n===Sri Lanka===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Sri Lanka}}\n\n==East Asia==\nCompared with other regions, notably Africa and the Americas, the national HIV prevalence levels in [[East Asia]] are very low (0.1% in the adult (15-49) group). However, due to the large populations of many East Asian nations, this low national HIV prevalence still means that large numbers of people are living with HIV.\n\n===China===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in the People's Republic of China}}\n[[File:ChinaHIVAIDSmap.svg|thumb|Cases of HIV in Chinese provinces by December 2005; high number of cases near Eastern and Western borders.]]\nMuch of the current spread of HIV in the [[People's Republic of China]] is through intravenous [[drug abuse]] and [[paid sex]]. <!-- Citation needed --> In the rural areas, especially in [[Henan]] province, large numbers of farmers participated in contaminated [[blood transfusion]]s; estimates of those infected are in the tens of thousands.\n\n===Japan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Japan}}\n[http://api-net.jfap.or.jp/mhw/survey/mhw_survey.htm Official figures] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20081213003434/http://www.japanetwork.org/aidsnews/stats/06jul-sep.html English]) for July\u2013October 2006 showed that just over half of domestic HIV/AIDS cases were among [[homosexuality|homosexual men]], with the remainder transmitted through heterosexual intercourse, [[drug abuse]], [[perinatal|in the womb]] or via unknown means. As of 2015, there have been a total of 17,909 HIV and 8,086 AIDS cases reported in Japan since 1985. [https://www.niid.go.jp/niid/en/iasr-vol33-e/865-iasr/6775-439te.html IASR 37(9)\u30012016\u3010TOPIC\u3011HIV/AIDS in Japan, 2015]\n\n===North Korea===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in North Korea}}\nAccording to UNAIDS, less than 0.2% of [[North Korea]]'s adult population has HIV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.unaids.org/pub/Report/2006/2006_gr_en.pdf#342 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208200442/http://data.unaids.org/pub/Report/2006/2006_gr_en.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-12-08 |title=2006 Report on the global AIDS epidemic : A UNAIDS 10th anniversary special edition |date=2006 |publisher=UNAIDS |page=343 |access-date=7 December 2015 }}</ref> WHO estimates that North Korea has less than 100 people with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.searo.who.int/PDS_DOCS/B0367.pdf |title=Young People and HIV/AIDS : Fact Sheet : DPR Korea |date=20 November 2006 |publisher=Regional Office for South East Asia, World Health Organization |access-date=7 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208142659/http://apps.searo.who.int/PDS_DOCS/B0367.pdf |archivedate=8 December 2015 }}</ref> Officially, the country maintains that it is completely free of AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web | title = North Korea fights AIDS | publisher= ABC Radio National | last=O'Byrne|first=Tom| date = 2 December 2001 | accessdate = 2015-12-08 | url = http://www.abc.net.au/correspondents/s430901.htm }}</ref>\n\n===South Korea===\nSouth Korea cumulative ''reported'' cases of HIV surpassed 6,000, and 797 reported in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kaisernetwork.org/daily_reports/rep_index.cfm?DR_ID=56908|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090623135428/http://www.kaisernetwork.org/daily_reports/rep_index.cfm?DR_ID=56908|url-status=dead|title=KaiserNetwork: Korea cases|archivedate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention'', the prevalence of HIV in South Korea is rising. The first case of HIV was in 1985 <ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/29/6/1524/307521 |jstor=4482066|title=Spectrum of Opportunistic Infections and Malignancies in Patients with Human Immunodeficiency Virus Infection in South Korea|last=Oh|first=Myoung-don|date=December 1999}}</ref> In 2000, the number of people diagnosed with HIV was 219, and has risen to 797 diagnoses in 2008.<ref name=\"bmc\">{{Cite web|url=https://bmcpublichealth.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1471-2458-10-411|title=Increasing Late Diagnosis in Hiv Infection in South Korea: 2000-2007|last=Lee|first=Jin-Hee|date=December 2009|website=BIO MED CENTRAL|accessdate=}}</ref> Males were found to have a much higher infection rate.<ref name=\"bmc\"/> In order to prevent Korean women from contracting HIV, HIV positive males should be detected early on.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/40542225?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents |jstor=40542225|title=Epidemiological Characteristics of HIV-Infected Women in the Republic of Korea: A Low HIV Prevalence Country|last=Lee|first=Jin-Hee|date=September 2009}}</ref> The most common transmission mode in South Korea is through heterosexual sexual contacts, because homosexuality is uncommon and socially unacceptable.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nDue to the lower prevalence of HIV in South Korea, the Korean media has represented HIV as a disease brought to Korea by foreigners from other countries.<ref name=\"Cheng 2004\">{{cite web |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4065354?seq=1 |jstor=4065354|title=Interrogating the Absence of HIV/AIDS Interventions for Migrant Sex Workers in South Korea|last=Cheng|first=Sealing|date=2004}}</ref> The Korean government has created policies to incorporate these ideas. Any foreigners who plan to stay in South Korea must test for HIV, and if results show they are positive they are no longer able to stay in the country for any reason.<ref name=\"Cheng 2004\"/>\n\n===Taiwan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Taiwan}}\nAs of March 2016, there are 31,620 reported cases of Taiwanese nationals testing positive for HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov.tw/downloadfile.aspx?fid=40CE068DC7A0F111 |title=HIV\u6708\u5831105-03(\u66f4\u65b0) |publisher=Centers for Disease Control, R.O.C (Taiwan) |format=PDF |access-date=2 May 2016}}</ref> Currently HIV/AIDS patients who are Taiwanese nationals can enjoy free medical care (including HAART therapies), with the state covering the cost. Non-governmental organizations have set up \"AIDS Half-Way Houses\" for homeless patients. The ratio of patients of drug users increases rapidly, which has led the authority to promote a harm reduction program.\n\n==South-East Asia==\nCompared with other regions, notably Africa and the Americas, the national HIV prevalence levels in South-East Asia are very low (0.3% in the adult (15-49) group). However, due to the large populations of many South-East Asian nations, this low national HIV prevalence still means that large numbers of people are living with HIV.\n\nIn [[Southeast Asia]], the HIV epidemic remains largely concentrated in [[injecting drug user]]s, [[men who have sex with men]], [[sex workers]], and clients of sex workers and their immediate sexual partners. Prevention strategies in these populations are, for the most part, inadequate.\n\n===Cambodia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Cambodia}}\n\nBetween 2003 and 2005, the estimated HIV prevalence among Cambodian adults aged 15 to 49 declined from 2.0 percent to 1.6 percent.<ref name=us/>\n\n===East Timor (Timor-Leste)===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in East Timor}}\n\n[[Timor-Leste]] is a low [[HIV]]-prevalence country with less than 0.2 percent of the adult population estimated to be HIV-positive. Forty-three cases of the disease were confirmed in 2007 and are now under treatment, according to the [[Ministry of Health (East Timor)|Ministry of Health]].\n\n===Indonesia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Indonesia}}\n\nUNAIDS has said that HIV/AIDS in [[Indonesia]] is one of Asia's fastest growing epidemics.<ref name='Document ID: 1916388651'>{{cite news | title = U.S., INDONESIA PARTNERSHIP TO FIGHT HIV/AIDS CONTINUES | date = 2009-12-07 | work = US Fed News Service, Including US State News | id = {{ProQuest|471598082}} }}</ref> In 2010, it is expected that 5 million Indonesians will have HIV/AIDS.<ref name=\"proquest\">{{cite news | title = FIVE MILLION HIV/AIDS CASES IN INDONESIA BY 2010 | date = 2009-11-15 | work = Antara | id = {{ProQuest|446446798}} }}</ref> In 2007, Indonesia was ranked 99th in the world by [[List of countries by HIV/AIDS adult prevalence rate|prevalence rate]], but because of low understanding of the symptoms of the disease and high social stigma attached to it, only 5-10% of HIV/AIDS sufferers actually get diagnosed and treated.<ref name=\"proquest\"/>\n\n===Laos===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Laos}}\n\nIn 2005, [[UNAIDS]] estimated that 3,700 people in Lao PDR were living with HIV.<ref name=usaid2>[http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/laos_profile.pdf \"Laos: HIV/AIDS Health Profile\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081115014707/http://www.usaid.gov/our_work/global_health/aids/Countries/ane/laos_profile.pdf |date=2008-11-15 }}. [[USAID]] (March 2008). {{PD-notice}}</ref> Lao PDR's currently faces a concentrated epidemic with an adult [[HIV]] prevalence of 0.1 percent.\n\n===Malaysia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Malaysia}}\nMalaysia for [[World AIDS Day]] 2008 ''reported'' 82,704 cumulative HIV cases since 1986 as of June 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/mysinchew.html|title=SinChew - MySinchew|website=www.sinchew.com.my}}</ref>\n\n===Myanmar===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Myanmar}}\n\nIn 2005, the estimated adult HIV prevalence rate in Burma was 1.3% (200,000 - 570,000 people), according to [[UNAIDS]], and early indicators show that the epidemic may be waning in the country, although the epidemic continues to expand in parts of the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/myanmar_statistics.html#25 |title=At a glance: Myanmar - statistics |accessdate=9 January 2007 |work=UNICEF }}</ref><ref name=\"UNAIDSasia\">{{cite web |url=http://data.unaids.org/UNA-docs/REPORT_ICAAP_01July05_en.pdf |title=A scaled-up response to AIDS in Asia and the Pacific |accessdate=10 January 2007 |date=1 July 2005 |work=UNAIDS |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223010935/http://data.unaids.org/UNA-docs/report_icaap_01july05_en.pdf |archive-date=23 February 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"06decUNAIDS\">{{cite web |url=http://data.unaids.org/pub/EpiReport/2006/05-Asia_2006_EpiUpdate_eng.pdf |title=Asia |accessdate=9 January 2007 |work=UNAIDS |date=December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070116033206/http://data.unaids.org/pub/EpiReport/2006/05-Asia_2006_EpiUpdate_eng.pdf |archive-date=16 January 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> An estimated 20,000 (range of 11,000 to 35,000) die from HIV/AIDS annually.<ref name=\"myUN2004epid\">{{cite web |url=http://data.unaids.org/Publications/Fact-Sheets01/Myanmar_EN.pdf |title=Myanmar: Epidemiological Fact Sheets\n |accessdate=10 January 2007 |year=2004 |work=UNAIDS}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in the Philippines}}\nThe Philippines has a relatively low incidence of HIV/AIDS. There have been about 2,800 reported cases since 1984, but independent estimates put the number of cases closer to 12,000.<ref>[http://www.youandaids.org/asia%20pacific%20at%20a%20glance/philippines/index.asp HIV and AIDS in Philippines,HIV in Philippines,AIDS in Philippines,social Indicators,social statistics, HIV Estimates,Figures,HIV situation in Philippines<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510215242/http://www.youandaids.org/Asia%20Pacific%20at%20a%20Glance/Philippines/index.asp |date=2008-05-10 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/92012/news/nation/rp-hiv-aids-situation-alarming-undocumented-cases-at-11-000-solon/|title=RP HIV/AIDS situation alarming; undocumented cases at 11,000 - solon|website=GMA News Online}}</ref> The majority (70-75%) of carriers are male, 25\u201339, and the predominant mode of transmission is through sexual intercourse.\n\nAlthough national incidence remains to be relatively low, an independent HIV surveillance study conducted in 2010 by Dr. [[Louie Mar Gangcuangco]] and colleagues from the [[University of the Philippines]]-[[Philippine General Hospital]] showed that out of 406 men having sex with men tested for HIV in Metro Manila, HIV prevalence was at 11.8% (95% confidence interval: 8.7- 15.0).<ref>Gangcuangco, et al. Prevalence and risk factors for HIV infection among men having sex with men in Metro Manila, Philippines. {{cite web|url=http://www.tm.mahidol.ac.th/seameo/2013-44-5/10-5743-12.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-04-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172137/http://www.tm.mahidol.ac.th/seameo/2013-44-5/10-5743-12.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iasociety.org/Abstracts/A200739361.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213252/http://www.iasociety.org/Abstracts/A200739361.aspx |archivedate=2013-10-04 }}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nThe Ministry of Health maintains a confidential registry of HIV positive individuals. The private details of 8,800 foreigners and 5,400 Singaporeans infected with HIV were exposed as a result of improper handling of the data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/government-economy/data-of-14200-people-with-hiv-leaked-online-by-american-fraudstermoh|title=Data of 14,200 people with HIV leaked online by American fraudster:MOH|date=January 28, 2019|website=The Business Times}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Thailand}}\nAround 532,522 Thais were living with HIV/AIDS in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nationmultimedia.com/2008/11/25/national/national_30089295.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126122625/http://nationmultimedia.com/2008/11/25/national/national_30089295.php|url-status=dead|title=More teenaged girls getting HIV infection|archivedate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Vietnam}}\nThe UN believes that there were approximately 290,000 people living with HIV as of 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Countries/viet_nam.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703024928/http://www.unaids.org/en/CountryResponses/Countries/viet_nam.asp |archivedate=2010-07-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Middle-East and Central Asia==\n===Afghanistan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Afghanistan}}\n\nThe prevalence of [[HIV]] in Afghanistan is 0.04%.<ref name=\"Factbook\"/> According to Afghanistan's National Aids Control Program (NACP), 504 cases of HIV/AIDS were documented in late 2008.<ref>[http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/afghanistan_46717.html Children at risk of contracting HIV/AIDS in Afghanistan]. December 1, 2008.</ref> By the end of 2012, the numbers reached 1,327.<ref name=\"over-1300-hiv-cases-registered-afghanistan\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pajhwok.com/en/2012/12/01/over-1300-hiv-cases-registered-afghanistan |title=Over 1,300 HIV cases registered in Afghanistan |publisher=Pajhwok Afghan News |date=December 1, 2012 |accessdate=2012-12-02}}</ref> As of 2015, as much as 6,900 people are living in Afghanistan with HIV and about 300 have died in from the disease.<ref name=\"Factbook\"/>\n\n===Armenia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Armenia}}\n\n===Azerbaijan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Azerbaijan}}\n\nAdult prevalence rate: less than 0.2% (2012 est.)\nCountry comparison to the world: 106\nPeople living with HIV/AIDS: 10.400 (2012 est.)\nCountry comparison to the world: 102\nDeaths: 65 (2012 est.)\nCountry comparison to the world: 85\n\n===Bahrain===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Bahrain}}\n\nAdult prevalence rate: 0.01% (2016 est.), People with HIV/AIDS: Fewer than 500 (2016 est.), Deaths: Fewer than 100 (2016 est.)\n\n===Iran===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Iran}}\n\n===Iraq===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Iraq}}\n\n===Jordan===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Jordan}}\n\nIn 2007, there were an estimated 380,000 people living with HIV/AIDS ([[PLWHA]]) in the region, according to UNAIDS.\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Saudi Arabia}}\n\nIn 2003 the government announced the number of known cases of HIV/AIDS in the country to be 6,700, and over 10,000 in June 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/08/world/middleeast/08saudi.html|title=Saudi Arabia Begins to Face Hidden AIDS Problem|newspaper=New York Times|author=Hassan M. Fattah|date=August 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Turkey===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in Turkey}}\n\nAccording to the United Nations HIV / AIDS Theme Group's 2002 HIV / AIDS Situation Analysis report in Turkey, between 7,000 and 14,000 people have been infected with AIDS since the beginning of the pandemic. Figures released by the ([[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Ministry of Health]]) in June 2002 show that a total of 1,429 HIV / AIDS cases had been reported since 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last1=UNICEFF T\u00fcrkiye|title=Evet Deyin: K\u0131\u015f 2003 AIDS'i Anlamak|url=https://www.unicef.org/turkey/sy5/_ah10.html|website=UNICEFF T\u00fcrkiye|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===United Arab Emirates===\n{{Main|HIV/AIDS in United Arab Emirates}}\n\nOfficial figures show that 540 people were living with HIV/AIDS by the end of 2006, and the number of recorded new cases is about 35 annually.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[AIDS pandemic]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Africa]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Europe]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in North America]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in South America]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060723190810/http://www.unaids.org/epi/2005/doc/EPIupdate2005_pdf_en/epi-update2005_en.pdf AIDS epidemic update 2005] (PDF)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060809220625/http://www.unaids.org/en/Regions_Countries/ Specific country data from UNAIDS]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070114083834/http://www.aidsportal.org/overlay_details.aspx?nex=24 AIDSPortal Asia page] Latest research, case studies and news stories\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101205023545/http://aidsportal.org/overlay_details.aspx?nex=44 AIDSPortal Central Asia page] Latest research, case studies and news stories\n\n{{AIDS}}\n{{Asia topic|HIV/AIDS in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hiv Aids In Asia}}\n[[Category:Asian society]]\n[[Category:Health in Asia]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in Asia| ]]\n", "name_user": "Llunnaz", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIV/AIDS_in_Asia"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kuwait", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Kuwait}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n \n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kuwait\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Kuwait]]\n| first_case      = [[Kuwait City]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 February 2020\n| origin          = [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 176\n| deaths          = 3\n| confirmed_cases = 1,355<ref name=\"COVID 19 Updates\">{{cite web |title=COVID 19 Updates |url=https://corona.e.gov.kw/En/ |website=e-govkw}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = 9<ref name=\"COVID 19 Updates\">{{cite web |title=COVID 19 Updates |url=https://corona.e.gov.kw/En/ |website=e-govkw}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = 1,355\n| website         = [https://corona.e.gov.kw/En/ corona.e.gov.kw]\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Kuwait]] was announced on 24 February 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is a coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== February 2020 ===\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Kuwait medical cases chart}}\nOn 24 February, Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced that there were 3 cases detected coming from [[Iran]] that carry [[coronavirus disease 2019]]. The first person was a [[Kuwait]] I national, 53 years old, while the second was a [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] national, 61 years old, and the third was a person from the [[Statelessness|stateless]] community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/bahrain/bahrain-and-kuwait-confirm-first-cases-of-coronavirus-disease-1.1582526120524|title=The Kuwaiti health ministry of health confirms first 3 COVID-19 cases|date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\nLater, 2 cases were announced on that same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2865550&language=en|title=The Kuwaiti health ministry of health confirms 2 more COVID-19 cases|date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\nAt the end of 24 February, there were 5 confirmed cases in Kuwait.\n\nOn 25 February, Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced that there were 4 new cases coming from [[Iran]] with [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.kuwaittimes.net/website/kuwait-confirms-4-coronavirus-cases-total-number-jumps-to-9/|title=The Kuwaiti health ministry of health confirms 4 more COVID-19 cases|date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\nAt the end of 25 February, there were 9 confirmed cases in Kuwait.\n\nOn 26 February, Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced that 16 news cases have been reported with the novel coronavirus, associated with travel to Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/kuwait-coronavirus-cases-jump-to-25-on-wednesday-1.1582702570951|title=The Kuwaiti health ministry of health confirms 16 more COVID-19 cases|date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\nAt the end of 26 February, there were 25 confirmed cases in Kuwait.\n\nOn 27 February, Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced new 18 cases associated with travel to Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/health/kuwaits-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-45/1748351|title=The Kuwaiti health ministry of health confirms 19 more COVID-19 cases|date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\nAt the end of 27 February, there were 43 confirmed cases in Kuwait.\n\nOn 28 February, Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced new 2 cases associated with travel to Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/health/kuwaits-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-45/1748351|title=The Kuwaiti health ministry of health confirms 2 more COVID-19 cases|date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\nAt the end of 28 February, there were 45 confirmed cases in Kuwait.\n\nOn 29 February, the Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced that there were no new cases.\nAt the end of February, there were 45 confirmed cases in Kuwait.\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n\nOn 11 March, Kuwaiti Directorate General of Civil Aviation has suspended all travel, except cargo flights, to and from Kuwait starting from 13 March, effectively locking down the nation until further notice.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 12 March, Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced 8 new cases, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 80.\n\nOn 13 March, the Kuwaiti Ministry of Health announced 20 new cases, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 100. The Public Authority Of Agriculture Affairs And Fish Resources closed public parks, and the ministry of Awqaf and Islamic Affairs announced just before noon prayers for Muslims to pray from home and not to attend Friday prayers during a pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prayers restricted across the Middle East amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/prayers-restricted-middle-east-coronavirus-fears-200313113106897.html |agency=Al-Jazeera |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Etheridge |first1=Jamie |title=Kuwait extends lockdown by closing mosques, parks; no curfew as cases surge to 100 |url=https://news.kuwaittimes.net/website/kuwait-extends-lockdown-by-closing-mosques-parks-no-curfew-as-cases-surge-to-100/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=Kuwait Times |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the ministry of health announced 11 new cases for a total of 123.<ref name=\"curfew, ex-pat deportation\" />\n\nOn 18 March, the Ministry of Health announced 6 new cases for a total of 148. More than 14,000 swipe tests had been conducted by this point.<ref>{{cite news |title=Six new coronavirus cases in Kuwait, total infections at 148 |url=https://news.kuwaittimes.net/website/six-new-coronavirus-cases-in-kuwait-total-infections-at-148/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=news.kuwaittimes.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the Ministry of Health announced 17 new cases for a total for 176.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2880435|title=Kuwait: 17 new coronavirus cases, total at 176|date=21 March 2020|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April, the Ministry of Health announced 28 new cases for a total of 317 cases.\n\nOn 2 April, the Ministry of Health announced 25 new cases for a total of 342 cases.\n\nOn 3 April, the Ministry of Health announced 75 new cases for a total of 417 cases. \n\nOn 4 April, an Indian national, 46 years old died from the virus. The country reported its first death from the virus.<ref name=\"firstdeath\">{{cite news |title=Kuwait reports first death from coronavirus outbreak: state news agency |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-kuwait/kuwait-reports-first-death-from-coronavirus-outbreak-state-news-agency-idUSKBN21M0DK |accessdate=4 April 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Ministry of Health announced 62 new cases for a total of 455 cases.\n\nOn 5 April, the Ministry of Health announced 77 new cases for a total of 556 cases.\n\nOn 6 April, the Ministry of Health announced 109 new cases for a total of 665 cases and a recovery of 4.\n\nOn 7 April, the Ministry of Health announced 78 new cases for a total of 743 cases and a recovery of 2.\n\nOn 8 April, the Ministry of Health announced 112 new cases for a total of 855 cases and a recovery of 6.\n\nOn 9 April, the Ministry of Health announced 55 new cases for a total of 910 cases.\n\nOn 10 April, the Ministry of Health announced 83 new cases for a total of 993 cases.\n\nOn 11 April, the Ministry of Health announced 161 new cases for a total of 1,154 cases in Kuwait.\n\nOn 12 April, the Ministry of Health announced 80 new cases for a total of 1,234 cases in Kuwait.\n\nOn 13 April, the Ministry of Health announced 66 new cases for a total of 1,300 cases and a recovery of 8. Kuwait reported its 2nd death due to the virus. A Kuwaiti citizen aged 50 years old died from the virus. He was in ICU and was receiving medical attention for the last 21 days.\n\nOn 14 April 2020, the Ministry of Health  announced 55 new cases for a total of 1,355 cases and a recovery of 21. Today, Kuwait reported its 3rd death in the country due to the virus.\n\n==Response==\n\nAll commercial flights were suspended on 13 March, with an exception for cargo flights. A public holiday was declared from 12 to 26 March, with work to resume on 29 March. Some shops were closed, and restrictions were placed on restaurants.<ref name=\"What we know so far 11\"/> Authorities asked people to stay home for Friday prayers, saying \"The doors of the mosques will stay closed\" and citing a [[fatwa]] allowing people not to attend prayers in mosques.<ref name=\"Gulf States Cancel Events\">{{cite news |title=Gulf States Cancel Events, Kuwait Shuts Mosques Over Coronavirus |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-03-13/kuwait-asks-muslims-to-pray-at-home-to-halt-coronavirus-spread |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Classes were suspended from 1 to 12 March, which was extended to 29 March,<ref name=\"What we know so far 11\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus in Kuwait: What we know so far  |url=https://news.kuwaittimes.net/website/coronavirus-in-kuwait-what-we-know-so-far-11/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=news.kuwaittimes.net}}</ref> and later to 4 August.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kuwait closes schools till August |url=https://news.kuwaittimes.net/website/kuwait-extends-school-vacation-till-august-4/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=news.kuwaittimes.net}}</ref>\n\nVisas were partially suspended, and quarantines required for all arrivals from certain high-risk countries. Arrivals at [[Kuwait International Airport]] from other countries were required to self-quarantine for 14 days.<ref name=\"What we know so far 11\"/> The borders with [[Iraq]] and [[Saudi Arabia]] were closed.<ref name=\"Kuwait Gears Up\">{{cite news |title=Kuwait Gears Up for Coronavirus Lockdown, Minister Urges Calm |url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/12/world/middleeast/12reuters-health-coronavirus-kuwait.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFood exports were banned, and [[Trade Minister]] [[Khalid Al Roudan]] reassured people that the country had enough food and shipping was continuing.<ref name=\"Kuwait Gears Up\"/>\n\nOn 15 March, Interior Minister [[Anas Al-Saleh]] told people to follow the measures imposed by the government and stop going out unnecessarily. He warned that curfews or deportations could be used if people failed to comply.<ref name=\"curfew, ex-pat deportation\">{{cite news |title=Interior minister warns of curfew, ex-pat deportation |url=https://news.kuwaittimes.net/website/interior-minister-warns-of-curfew-expat-deportation/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=news.kuwaittimes.net}}</ref>\n\n== Impacts ==\n\n=== Academic Studies ===\n\nThe suspension of the schools was needed to avoid the spread of the coronavirus in children, teenagers and younger people (Kindergarten up to university level). The high school graduates (Grade 12 seniors) were the most affected by the suspension since graduation is usually in May\u2013June yearly. However, the academic year will be resumed in August 2020, which means their graduation will be delayed. Furthermore, getting sponsored scholarships to study in universities, will also be delayed due to the same reasons.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentences|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Economics ===\n\nThe strategic planning and surplus for food and supplies are for six months. All supermarkets and grocery stores have all usual products as before the border closure or the imposed partial curfew.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nHowever, small businesses are the most affected since they are losing a lot of money, and yet, have to pay rent or salaries to their workers. The government have promised packages and solutions to ensure these businesses are compensated for these unfortunate circumstances with the partial lockdown.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== People ===\n\nAll the Kuwaitis and non-Kuwaitis are appreciative of the efforts that were put in place to ensure the control of the coronavirus. However, there is a sense of rush in buying supplies in non-curfew hours (6 a.m to 5 p.m), even though the Kuwaiti government have reiterated that goods and supplies are for six months.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe partial lockdown, staying at home and social distancing has caused boredom for the majority, as cinemas, malls, department stores, and entertainment places are shut and closed. Normal things like exercising in the gym, or eating outside people homes, suddenly unacceptable, shut and closed due to the coronavirus.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons-inline|Category:COVID-19 pandemic in Kuwait|COVID-19 pandemic in Kuwait}}\n* [https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases] and [https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 historical data] by [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Kuwait]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Kuwait]]\n[[Category:2020 in Kuwait]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Kuwait]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Kuwait}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n \n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kuwait\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Kuwait]]\n| first_case      = [[Kuwait City]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 February 2020\n| origin          = [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 176\n| deaths          = 3\n| confirmed_cases = 1,355<ref name=\"COVID 19 Updates\">{{cite web |title=COVID 19 Updates |url=https://corona.e.gov.kw/En/ |website=e-govkw}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = 8<ref name=\"COVID 19 Updates\">{{cite web |title=COVID 19 Updates |url=https://corona.e.gov.kw/En/ |website=e-govkw}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = 1,355\n| website         = [https://corona.e.gov.kw/En/ corona.e.gov.kw]\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Kuwait]] was announced on 24 February 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is a coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |wor